<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Nielsens 1stLd-Writethru a0723 05-17 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0723,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perry Mason Solves Nielsens for NBC</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `NBC won ...' to CORRECT NBC's season-to-date
rating to 15.8, sted 5.8</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's perennial sweeps favorite, Perry Mason,
topped the Nielsen ratings last week despite a lot of competition
from specials, movies and miniseries.
   ``Perry Mason: The Case of the Lady in the Lake'' was the No.
1-rated prime-time network show of the week with a rating of 22.6
and a 35 share. NBC said it was the network's best Sunday movie
rating all season.
   May is one of four months during the year when local stations'
ratings are measured for use in negotiating advertising rates, so
the networks put on a lot of special programming to draw viewers to
their affiliates.
   Other sweeps specials that landed in the top 10 were the
theatrical film ``Beverly Hills Cop'' and Barbara Walters' special,
both on ABC, and the concluding episodes of the two-parters
``Something Is Out There'' on NBC and ``The Bourne Identity'' on
ABC.
   CBS was shut out of the top 10, but came in 11th with the
season-ending cliffhanger of ``Knots Landing.'' Part one of its big
miniseries of the week, ``Beryl Markham: A Shadow on the Sun,''
fared poorly against ``Perry Mason,'' though, and came in 43rd with
a rating of 10.4.
   The top 10-rated shows, as ranked by the A.C. Nielsen Co. were:
``Perry Mason'' NBC, ``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``Cheers'' NBC,
``Beverly Hills Cop'' ABC, ``Barbara Walters Special'' ABC, ``Night
Court'' NBC, ``Golden Girls'' NBC, ``Something Is Out There, Part
2'' NBC, ``The Bourne Identity, Part 2'' ABC and ``Who's the
Boss?'' ABC.
   NBC won the week ending May 15 with an average, prime-time
rating of 14.7 and a 26 share. ABC was second with a 12.8 and 22
share. CBS had an 11.4 average rating and 20 share. NBC's
season-to-date average is 15.8. ABC has 13.5 and CBS 13.3.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   Though it has been tops in prime time virtually the entire
season, NBC's ``Nightly News'' has spent most of the season in
third place since Nielsen installed its new people-meter rating
system last fall. For the week ending Friday the 13th, ABC's
``World News Tonight'' was first with a rating of 9.4 and a 20
share. The ``CBS Evening News'' was second with 9.1 and 20. ``NBC
Nightly News'' continued to trail with an 8.0 and 17 share.
   ABC, in first place for the third week in a row, said so far
this quarter, its ``World News'' has increased its share of the
audience by 11 percent compared to the second quarter of 1987.
Meanwhile, said ABC, CBS is down 9 percent in share, and NBC has
dropped 18 percent.
   The lowest-rated prime-time shows of the week were: ``I Married
Dora,'' ``Tour of Duty,'' ``Uncommon Valor,'' ``West 57th,'' ``High
Mountain Rangers,'' ``48 Hours,'' ``Aaron's Way,'' ``Houston
Knights,'' ``Ohara'' and ``Supercarrier.''
</TEXT>
