<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Prince     05-17 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Prince,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Album Showing Prince In The Buff Selling Well</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Controversy over the cover of rock star
Prince's new album, ``Lovesexy,'' on which the singer appears nude
but with his legs strategically placed, doesn't appear to have hurt
sales.
   The album has sold at least 1.6 million copies since its May 10
release even though some record outlets are refusing to sell it,
Prince publicist Robyn Riggs said Monday.
   ``Obviously, it doesn't seem to be hurting,'' she said of the
controversy.
   The album sold 800,000 copies in the first week in the United
States and 800,000 in Great Britain in the first four days, she
said. Sales of the album's first single, ``Alphabet St.,'' were at
least 700,000 in the United States, she said.
   Prince, who lives in suburban Chanhassen, will begin a two-month
tour of Europe on July 8, with a concert in Paris, Ms. Riggs said.
He may follow with a U.S. tour in the fall, she said.
</TEXT>
