<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     05-17 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Friday The 13th' Carves Out First Place</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Friday The 13th'' was a lucky day for the six
sequel in the blood-letting movie series as it earned $8.2 million
and first place at the box office last weekend.
   ``Friday the 13th Part VII _ The New Blood,'' opened on Friday
the 13th on nearly 1,800 screens, making impressive earnings during
a normally lackluster time of year when students attend proms and
get ready for graduation.
   ``This is normally a very bad week,'' said John Krier of
Exhibitor Relations Co. ``But Jason still lives,'' he said,
referring to the much-resurrected hockey-masked killer of the
``Friday the 13th'' movies.
   Earnings fell sharply after the No.1 spot, and there were no
other new movies in the Top 10.
   ``Colors,'' the gang movie starring Sean Penn and Robert Duvall,
fell to second place, earning $3.3 million, followed by the ghost
movie ``Beetlejuice,'' which sold $3 million in tickets.
   ``Shakedown,'' about an undercover cop exposing corrupt
colleagues, earned $2 million for fourth place, followed by the
dance-romance movie ``Salsa'' with $1.8 million.
   ``Biloxi Blues'' was in sixth place with $1.2 million and
``Above The Law'' was seventh with $1.1 million.
   Rounding out the Top 10 was ``Moonstruck,'' $1.09 million; ``The
Last Emperor,'' $1.05 million; and ``Bloodsport,'' $911,000.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release, and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Friday the 13th Part VII _ The New Blood,'' Paramount, $8.2
million, 1,796 screens, $4,590 per screen, $8.2 million, one week,
n-a.
   2. ``Colors,'' Orion, $3.3 million, 1,387 screens, $2,439 per
screen, $30 million, five weeks, $12 million.
   3. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $3 million, 1,533 screens,
$1,994 per screen, $55.1 million, seven weeks, $20 million.
   4. ``Shakedown,'' Universal, $2 million, 1,522 screens, $1,330
per screen, $6.1 million, two weeks, n-a.
   5. ``Salsa,'' Cannon, $1.8 million, 1,068 screens, $1,722 per
screen, $5.1 million, two weeks, n-a.
   6. ``Biloxi Blues,'' Universal, $1.2 million, 910 screens,
