<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0848 05-17 0899</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0848,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Suggests Meese, Noriega Hurting Him in Polls</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf pvs to include Kerry comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush suggested on
Tuesday that controversies swirling around the Reagan
administration are hurting him in presidential polls, but he said
he wasn't worried about it.
   On one of those matters, the Iran-Contra affair, Bush struck
back hard, accusing Democrats of leaking ``scurrilous allegations''
against him that aren't true.
   ``You've had endless investigations _ each one with a lot of
Democrats ...trying to find something wrong and they haven't,''
Bush told reporters in Fresno. ``The American people are fair. They
know when someone is telling the truth.''
   Bush singled out Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., saying Kerry's
subcommittee is the source of the latest allegation to link Bush
aides to a Contra arms network involving drug deals. Kerry denied
that he or his staff leaked any committee information.
   On another controversy, Bush refused to answer repeated
questions about a possible administration deal with Panamanian Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, while admitting a Senate resolution
condemning a deal reflects public opinion.
   ``I think it expresses a lot of the strong feeling out there
across the country on that matter, very strong,'' Bush said.
   President Reagan, when asked about the reported deal that would
drop charges against Noriega if he steps down, told reporters at
the White House, ``We're negotiating right now, and therefore I
can't comment on negotiations that are under way. ... I have to say
that I think that much of what many of you have been dealing with
as a story is based on some kind of leaks or misinformation,
because there are no facts to sustain it.''
   Bush talked about agriculture Tuesday, touring an irrigation
center at California State University at Fresno, a fresh fruit
processing plant and an orchard.
   The vice president professed not to be concerned about a CBS
News-New York Times poll putting him 10 points behind likely
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
   ``I don't worry about it. The election is 5{ months away,'' he
told reporters on the college campus.
   The poll put Bush at 39 percent and Dukakis at 49 percent in a
prospective fall matchup, numbers Bush admitted were not good news.
   ``No, they weren't,'' he said. ``I feel about like I did about
how (opinion polls) looked in New Hampshire 24 hours before the
polls opened. I was 8 points back and I won by 10. They were off by
18 points.
   ``So what you do when the polls don't look good, you work hard.''
   Bush's negative ratings were high in the poll. Thirty-three
percent said they had a favorable view of Bush and 35 percent said
they had an unfavorable view. While voters are less familiar with
Dukakis, his favorable rating stood at 38 percent and unfavorable
at 14 percent.
   Asked if the administration's recent problems _ particularly
with Noriega and the investigation of Attorney General Edwin Meese
III _ have contributed to his high negatives, Bush agreed.
   ``You may have put your finger on something there,'' he said.
   Later in Los Angeles, Bush added: ``It could an accumulation of
current events, but I don't worry about it. I've learned not to
live on these polls.
   However, Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said that the
negative ratings can change quickly in a presidential campaign.
   Bush spokesman Pete Teeley added that Dukakis has some
advantages with a race still under way.
   ``Dukakis is in a very enviable position_ he is scoring a knock
every Tuesday, while we have no opponents...and we have suffered in
the polls,'' said Teeley.
   Bush argued that the general election battle has not been joined.
   ``The thing hasn't really started in terms of Democrats versus
Republicans and we haven't gotten any of that in focus and it won't
be until after the convention,'' Bush said.
   He said that his focus on Republican groups will change as the
fall race gets started.
   ``In a primary you go where the primary votes are,'' Bush said.
``I think we have to reach out the best we can to all voters. I
made that point clear to a group of Hispanic leaders. ... We'll
start doing more of that.''
   On agriculture, Bush said the outlook had improved for farmers.
   ``I know the 80s have been tough years for farmers, very tough
years for some,'' he told a gathering of supporters in Fresno.
``But there is strontg evidence now that the 85 farm bill is
working.''
   Bush said farmers had convinced him to talk to the Immigration
and Naturalization Service about the guest workers program that
allows Mexicans to come into the country to harvest crops.
   ``I recognize how important guest workers are not only to you
and harvesting crops, but to the country. And I support the
provision of the immigration reform bill that allows you an
adequate supply,'' he said.
   He also slammed Dukakis for calling for a greater federal role
in allocating water, ``the lifeblood of California agriculture.
   ``I was interest to see that Gov. Mike Dukakis assert a federal
interest in allocating water rights in the West. You want to see
the sagebrush rebellion start up all over again. Listen to that
kind of talk. It's the states that should have the major say and
the major control, not the federal government,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
