<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusAccident 2ndLd-Writethru a0854 05-17 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Accident, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0854,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Carrying Mentally Handicapped People Crashes, 3 Known Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with number of passengers aboard,
details of crash and conditions of injured people.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB15</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus carrying mentally handicapped people
careened down a hill and overturned near a creek Monday, killing
three people and injuring the other 20 aboard, state police said.
   The bus, owned by the California-based transportation company
Laidlaw Transit, was the only vehicle involved in the afternoon
accident 12 miles northeast of Poughkeepsie, said Trooper Gerard
Salmon.
   The bus was traveling down a steep hill when it failed to make a
sharp right turn, hit a utility pole, overturned and came to rest
on its side about 30 feet from the road and just a few feet from
Little Wappingers Creek, state police Sgt. Dennis Cody said.
   It was not immediately known what caused the accident, Cody said.
   Witnesses described the wreckage as looking like a crushed
yellow school bus. The safety of converted school buses is under
scrutiny this week after a fiery weekend crash in Kentucky killed
at least 27 people on a church outing. The passengers, who were
mentally handicapped, worked for Rehabilitation Programs Inc. in
the town of Poughkeepsie. They were being driven home from three
locations, Cody said.
   John Dalyrymple, 44, of Clinton Corners, and Patricia Russo, 23,
of Clinton Hollow, were dead at the scene, Cody said. Raymond
Phillips, 25, of Clinton Corners, was dead on arrival at Northern
Dutchess Hospital in Rhinebeck, Cody said.
   Bus driver, Lewis Taylor, 44, of Poughkeepsie, was in stable
condition with head injuries, abrasions and broken bones, said a
Northern Dutchess Hospital spokeswoman. She said two other
passengers were treated and released.
   A spokeswoman for Vassar Brothers Hospital said six passengers
were treated and released and two others were being held for
observation. A fireman was treated and released for heat
exhaustion, she said.
   St. Francis Hospital spokeswoman Carol Huber said nine people
were treated for injuries there.
   Huber said six people were in critical condition, including two
who were transferred to Westchester Medical Center in Valhalla. One
person was in fair condition, one was in good condition and another
was treated and released, she said.
</TEXT>
