<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SkyscraperEvacuation     05-17 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skyscraper Evacuation,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Alarms Send 400 Out of Damaged Tower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people evacuated the state's
tallest building twice Monday after a smoking air compressor and a
small fire in a sub-basement sparked fears of a repeat of this
month's deadly blaze.
   A small fire that ignited in a basement section of the 62-story
First Interstate Bank tower was extinguished by the time
firefighters arrived late Monday afternoon and no damage or
injuries were reported, Assistant Fire Chief David Sloan said.
   Firefighters were called back to the building a third time late
in the afternoon because of a report of smoke. That turned out to
be a false alarm, said Fire Department spokesman Jim Williamson.
   Sloan said the three incidents were coincidence.
   A May 4 fire gutted four floors of the downtown bank tower,
killed a janitor who became trapped in a fiery elevator and injured
40 others, several of them firefighters overcome by smoke.
   The approximately 400 people evacuated Monday included crews
cleaning up from the earlier fire. Some workers had to walk down
dozens of flights of stairs, and one woman reportedly fainted and
had to be treated.
   ``My knees were telling me I'm an old man,'' said electrician
Dan Pullen, who went down from the 46th floor.
   Meanwhile, a special task force that examined the deadly blaze
urged Monday that sprinklers be required for all high-rise
buildings in the city within four years. The task force report,
released by Mayor Tom Bradley, also recommended enclosure of
elevator lobbies and air pressurization of stairwells.
</TEXT>
