<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDS-CivilRights Bjt   05-17 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Civil Rights, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Hearing Marked By Protests, Name-Calling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Civil Rights Commission hearing on AIDS
turned surreal when gay protesters in clown masks hummed ``America
the Beautiful,'' shouted insults at witnesses and commissioners and
held up wristwatches to denote that ``time is running out'' for
AIDS victims.
   Monday's hearing became so heated that one witness said he would
rather die ``in the street'' than in the hospice run by another,
and a third said gay pressure groups are thwarting public health
efforts.
   The hearing also featured feuding commission members denouncing
each other's remarks and tangling with witnesses over racism,
``sexual addiction'' and other issues with little direct relation
to the subject at hand _ AIDS and discrimination.
   At one point, the 65 gay protesters in clown masks turned their
backs on the proceedings to show their disdain for the commission
and its efforts.
   ``This is a waste of time,'' said Duncan Osborne, one of the
protesters. ``This is a waste of money.''
   Osborne said the money would be better spent testing new drugs
or educating people on how to avoid getting AIDS.
   The commission proposed its hearings, part of a larger study, in
a memo that discussed state sodomy laws in the same footnote as
Biblical denunciations of homosexuality.
   Osborne and others said the commission could play a legitimate
role investigating employment, housing, health care and insurance
discrimination against AIDS victims. But they said the panel has no
business reopening debate on how AIDS is transmitted or hearing
inflammatory testimony from witnesses who are not medical or public
health experts.
   Jim Johnson, executive director of a religious hospice in Long
Beach, Calif., called Beyond Rejection, said homosexual activists
had bombed his hospice and threatened him because he had left
behind ``the narcissism and contempt of my earlier life'' as a
homosexual.
   Jeffrey Levi, executive director of the National Gay and Lesbian
Task Force, noted the prevailing medical belief that a homosexual
orientation cannot be changed.
   ``If I had to make the choice between dying in the street and
dying in his hospice, I'd choose dying in the street,'' Levi said.
   Dr. David Pence, a University of Minnesota radiologist, Vietnam
war protester and civil rights worker, alleged that gay pressure
groups have thwarted public health efforts to stop the spread of
AIDS.
   ``Twenty-five years ago it was Southern bullies in jeans that we
had to fight. Now it's Northern smoothies in ties,'' Pence said.
   An outraged Levi demanded a retraction and an apology.
   ``He has just likened us ... to the Ku Klux Klan,'' Levi said.
``That is so deeply offensive that I question whether I can
continue to sit at the same table with him.''
   He said gay people oppose reporting techniques which identify
victims by name because they fear discrimination of all types, even
prosecution for violating sodomy laws, if anyone finds out they are
victims or carriers of AIDS.
   If there were federal laws barring discrimination on the basis
of sexual orientation, Levi said, ``we wouldn't have to be here.''
He said the commission should recommend that type of law and
recommend extending to the private sector a law barring
discrimination against handicapped people who are not a public
health threat.
   Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of the National Institute of Allergy
and Infectious Diseases, said public health officials had not been
influenced by any lobbying groups in determining AIDS policy or
interpreting AIDS research.
   ``It is totally preposterous to even imagine that any scientist
I know ... would take a stand on how the virus is transmitted based
on pressure,'' he said. ``The evidence is overwhelming.''
   Teen-age pregnancy, babies with AIDS and incest in migrant
families were among the concerns discussed by commissioners and
witnesses. So was ``sexual addiction,'' a condition Pence described
as likely to lead to AIDS and defined as engaging in ``compulsive
coital behavior outside of marriage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MobTrial     05-17 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mob Trial,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Mafia Leader Sentenced to Six Years in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reputed leader of the Southern California
Mafia, who pleaded guilty to extortion, was sentenced to six years
in prison Monday as provided under a plea bargain arrangement.
   Seven other reputed mobsters also were sentenced by U.S.
District Court Judge Ferdinand Fernandez, who upheld the plea
bargain agreements for each.
   Peter John Milano, 62, of Westlake Village, pleaded guilty in
March to involvement in a criminal enterprise in which he committed
two acts of racketeering. In return, he was guaranteed a 6-year
sentence rather than a possible 20 years.
   Milano, who owns Rome Vending Co., also was assured that he
would have other federal charges against him dropped and that he
was ``not a subject or target'' of any other federal investigation.
   While Milano pleaded guility, he and others indicted have
maintained they do not belong to the Mafia.
   When the indictment against Milano and his associates was
announced last year, U.S. Attorney Robert C. Bonner said ``the main
body of La Cosa Nostra in Los Angeles has been severely gutted.''
   Attorney General Edwin Meese called it ``the most significant
organized crime case on the West Coast in a decade.''
   Also sentenced were Milano's brother and reputed underboss,
Carmen Joseph Milano, 58, of the Los Angeles district of Tarzana,
to six months; Charles Caci, 51, an entertainer who uses the name
Bobby Milano, to one year, one day, and his brother, Vincent Caci,
52, both of Palm Springs, to one year and one day; Rocco Zangari,
54, of Palm Springs, to five years probation, and a $2,000 fine;
Stephen Cino, 51, of Las Vegas, to 1{ years; Albert Jesus Nunez,
57, to 10 years.
   All pleaded guilty to extortion and conspiracy. Nunez also
pleaded guilty to conspiring to distribute cocaine, and Cino also
pleaded guilty to making false statements.
   Also sentenced was John DeMattia, 51 of Sherman Oaks. DeMattia,
who pleaded guilty to conspiracy, conspiracy to make a false
statement on a loan application, and wire fraud, was given 3 years,
3 days in prison.
   The indictment involved violations of the federal Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations statute. The Los Angeles case
was one of several RICO indictments nationwide that stemmed from a
1982 crackdown on organized crime.
   The indictment followed an FBI investigation during which Milano
allegedly ordered the killing of two suspected informants. The
murders never occurred because of tips from informants, the
indictment said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Eastland Bjt   05-17 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Eastland, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Fires Spokesman, Seeks Outside PR Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III is turning to
an outside public relations consultant to improve his image after
firing the Justice Department's chief spokesman, prompting
accusations by conservatives that he wants ``blind loyalty.''
   Despite the department's annual $1.7 million public affairs
budget, it is negotiating a contract with an employee of the public
relations firm Hill & Knowlton to help depict Meese as a tough
drug-buster.
   Word of the planned outside public relations contract surfaced
Monday along with the news that Meese had fired department
spokesman Terry Eastland.
   At a news conference, Eastland said that with Meese under
criminal investigation since May 1987, ``it would be difficult for
me to be as aggressive as he might like'' in defending the attorney
general.
   Meese said he simply thought it was time for ``new leadership''
and denied that Eastland's dismissal had anything to do with his
own legal problems.
   But department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Eastland was fired Friday for refusing to provide unconditional
support to Meese in the face of the criminal investigation.
   In a letter to Meese, Eastland said that ``you have expressed to
me your desire to have as director of public affairs someone
willing to aggressively defend you against, in effect, any and all
criticism. ... You have concluded that my efforts have not
sufficed.''
   As soon as Eastland's firing was disclosed, the head of Meese's
speech-writing unit, William Schambra, abruptly quit, saying he was
``perplexed and deeply disturbed by the attorney general's
decision.''
   The outside public relations contract is being negotiated with
Charles Crawford of Hill & Knowlton's Washington office.
   Hill & Knowlton chairman Bob Gray emphasized that the contract
is to be a 60-day arrangement with Crawford personally on drug
enforcement issues and that ``it's not a contract with me or the
firm.''
   However, he also said, ``I've always felt that whoever had''
Eastland's position ``had too much to do on a day-to-day basis to
spend much time on departmental problems.''
   Gray has close ties to the Reagan administration, but he denied
having anything to do with Eastland's dismissal, saying it was
``news to me.''
   Conservatives lamented the firing of Eastland, a staunch
conservative who helped craft many of Meese's most controversial
speeches on subjects ranging from civil rights policies to Supreme
Court rulings.
   ``I think it is a severe blow to the overall effort of the Meese
Justice Department to change the conventional intellectual
wisdom,'' said conservative scholar Bruce Fein, a former department
official. ``Terry was devoted to challenging the liberal nostrums
of the past.''
   Meese ``has fallen prey to bad advice from those who confuse
blind loyalty with good government,'' said Gary L. McDowell, a
political conservative and Meese's former chief speechwriter. He
called the firing ``the single greatest mistake Ed Meese has made
since becoming attorney general.''
   Meese told reporters that there ``are times when you need new
leadership in a particular division and that's what happened here.''
   He contradicted the statement in Eastland's letter about a
perceived lack of a sufficiently aggressive defense, saying the
dismissal ``had nothing to do with a defense of me.''
   Meese replaced Eastland with his No. 2 spokesman, Patrick
Korten, who told reporters he intends ``to be very aggressive about
every part of the job.''
   Meese's ``ethical conduct has been entirely aboveboard,'' said
Korten. ``I think he's a very ethical man. I think he's a very
moral man.''
   Independent counsel James McKay has been investigating the
attorney general's ties to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and a $1
billion Iraqi oil pipeline project. Meese's longtime friend E.
Robert Wallach is under indictment in the Wedtech case.
   McKay also has subpoenaed records of the $40,000-a-year job held
by Meese's wife, Ursula. Her salary with a Washington charity is
being paid by a wealthy Washington family that leases offices to
the Justice Department.
   McKay is expected to issue a report shortly raising numerous
questions about Meese's ethical behavior, and Eastland said
``someone like me could not be indifferent to what might be
contained or flow from the independent counsel's report.''
   Education Secretary William Bennett, who once wrote a book with
Eastland, immediately offered him a job at the Department of
Education.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, the ranking Republican on
the Senate Judiciary Committee, issued a statement saying he was
concerned by the firing.
   Thurmond said ``Eastland has a fine reputation,'' and he added
that the committee will hold hearings after the independent
counsel's investigation of Meese is concluded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
