<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Canada-Jazz     05-17 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Canada-Jazz,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montreal Jazz Festival Also Features Salsa, Reggae and Strings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This summer's version of the Montreal Jazz
Festival will also feature salsa, reggae, blues and an all-Gershwin
program by the Montreal Symphony Orchestra, organizers announced.
   ``Everybody will find what they're looking for,'' the festival's
president, Alain Simard, said on Monday.
   The ninth Montreal International Jazz Festival, July 1-10, will
open with a concert by legendary trumpeter Miles Davis. Other stars
include Carmen McRae, Dizzy Gillespie, Ornette Coleman, Diane
Schurr and the Count Basie Orchestra, Carla Bley, Larry Coryell and
Manhattan Transfer.
   About 600 musicians in all, from Senegal's Youssou N'Dour to
salsa king Louie Ramirez and reggae star Jimmy Cliff, will be in
Montreal for the bash.
   Toronto is also planning a summer jazz festival, starting June
17 with Oscar Peterson and later featuring trumpeter Wynton
Marsalis, George Shearing, Gary Burton and Archie Shepp.
