<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Teamsters-Presser     05-17 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters-Presser,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Officials Meet; Power Struggle Denied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARADISE VALLEY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters union executives met
behind closed doors to discuss an orderly transfer of power while
indicted president Jackie Presser undergoes cancer treatment, an
official said.
   Union leaders are supporting Presser, not vying for his job as
head of the 1.7 million-member union, Secretary-Treasurer Weldon L.
Mathis said Monday.
   ``You're talking about a very dear personal friend of mine,''
Mathis said of questions about possible successors to Presser if
his illness proved to be life-threatening. ``I don't know of any
power struggle.''
   Presser, 61, is hospitalized at the Barrow Neurological
Institute in Phoenix, reportedly for treatment of brain cancer. He
previously underwent surgery for a malignant tumor on his lung.
   Institute spokeswoman Debra Gelbart confirmed that Presser was
being treated but said no other information would be released.
   Labor-movement specialist Nick Salvatore of Cornell University's
School of Industrial and Labor Relations said the nature of power
ensures contenders for Presser's job.
   ``I think he wants to run things from the hospital, but I don't
know how he's going to do it,'' Salvatore said. ``This is what
(former Teamsters president) Jimmy Hoffa was going to do from jail,
and Frank Fitzsimmons had other ideas.''
   ``If the incapacitation becomes permanent, the question seems to
be who will win the power struggle, who will take over,'' Salvatore
added. ``But those aren't the real issues. The real issue is that
the nation's largest union has no internal democratic structure.''
   Mathis discounted reports that Presser's illness and his May 4
start of a four-month leave of absence had sparked a power struggle.
   ``This meeting was called to report to the board on the
procedures to be followed in the absence of the general president,
to make sure we continue to operate in an orderly manner,'' he said.
   At least five members of the 18-member executive committee
failed to attend Monday's meeting here, but Mathis denied that they
were dissenting although some had wanted to meet in Washington.
Several were on vacation or ill and one excused himself because he
was placing his wife in a hospital, Mathis said.
   The committee is comprised of vice presidents, Presser and the
secretary-treasurer.
   Mathis said he had not been told how Presser was faring or given
details of his condition, which he described as ``lesions of the
brain.''
   ``I know that he left a Cleveland clinic and came out here for
an evaluation of whether the condition was operable,'' Mathis said.
   Mathis said he did not know whether Presser's leave of absence
would last longer than four months. But he added, ``I don't expect
him to be out longer than that.''
   Presser is scheduled to stand trial on July 12 in U.S. District
Court in Cleveland on embezzlement and racketeering charges.
   Presser's attorneys have said he does not want to postpone the
trial, but was too ill to attend a hearing this week by U.S.
District Judge George White to discuss Presser's health. The
hearing was rescheduled for June 3.
   Presser is accused, along with two other Teamsters officials, of
siphoning $700,000 in union funds to no-show employees from
Teamsters Local 507 in Cleveland. Presser remains
secretary-treasurer of Local 507, his hometown local.
   Presser, who has been Teamsters president since 1983, has
pleaded innocent. His attorneys say Presser was a government
informant and was authorized by the FBI to pay the so-called ghost
employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Regan-Doctor     05-17 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Regan-Doctor,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Doctor Says Surgery Not Influenced by Astrology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's doctor has taken former
White House chief of staff Donald T. Regan to task for alleging
that astrology might have played a part in the timing of the
president's 1985 operation for colon cancer.
   ``At no time was astrology consulted,'' presidential physician
Col. John Hutton said in a letter released Monday by the White
House.
   Hutton sent the letter to Time magazine, which printed excerpts
from Regan's book, ``For the Record.'' In the book, the former
presidential aide disclosed that Nancy Reagan consulted an
astrologer for help in determining the president's schedule.
   Although White House officials confirmed that the first lady had
an interest in astrology, they refused to point to specific
incidents in which it was used.
   A telephone call placed to the White House physician was not
immediately returned.
   Hutton said in the letter that the subject of astrology never
came up in the conversation he witnessed between the president and
first lady about the timing of the cancer surgery.
   Regan's book discusses a conversation he had with the first lady
before the president's July 1985 surgery in which she told Regan
the surgery might have to be delayed for a day and a half. Regan
said he was concerned by that comment.
   ``First, that President Reagan's condition was more serious than
his wife had been able to tell me over the phone, and second, that
the first lady was choosing a date for surgery in consultation with
her astrologer,'' Regan wrote.
   Hutton criticized Regan for making that allegation.
   ``Unfortunately, Mr. Regan chose the second alternative as the
most likely and on this false assumption provides the reader with
the first element of incorrect information concerning an event he
did not witness,'' Hutton said.
   The physician, an Army colonel, said that following an
examination of the president's colon on July 12, 1985, ``a large
suspicious mass or polyp'' was discovered, four sites were
biopsied, and ``a presumptive diagnosis of cancer was made.''
   The president's team of doctors recommended that the surgery be
scheduled for the next day and ``the first lady agreed that we
should proceed as soon as possible,'' Hutton wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
