<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmDrivers     05-17 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Drivers,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Drivers Should Be Exempt From Commercial Vehicle Rules,
Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drivers of farm vehicles should be exempted
from regulations being considered to implement a 2-year-old federal
law regulating commercial vehicles, says an Agriculture Department
official.
   Martin F. ``Buzz'' Fitzpatrick Jr., head of the USDA's office of
transportation, said Monday that drivers of farm vehicles are not
commercial drivers and should be excluded from the Commercial Motor
Vehicle Act of 1986.
   ``Compared to non-farm drivers, they drive shorter distances,
fewer total miles and have a lower rate of involvement in fatal
accidents,'' he said. ``The minimal risk presented by these drivers
does not justify the burden that would be imposed on them or on
enforcement officials if all the provisions of the act were to be
enforced.''
   Fitzpatrick said the law requires that the drivers of commercial
vehicle with a gross weight of more than 26,000 pounds have a
single driver's license with a single driving record, be tested for
the type of vehicle driven, and be required to notify their
employer and home state of any traffic violations.
   Regulations to implement the law are currently under
consideration by the Transportation Department.
   Fitzpatrick said the law gives the secretary of transportation
authority to waive any class of drivers or vehicles from any or all
of the law's provisions.
</TEXT>
