<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PresidentialScholars     05-17 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Scholars,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>139 High School Seniors Named Presidential Scholars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 139 high school seniors chosen as 1988
Presidential Scholars will each receive a $1,000 award and will be
feted in Washington next month during a round of ceremonies
including a White House visit.
   The administration announced the winners Monday. They include at
least one boy and girl from each state, and were honored for
achievements in both academics and the arts.
   They have been invited to Washington June 13-17, when they will
receive their Presidential Scholar medallions at the White House.
   Of the winners, 121 were selected on the basis of academic
achievements, leadership qualities, character and ideals; 18 were
chosen for their accomplishments in the performing or creative
arts, as well as leadership and character.
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett said in a statement:
``These young men and women have worked hard and they have much to
show for it. We are proud to recognize them and thereby reaffirm
our national commitment to excellence in education.''
   The winners were chosen from a field of 1,500 seniors who scored
high on the Scholastic Aptitude Test or the American College Test
and who had top grades and extracurricular activities.
   That field was winnowed to 500 after the students submitted
essays, self-assessments, school recommendations and transcripts. A
Commission on Presidential Scholars subsequently made the final
selection.
   The program is in its 24th year. Each student has named his or
her most influential teacher, who will also be brought to
Washington and receive a certificate from the Department of
Education.
   The Geraldine R. Dodge Foundation of Morristown, N.J., provides
$1,000 awards to each scholar to pursue an ``educational dream.''
The General Motors Corp. provides financial support for the
scholars' recognition week in Washington.
</TEXT>
