<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Afghan     05-17 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghan,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Mediator Contacting Afghans For Broad-Based Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Afghan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan government that includes
Marxists and Moslems is within reach even though the guerrillas
have vowed to seize the country when the Soviets leave, a United
Nations official said.
   Undersecretary-General Diego Cordovez, who mediated the April 14
agreement for the removal of Soviet troops, said he has begun
promoting contacts among disparate Afghan groups in an effort to
form a broad-based government.
   ``I think there is more communication now between the Afghans
themselves than you think,'' he said told a news conference on
Monday. ``The effects of the settlement and troop withdrawal are
beginning to sink in.''
   About 1,300 Soviet soldiers pulled out of the northeastern city
of Jalalabad on Sunday, the first contigent of troops to withdraw
under the international accord signed in Geneva.
   The Soviets intervened militarily in December 1979 to help the
Marxist government battle the predominately Moslem guerrillas who
have been backed by the United States and Pakistan.
   Under the Geneva accord, all of the 115,000 Soviet military
personnel in Afghanistan are to be withdrawn within nine months.
   The agreement between Afghanistan and Pakistan, with guarantees
by the United States and Soviet Union, also calls for an end to
outside interference and repatriation of more than 5 million Afghan
refugees in Pakistan and Iran.
   ``The agreement also says the desirable government is a
broad-based government involving all segments of Afghan society now
living inside and outside the country,'' Cordovez said. ``That is
what I hope will be achieved.''
   Afghan guerrillas, who received support from the United States
and Pakistan, have rejected the accords and have vowed to continue
fighting. They did not participate in the Geneva negotiations.
   Cordovez declined to answer questions about allegations that
arms for the rebels are still being moved into Afghanistan, mainly
from Pakistan.
   He said if a formal complaint is lodged about such arms
shipments, ``My approach would be to discuss the problem with
whoever is involved on a case-by-case basis.''
   A U.N. peace mission in the country will have 50 unarmed
military officers headquartered in Kabul, the Afghan capital, and
Islamabad, Pakistan, where many of the guerrilla groups have
offices. The mission also will have a civilian support staff of 40
to 50 people.
   Cordovez confirmed the 50 military officers now are deployed,
and said 10 were in Jalalabad as Soviet troops began to leave
Sunday.
   Members of the U.N. mission are from Austria, Canada, Denmark,
Fiji, Finland, Ghana, Ireland, Nepal, Poland and Sweden.
   Cordovez said the top U.N. officer in the area, Maj. Gen. Rauli
Helminen of Finland, was assured by Afghanistan and Pakistan that
they would implement the Geneva accords.
   ``We have been given full assurances that we will observe this
(withdrawal) operation and ... on the day in which they (Soviet
troops) cross the border, there will be United Nations military
officers on the border between Afghanistan and the Soviet Union,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
