<HEAD>Hotel Workers Call Off Strike In Bermuda</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fixes typo in dateline. Pickup 2nd graf pvs, ``The
decision...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bermuda's hotel workers called off a
strike they had planned to begin on Wednesday.
   The decision was reached Monday after the government offered to
establish a board of inquiry into the workers' 5-month-old
employment contract dispute.
   The offer won narrow acceptance in a secret ballot among the
members of the Bermuda Industrial Union, said the union's
president, Ottiwell Simmons.
   ``This strike is off for the moment,'' said Simmons, who
represents about 3,000 hotel workers in the British colony.
   Workers are demanding salary increases of at least 13 percent.
The hotels offered an 8 percent increase. Workers also want to
reduce work week from six days to five and a say in managing their
$12 million pension fund.
