<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     05-17 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Backs Away From Reagan Record On Environment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When George Bush talks about Republican
presidents who protected the environment, he praises Theodore
Roosevelt's accomplishments and mentions Richard Nixon. But the
vice president doesn't cite Ronald Reagan.
   The GOP nominee-apparent usually keeps himself well-aligned with
Reagan administration policies, but on Monday he began to put some
space between his campaign and Reagan's environmental record.
   `I don't think we've been doing enough to protect our
environment in recent years. We need to do more,'' he said.
   Bush was also blasting a published report that linked his
national security adviser, Donald Gregg, with a Contra arms-supply
operation that was bankrolled with drug money.
   Bush accused Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts, who chairs a
Senate subcommittee that has been looking into the allegations, of
leaking ``slanderous'' information about the matter.
   ``I would challenge Sen. Kerry ... to show some evidence and
stop leaking out information that's not fair or true,'' he told
reporters in Seattle on Monday.
   Kerry could not be reached for comment Monday night, but The
Washington Post quoted him in today's editions as denying that he
or his staff was responsible. The most recent report about the
matter appeared in Newsweek magazine.
   ``Some magazine elects to reprint garbage,'' Bush said. ``I get
annoyed. Some insidious political game is going on.''
   On environmental issues, the vice president was distancing
himself from Reagan.
   ``A new administration is a time for change, a time for renewal.
I will put the very best people we can find to work on our
environmental agenda,'' Bush told the Greater Seattle Chamber of
Commerce.
   ``A Bush administration will enforce environmental laws
aggressively, putting the responsibility for the cleanup where it
belongs _ on those who caused the problem in the first place,'' he
said.
   The vice president met privately Monday with Washington state
backers of Pat Robertson, who halted his presidential campaign
Monday.
   Bruce Hawkins, Robertson's state organizer, said he was happy
with the meeting.
   ``I didn't have to pledge anything,'' Bush told reporters
afterward. He said Robertson wouldn't have enough delegates to
disrupt things at the convention in New Orleans anyway.
   He quickly added, ``I don't want to suggest they're going to go
there and be disruptive.''
   The vice president was asked by reporters in Seattle about
Attorney General Edwin Meese's firing of his chief spokesman, Terry
Eastland, but refused to comment. He also declined to say whether
Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega was the kind of
``drug kingpin'' Bush has proposed the death penalty for.
   Environmental issues have been the focus of Bush's weeklong
Western swing _ both in his speeches and in his actions, including
a raft trip down an Oregon river on Sunday.
   Today he shifts his focus to agriculture, with a tour of two
orchards near Fresno and a briefing on the state of the farm
economy.
   Both themes are aimed at bolstering the vice president in the
general election, Bush aides say, emphasizing the importance of the
Pacific Coast states in winning the White House in November. Bush
trails Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis in recent polls in
both California and Oregon.
   The vice president on Monday demonstrated some prowess with a
forklift, impressing a sawmill operator as he deftly lowered a pile
of logs into a lake for storage.
   ``How 'bout that,'' Bush said as they landed.
   Alex Cugini, Jr., president and manager of the family-operated
sawmill near Seattle, said Bush ``showed a lot of finesse,'' and
added: ``I'd definitely hire him.''
</TEXT>
