<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-StalinFilm     05-17 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stalin Film,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stalin Documentary Premiers Nationwide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A film debating the leadership of Josef V. Stalin
premiered on nationwide television after censors held it back for
eight months and the director was reprimanded for putting the
nation's history on public trial.
   ``The Process'' discusses the late dictator's repression of real
and imagined political opponents, mass deportation of people who
resisted the spread of Soviet rule in the Baltic and the Ukraine
and other topics.
   Most of the Soviets interviewed in the two-hour documentary
aired Monday night condemned Stalin's 29-year leadership. But there
were others who saw him as the force that transformed a peasant
nation ravaged by revolution and war into an industrial and
military power.
   ``Instead of wasting time and talking about how to catch up with
the highly developed countries, it was necessary to make people
work,'' an academician identified as Medovar stated in the film.
``How could it have been done? By persuasion? No, only in this
way.''
   Anna Bukharin-Larina, widow of Nikolai I. Bukharin, had harsh
words for Stalin. ``He was cunning, perfidious, artful,
vindictive,'' Ms. Larina said. ``I consider him a criminal.''
   Bukharin, an early member of the Communist Party Politburo, was
expelled in 1929 for disagreeing with Stalin and was executed in
1938 after a show trial.
   Excerpts of the heated condemnations of show-trial prosecutor
Andrei Vyshinsky followed a film clip in which Stalin raises a
rifle and takes aim.
   The juxtaposition apparently was director Igor Belyaev's way of
symbolically saying that Stalin was behind the deaths of Bukharin
and other revolutionary contemporaries of Soviet founder Vladimir
I. Lenin.
   Ms. Larina read a letter written by her husband when he knew
Stalin had targeted him. The letter appealed to a future leader to
clear Bukharin's name and expose Stalin's crimes against the Soviet
people.
   Ms. Larina said she memorized the letter and recited it to
herself each day when she was in a labor camp following Bukharin's
death. The letter was made public last November. Bukharin was fully
rehabilitated in February.
   The second half of the film opened with footage from the late
1920s showing zealots blowing up churches and driving wagons over
crops in the brutal collectivization campaign. The footage was
accompanied by historian Vladimir Tikhonov's claim that the drive
was carried out ``at a barbaric pace.''
   Veterans of the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution that brought the
Soviets to power told of bread rationing and hunger that followed
collectivization, but argued among themselves about the need for
the drive and about its success.
   In a discussion after scenes from an anti-Stalinist play,
``Dictatorship of Conscience,'' young people said that some were
confused by the rejection of their past.
   The review and rejection of Stalinism, carried in articles in
the Soviet press over the past year, is seen as part of Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's perestroika campaign that aims to rebuild society and
root out stagnation.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda published an article on Saturday saying the
film, prepared in advance of last November's 70th anniversary of
the revolution, was held back by censors for eight months and that
director Belyaev was reprimanded for the heavy criticism in the
documentary.
   The newspaper concluded that the Soviet Union would not have
been ready for the film without first facing the facts about
Stalin's legacy in the smaller doses that have been administered
over the last year.
   ``There is no confidence that this will last,'' a young Soviet
worker said of Gorbachev's social reforms. ``We don't know what
will be tomorrow or the day after tomorrow, and nobody will tell
you what he really thinks.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
