<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Honduran-Cocaine     05-17 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduran-Cocaine,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduran Official Held For Alleged Cocaine Possession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras' ambassador to Panama tried to smuggle
more than 25 pounds of cocaine into the United States by stashing
it in clothing in his suitcase, authorities said.
   A U.S. magistrate on Monday ordered Rigoberto Regalado Lara,
step-brother of Honduras' armed forces commander-in-chief, held
without bond on a charge of possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute.
   Regalado, 49, was arrested Sunday after he arrived at Miami
International Airport from Tegucigalpa on TAN Airlines Flight 808,
according to court records.
   An affidavit said that during an examination of Regalado's
luggage, a U.S. Customs inspector ``discovered a white powdery
substance secreted inside 10 packages surrounded by coffee and
wrapped in plastic, concealed inside pants legs and other clothing
in his suitcase.'' Tests showed that the substance contained 25.85
pounds of cocaine, the affidavit said.
   A narcotics agent who spoke on the condition that he not be
identified said cocaine smugglers sometimes use coffee to block
detection by dogs.
   U.S. Magistrate Peter Palermo scheduled a second hearing for
Thursday. Regalado was being held in the federal Metropolitan
Correctional Center.
   The Honduran Foreign Ministry, meanwhile, announced Monday night
it suspended Regalado's diplomatic status, and that U.S.
authorities were free to prosecute.
   If convicted, Regalado would be liable for ``the corresponding
legal sanctions'' in Honduras and the United States, said Eugenio
Castrol, a spokesman for the Honduran Foreign Ministry in
Tegucigalpa.
   ``This once again is a demonstration that the government of
President Jose Azcona Hoyo is engaged in open combat against drug
trafficking ... without discrimination of any kind,'' said the
communique from Tegucigalpa.
   Regalado, a retired army colonel and Honduran ambassador to
Panama since 1986, is a step-brother of Gen. Humberto Regalado
Hernandez, the armed forces commander-in-chief of Honduras.
   In February, the Los Angeles Times reported that the general was
suspected of protecting Colombian traffickers who used Honduras as
a staging base for cocaine shipments to the United States. However,
the general, and the U.S. ambassador to Honduras, Everett Briggs,
denied the report.
   Leon Kellner, the U.S. attorney in Miami, called the case a
tragedy.
   ``It shows what drug-oriented money will do in the Western
Hemisphere,'' said Kellner, who also is prosecuting Panamanian
military leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega on drug trafficking
charges. ``No one is immune from the lure of drug-generated money _
not even an ambassador.''
   Honduras experienced an outbreak of anti-American sentiment
after April 5, when Juan Ramon Matta, 43, considered an
international cocaine kigpin, was arrested and whisked out of the
country.
   Matta was taken to the United States to face drug trafficking
charges and questioning in the 1986 torture-slaying in Mexico of
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent Enrique Camarena Salazar.
   He is in a federal penitentiary in Marion, Ill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
