<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SEC-Harassment     05-17 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SEC-Harassment,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Worker Who Won Harassment Case Says Office Was `Sexual
Playground'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Securities and Exchange Commission lawyer
who says the office had so many affairs going on that it ``operated
as a brothel'' may soon be clinching her legal victory over the
agency after winning the first round in court.
   SEC Chairman David Ruder said Monday that SEC lawyers were
scheduled to meet today with counsel for Catherine Broderick, who
had asked Ruder to discuss a way to avert a lengthy battle in the
federal appeals court.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt ruled Friday that Ms.
Broderick, who worked for five years in the SEC's Washington
regional office, suffered sexual harassment by being forced to work
in a hostile environment.
   Pratt found that female employees who had sexual or other social
relationships with managers of the regional office's enforcement
division received promotions, positive evaluations and cash bonuses.
   But Ms. Broderick received negative evaluations, threats of
dismissal and eventually a transfer when she complained about
having ``to work in a hostile work environment.''
   Ms. Broderick told reporters Monday she hopes her former
supervisors will be fired for using the office as a ``sexual
playground.''
   ``The office operated as a brothel,'' she said.
   ``The affairs were carried on at the office and flaunted in
front of other employees,'' Broderick told reporters. ``They went
out for three-hour lunches and used the office for rendezvous after
work and on weekends.''
   Ruder, meanwhile, said in a statement that he was ``concerned
about the implications of the Broderick decision.''
   Indications of a possible settlement are a marked departure from
the SEC's previous stance in the case. During the trial, which took
place before Ruder became chairman the SEC had branded Ms.
Broderick as ``paranoid.'' Pratt specifically rejected that
assertion.
   Pratt scheduled a May 26 hearing to determine what sanctions to
impose against the SEC, which is likely to include an order that
Ms. Broderick receive promotions. The judge ruled she was denied
promotions even though she met eligibility requirements.
   Although Ms. Broderick herself was the victim of only isolated
incidents of direct sexual overtures, ``conduct of a sexual nature
was so pervasive ... that it can reasonably be said that such
conduct created a hostile or offensive work environment which
affected the motivation and work performance of those who found
such conduct repugnant and offensive,'' Pratt said.
   Ms. Broderick and attorneys S. Beville May and Lawrence King
called on Ruder to initiate disciplinary proceedings against the
agency officials. The judge said the officials gave testimony that
was ``deserving of little credence.''
   Ruder's statement noted that ``a determination whether to appeal
would be made by the entire commission.''
   Pratt's ruling included a finding that former SEC Chairman John
Shad, now U.S. ambassador to the Netherlands, and executive
director George Kundahl took no action after learning of Ms.
Broderick's complaints.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
