<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Garbologist'sView     05-17 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Garbologist's View,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court's Garbage Ruling Smells Just Fine to Arizona `Garbologist'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Rathje can breath a lot easier because
of a Supreme Court ruling, although the garbage will smell the same
as he rummages through the trash of Tucson.
   The University of Arizona professor is a 42-year-old
archaeologist who studies garbage for what it reveals about modern
civilization. He's a garbologist.
   Rathje's 30 students spend their class time sorting through
sacks brought in from selected tracts by city sanitation workers.
The contents are logged into 185 categories.
   The Supreme Court ruled Monday in a narcotics case that once
garbage is put out for curbside collection it is not entitled to
privacy. In other words, it's OK for someone else to rummage
through it.
   If the court had ruled the other way, said Rathje, ``that would
have made it impossible to sort garbage, period, without the
permission of each and every individual homeowner in the
community.''
   But Rathje says he and his students are not interested in
snooping on individual homeowners. ``We never have any tie directly
to any household,'' he said.
   What is learned from all this? For one thing, who contributes
what to the hazardous waste problem.
   ``Lower income neighborhoods tend to do a lot of home auto
repair, so they tend to dump a lot of used motor oil, spark plugs
and batteries,'' Rathje said in a telephone interview from Tucson.
   ``Middle income neighborhoods do a lot of home fixups, and there
are paints, stains and varnishes in the waste. Upper income
families spend a lot more time gardening. Therefore pesticides,
herbicides and fertilizers are thrown out in large quantities.''
   Rathje, who began this kind of research in 1973, said the first
bag he personally sorted contained a cooked T-Bone steak wrapped in
a paper towel. Another time a bag contained the entire contents of
a picnic: hot dog rolls, mustard, hot dogs _ all still in their
unopened packages.
   ``I just have an image of a family at home deciding to go out on
a picnic; George takes the garbage out in a brown paper bag and
Martha takes the picnic out to the car. They get there and find
they brought the garbage.''
   Those people probably had enough to eat anyway, he conjectures,
because Americans waste about 15 percent of the food they buy.
   ``In Tucson, garbage amounts to 9,500 tons a year,'' he said.
``The General Accounting Office in 1977, using our data, calculated
that in the United States we throw out enough food to feed all of
Canada, if they would take our leftovers.''
   Even though his research has gone on for 14 years, Rathje still
is at the classifying site to oversee sorting the garbage.
   ``You can't send your men out where you fear to tread,'' he
said. ``If you don't have a feel for the data, you're finished.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
