<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Editorial     05-17 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Editorial,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Times Calls For Meese Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington Times, a politically
conservative newspaper, says Attorney General Edwin Meese III
should resign because he has ``destroyed'' the Justice Department
while trying to defend his reputation.
   The editorial today calling for Meese's resignation is unusual
because the newspaper has strongly supported the Reagan
administration. It said Meese should concentrate on ``the cult of
character assassination that finally broke his spirit and weakened
his judgment.''
   The newspaper said Meese's firing of Justice Department director
of public affairs, Terry Eastland, ``makes it clear that the
embattled attorney general has decided to defend his reputation at
all costs.''
   Meese reportedly fired Eastland because he wasn't defending him
strongly enough against criticisms rising from an investigation of
Meese by independent counselor James McKay.
   The newspaper said it was calling for Meese's resignation
because ``Edwin Meese's attempts to vindicate himself have
destroyed his department.''
   The newspaper portrayed Eastland as a Meese loyalist who shared
the attorney general's constitutional agenda. It added that
Eastland ``had steadfastly battled against the sleazy insinuations
that make up the bulk of the political case against Edwin Meese.''
</TEXT>
