<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrash-Survivors     05-17 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash-Survivors,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier Lost Entire Family in Church Bus Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soldier whose wife and two children were
among the 27 people killed in a fiery bus crash was in shock, but
asked his fellow soldiers to pray for the survivors.
   ``As a professional soldier, he was trained to die, but not to
have his family die,'' Chaplain Michael Tilus said Monday,
referring to Army 1st Sgt. Lee Williams, 38, a Vietnam veteran.
   ``He's in the initial stages of shock. He's walking around for
20 minutes looking for his glasses when they are on his face,''
Tilus said. ``He's pacing his house at 2 in the morning.''
   ``A lot of the guys know he is a true Christian,'' Army Spec.
Thaddeus Fura said of Williams, ``but now everyone does because he
left a phone message with our Charge of Quarters asking people who
felt like it to pray for the other survivors.''
   Williams' wife, Joy, and daughters, Kristen, 14, and Robin, 10,
were aboard the church bus that crashed late Saturday as it
returned a First Assembly of God youth group and adult chaperones
from an amusement park north of Cincinnati.
   A pickup truck being driven in the wrong direction on Interstate
71 plowed head-on into the bus, causing its fuel tank to rupture
and setting the bus ablaze. Twenty-seven were killed and 42 were
injured.
   ``He has no one else,'' said Jean Grimes, Joy Williams'
identical twin. ``Joy and the kids were all he had.''
   Radcliff abuts Fort Knox and most of the families represented on
the bus had ties to the Army post.
   Seventeen of the 27 victims were spouses or children of Army
personnel and five were dependents of Fort Knox civilian employees,
said Maj. John Eagles, Fort Knox press officer.
   The Radcliff area on Monday was replete with reminders of the
tragedy. Flags were at half staff in the town of 20,000 residents
and at Fort Knox. Marquees and display signs of businesses along
Radcliff's main street contained expressions of sympathy for the
victims' families.
   At Radcliff Middle School, which lost 16 pupils in the accident,
the staff was ``just trying to use good common sense and trying to
make it an hour at a time,'' Principal Charlie Jones said Monday.
   At nearby North Hardin High School, which lost three students,
counselors and chaplains were standing by and teachers were
encouraged to talk about the accident with any students who felt
the need, Principal Ray Story said.
   One of the survivors, sophomore Allen Tennison, 15, could have
stayed home Monday but was back in class.
   ``The only way I know how to deal with it is to talk about it,''
said Tennison, son of the church's pastor, the Rev. W. Don
Tennison. ``There's times when I'm home and I look at pictures of
my friends and it hits me. But I've been numb all weekend.''
   Erica Jefferson said her 14-year-old son, Mike, hospitalized in
serious condition at Kosair Children's Hospital in Louisville, has
been told that his friends were killed.
   ``Oh yes, and does he blame himself that he was trying to get
out and couldn't help the others,'' Mrs. Jefferson said. ``He says
he hates to go back to sleep because all the time he sees that
blaze in his sleep.
   ``And I can tell, when he is on the monitor, that his heart was
pounding and he doesn't want to talk. But we make him talk.''
</TEXT>
