<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-17 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Plan To Test Bus, Subway Operators for Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government plans to make federal
transit subsidies contingent on local drug testing programs for
city transit bus and subway operators.
   Alfred Dellibovi, head of the Urban Mass Transit Administration,
said Monday that new regulations would require operators to submit
to a broad range of drug tests, including random sampling.
   The federal regulations will call on transit officials to test
for illegal use of drugs before employment, after an accident, for
reasonable cause and under a random selection process, according to
DelliBovi.
   Operators of buses and subway trains as well as others in
``sensitive'' jobs such as train dispatchers would be subject to
the testing, he said.
   UMTA provides federal financial assistance to transit systems,
although a testing program would have to be imposed and
administered by the local transit authorities.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says Billions of Dollars Saved From Canceled Weapons</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Programs
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cutbacks brought on by budget cuts have
lowered the price tag on the major weapons programs central to
President Reagan's military build-up by $61.8 billion.
   The Pentagon said Monday that at the close of the quarter on
Dec. 31, the 95 key programs carried a combined price tag of
$757.25 billion, down 7.5 percent from the adjusted Sept. 30, 1987,
total of $819.05 billion.
   The Pentagon attributed the quarterly decline to seven programs
that were either cancelled or ``significantly cut back'' in order
to comply with fiscal 1988 spending limits adopted last fall in a
compromise deficit-reduction package.
   Among the seven were production of Copperhead artillery rounds;
development and production of surveillance drone aircraft; and
development of a jam-proof high frequency radio system. Those cuts,
respectively, saved $423.3 million, $1.3 billion and $4.4 billion.
   Also killed were the ground-launched cruise missile program and
the satellite-killing ASAT rocket.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eisenhower, Kennedy Kin Named to Presidential Library Advisory</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Panel
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grandson of one president and the daughter
of another are on a new advisory committee on presidential
libraries established by the archivist of the United States.
   The nine-member advisory committee announced Monday will form a
closer alliance with the National Archives on joint public programs
and exhibitions. It also will work toward increasing private
support for the presidential library system, said John Fawcett,
head of presidential libraries.
   David Eisenhower, who recently wrote ``Eisenhower at War'' about
his grandfather, Dwight D. Eisenhower, is one member. Caroline
Kennedy Schlossberg, daughter of John F. Kennedy is another.
   They and the others will serve three-year terms. The National
Archives operates and maintains eight libraries housing the papers
of presidents Herbert Hoover, Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman,
Eisenhower, Kennedy, Lyndon Johnson, Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter.
</TEXT>
