<DOCNO> AP880517-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RememberingGertie Bjt   05-17 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Remembering Gertie, Bjt,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friendly Face, Message On Side Of A Barn</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCKEY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than a decade, a friendly face and
message painted on the side of Joe and Gertrude Carpenter's white
barn has graced the quiet Wood County landscape and greeted
travelers.
   It has served as a landmark and way station, of sorts, for
motorists seeking directions or shelter from driving snowstorms.
   The barn needs painting now, said Carpenter, a 75-year-old
retired farmer. But when the new coat's on this summer, he's going
to have the smiling face, the friendly ``Hi!'' and the words Joe
and Gertie repainted on the side of the barn.
   After all, the message is a sign of love for his wife, who died
last year after a long illness.
   ``Everytime I look at it, I think of the old memories and the
people who stopped and admired it,'' he said.
   ``We were married 51 years. It's a loss. We did everything and
went everyplace together,'' Carpenter said. ``I miss her every
day.''
   The 18-foot-wide smiling face is visible from Interstate 75 and
Ohio 582, which runs from Haskins to Woodville in northwestern
Ohio. Carpenter's place is about 20 miles south of Toledo.
   The face on the barn was his wife's idea. Mrs. Carpenter, known
as Gertie, decided the face would be a fun gift to give her husband
to celebrate their 41st wedding anniversary in 1976. A year later,
a sign painter added the names Joe and Gertie.
   ``People laughed when they first saw it. But it has become a
local landmark,'' he said.
   The barnyard greeting has often been photographed and has become
a point of reference when local folks give directions. Curious
motorists often visit the Carpenter farm to hear the story of the
anniversary gift.
   ``People stop and say they want to meet Joe and Gertie. They ask
about the face. They say looking at it makes their day. We've
gotten a lot of enjoyment out of it over the years,'' Carpenter
said. ``People tell me, `Don't ever take that face off the barn.' ''
   He said his wife was a trusting person who opened the house to
stranded motorists.
   During a 1978 blizzard, he said, 14 people spent the night in
the Carpenter home.
   ``I remember that like it was yesterday. All these people
couldn't go any place because the highway was closed. It was either
spend the night here or in their cars,'' he said. ``Then she got up
in the morning and cooked breakfast for everybody.''
   She also had a keen sense of humor.
   For some years, two mannequins sat on the front porch of the
Carpenter home. Sometimes, the mannequins sat there like a young
couple courting. Mrs. Carpenter, he said, changed their clothing
with the seasons.
   Motorists did double takes as they passed the porch. But when
Gertie sold one of the mannequins, the courtship was over.
   These days, Carpenter spends most of his time making wooden
clocks and ornaments. Two of his three children live nearby.
   A few years ago, the couple designed their headstone _ a
detailed scene of the Carpenter farm with the house, mailbox and
barn with the smiling face. It also has the friendly ``Hi!'' from
Joe and Gertie etched in stone.
   ``She knew what it would look like, but she died before she saw
it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   05-17 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld - Writethru,f0265,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Reach New High; Dollar Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices reached a new high Tuesday following
the overnight advance on Wall Street, while the dollar rose
slightly against the Japanese yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues closed at 27,819.98, up 60.11 points, or 0.21
percent, from its previous high reached the previous day, when it
gained a sharp 291.56 points.
   ``The stock market was boosted by overnight gains on Wall
Street, where the Dow Jones Industrial Average went over the
2,000-dollar level,'' said Hiromi Yoneyama of Wako Securities.
   But investors wary of the market's rapid rise later sold shares
to cash in their recent gains, pulling stock prices back moderately
at the end of the morning session, Yoneyama added.
   The Nikkei Index had risen 197.17 points in the first 15 minutes
of trading.
   Stock prices also rose on expectations that U.S. trade figures
for March, scheduled to be announced in Washington later Tuesday,
would show a moderate narrowing in the U.S. trade deficit, traders
said.
   The dollar closed the day at 124.82, up 0.09 yen from Monday's
finish. It had opened the day higher at 124.89 and remained little
changed, hovering around 124.75-124.93 yen level.
   Michiko Kawai of the Bank of Tokyo said, ``The dollar was higher
in Tokyo following the overnight rise against the yen in New York.''
   But trading was scattered as participants stayed on the
sidelines in anticipation of the U.S. trade report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i Philippines-Foreigners     05-17 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Philippines-Foreigners,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Under Fire In Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign reporters, once lauded for
their role in the ouster of President Ferdinand Marcos, have gone
from heroes to heels for alleged unflattering coverage of Corazon
Aquino's Philippines.
   In recent weeks, Philippine columnists and government officials
have accused the foreign press of scaring off foreign investors,
depicting Manila as a decadent, crime-ridden slum and even paying
communist rebels to stage ambushes.
   The foreign ``press-bashing'' is a far cry from the adulation
heaped on the international press for its coverage of the
anti-Marcos movement.
   Many Filipinos believed the presence of so many foreign
reporters was responsible for Marcos' tame response to the February
1986 uprising which brought his downfall.
   A year after Marcos' ouster, a private group with government
backing even awarded certificates to foreign reporters who covered
the 1986 uprising, identifying them as ``heroes of the revolution.''
   Philippine media have themselves been sharply critical of Mrs.
Aquino's stewardship as the country grapples with such problems as
the communist insurgency, widespread poverty, inefficient
bureaucracy, deteriorating roads and bridges and a burgeoning
population.
   But the renewed sense of national pride that followed the Marcos
downfall also has shortened the patience of many Filipinos for
criticism by foreigners.
   A former communist rebel, Gemma Magallona, was quoted as saying
unidentified foreign reporters paid her group to stage an ambush in
southeastern Luzon and even provided weapons and ammunition.
   The report, published in the Philippine Daily Inquirer last
week, drew little response until Defense Secretary Fidel V. Ramos
said in a television interview Thursday that the military had
evidence the journalists were from a European television network.
   Later, the military identified the crew as from the British
Broadcasting Corp. The BBC in London denied the allegation and said
it had no crew in the country at the time of the ambush.
   It appeared the charge may have been raised to frighten foreign
reporters from contacts with the rebels and from visiting their
camps.
   The military has offered no evidence beyond the woman's
allegation. But opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, a former defense
minister, claimed the military had extensive files proving that
foreign reporters often paid rebels to stage attacks in exchange
for scoops.
   ``These foreign journalists go to the enemies of the government
and ask them to ambush soldiers so they can show to the world that
the country is in a state of turmoil,'' Enrile claimed.
   Sen. Ernesto Herrera called for curbs on the foreign press if
the former rebel's allegation was true.
   The immigration chief today said foreign journalists who pay
communist rebels to stage ambushes against government forces can be
deported.
   ``If there is sufficent evidence against the aliens, and the
reports can be verified, then, that would constitute a deportable
offense under the immigration act,'' Immigration Commissioner
Miriam Defensor-Santiago told reporters.
   Mrs. Aquino's spokesman Teodoro Benigno, a former bureau chief
of the French news agency Agence France-Presse, said the government
would look into the allegation about the BBC.
   But when pressed for comment, Benigno told Filipino reporters:
``You are journalists yourselves. Do you believe that thing really
happened?''
   The Foreign Correspondent's Association of the Philippines has
so far issued no statement on the charge, only the latest in a
series of allegations against the international media.
   Last week, Benigno's office claimed foreign reporters had
painted a distorted picture of Manila as a crime-ridden city by
reports on killings by communist rebels.
   The presidential press office released figures which showed
Manila with a lower crime rate than Hong Kong, Tokyo and New York.
   Filipino critics claim foreign press reports, which often focus
on the communist insurgency, coup attempts and political turmoil,
have distorted the image of the country and frightened off foreign
investors.
   ``The cumulative effect of such garbage that has lately been
featured in some sectors of the U.S. press could not be lost on the
American reader, who knows less and less of the real Philippines
and her people and more of the seamy side as viewed from the
gutter,'' wrote columnist Hernando Abaya in The Manila Chronicle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Foreigners     05-17 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Foreigners,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Under Fire In Philippines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore cycle designator.
