<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0501EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0471 05-17 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs to add 5 new grafs after 5th graf pvs, bgng ``We, the
... with Jackson comments at late evening rally; picks up 6th graf
pvs, Earlier Monday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COOS BAY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson was still seeking support in today's Oregon primary _ even
as voters were going to the polls.
   Jackson also made a primary-eve swing through the state, telling
an enthusiastic waterfront rally of about 1,000 people here that
they must fight to change the Reagan administration's economic
policies.
   Jackson noted that today's primary comes on the 34th anniversary
of Brown vs. Board of Education, the 1954 U.S. Supreme Court
decision that legally ended racial segregation in schools.
   Jackson said that back then, Democrats were working to ``end
racial violence by law.'' Now, he said, that has turned to a
struggle to ``end economic violence by law.''
   ``We, the people, must come together to fight for economic
justice in this country,'' Jackson said.
   At a late-evening rally of 2,500 people at Portland State
University, Jackson said neither Republican nominee-apparent George
Bush nor Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis have offered plans
to back up their campaign promises.
   ``Let Mr. Bush and Mr. Dukakis state their case,'' Jackson said.
``If they have a better plan, let them come forward.''
   He urged voters to go to the polls by telling them, ``Oregon
determines the course of our party, of our nation, of our world.''
   Jackson also said plans are being made for meetings after the
primary season, and before the party's national convention, with
constituent groups, including Jewish leaders in New York City.
   The meetings were among the items Jackson discussed with New
York Gov. Mario Cuomo while the two were on the West Coast late
last week, Jackson said.
   Earlier Monday, at his first stop in Oregon, he spoke of
environmental matters that are of concern here.
   At an airport rally that drew about 300 people in Eugene,
Jackson said the nation needs a timber industry that will ``nurture
the forests, not cut old-growth.''
   ``The greedy amongst us are attacking the environment,'' he
said. ``We the people live in one world community. We must clean up
the world.''
   Jackson, wearing a red-checked lumberman's jacket and wide red
suspenders, was looking ahead to the weeks remaining in the primary
season.
   ``I want to win in Oregon on tomorrow and take that momentum to
California,'' he said.
   He planned an airport rally today in Klamath Falls before
leaving for San Diego.
   On Monday, Jackson reiterated his appeal for what he called
fairness from the Democratic Party. He said he deserved credit for
``registering more Democrats than anybody else in history.''
   ``We're not discussing generosity. We're discussing
reciprocity,'' Jackson said as he campaigned in New Jersey.
   The Democratic presidential contender criticized party rules,
saying it is unfair that his delegate total is not in line with his
share of the popular vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BusCrash Bjt   05-17 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash, Bjt,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fuel Tank Didn't Meet Safety Regs; Pickup Driver Charged With
Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fuel tank of a bus that burst into a
fireball when a pickup truck slammed into it head-on didn't meet
federal safety requirements, investigators said after the truck's
driver was charged with 27 counts of murder.
   At the time of the accident, one of the nation's deadliest bus
crashes, truck driver Larry Mahoney's blood-alcohol level was
nearly 2{ times the legal definition of drunkenness, authorities
said Monday.
   John Ackman, Carroll County commonwealth's attorney, said he
planned to seek the death penalty against Mahoney, 34, who was in
serious condition at Humana Hospital-University of Illinois.
   Mahoney's northbound truck was traveling in the wrong direction
on Interstate 71 when it struck the church bus filled with
teen-agers and adult chaperones returning from an amusement park
near Cincinnati.
   Twenty-seven people were killed and 42 injured. The victims died
from smoke inhalation as they tried to scramble out of the burning
bus, said state medical examiner Dr. George Nichols. Seventeen
people remain hospitalized, most in critical or serious condition.
   The former school bus used by the First Assembly of God Church
in Radcliff did not meet post-1977 safety requirements for a caged
fuel tank, said Joseph Nall, a National Transportation Safety Board
investigator.
   The tank had a 3-inch gash and was pushed back 26 inches by the
crash's impact, Nall said Monday night.
   Asked if a caged tank might have prevented the fire, Nall said,
``That's the ultimate question we'd like to answer, but now it
would be premature.''
   The 1977 Superior bus with a Ford chassis, which the
manufacturer said was equipped to carry 66 passengers and a driver
_ the number aboard the night of the crash _ did not appear to be
overloaded, according to Nall.
   Some survivors said the seats that were supposed to hold three
people were too small, resulting in some people hanging in the
aisle.
   ``There were too many people on that bus,'' said Conrad Garcia.
He said he had to sit on a girl's lap in the back row because the
bench wasn't wide enough.
   NTSB investigators will remain in Kentucky for several more
days, and it could take up to 10 months before a final report is
released, Nall said.
   Investigators on Monday examined the accident site, about 45
miles northeast of Louisville, and noted some braking by both
drivers before the accident, Nall said.
   Only two survivors were interviewed as of Monday night, but more
interviews of witnesses were planned, Nall said.
   Federal investigators attempted to interview Mahoney on Monday,
but ``he would not talk to investigators for reasons of his own,''
Nall said.
   Mahoney, who was served with warrants in his hospital room, will
be arraigned once he is released. District Judge Stanley
Billingsley denied bond.
   Tests on Mahoney, of Worthville, found a 0.24 blood alcohol
level, said state police Capt. Neal Brittain. State law defines
intoxication at 0.1.
   Mahoney had a drunken driving arrest in 1984, for which he paid
a fine, and pleaded guilty twice to disorderly conduct, court
records show.
   He was twice divorced and has been living with his first wife.
He has two children.
   A friend, Dennis Mefford, said he was with Mahoney until 8:30
p.m. Saturday, about 2{ hours before the accident. Mahoney was very
tired, he said.
   Mahoney, a chemical operator at M&T Chemical Co. in Carrollton,
had worked 12-hour shifts for three consecutive days before getting
off at 7 a.m. the day of the accident, Nall said.
   ``I can't remember seeing him drive in that bad a shape,''
Mefford said.
   Friends described Mahoney as a quiet man who likes to hunt and
shoot pool.
   ``He was just an easy-going, good ol' country boy,'' said
Mefford's wife, Linda. ``He was a little backward _ shy and
quiet-spoken. But people should know that he wasn't some kind of
wild maniac.''
   Flags were at half-staff Monday in Radcliff and sympathies were
spelled out on marquees and display signs at businesses and
restaurants in the main business district.
   Among those killed were Army 1st Sgt. Lee Williams' wife, Joy,
and two daughters.
   ``He has no one else,'' said Jean Grimes, Joy Williams'
identical twin. ``Joy and the kids were all he had.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
