<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-17 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo's key stock market indicator reached a new
record high today for the second consecutive trading day, while the
U.S. dollar finished slightly higher against the Japanese yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
added 60.11 points, or 0.21 percent, to close the day at 27,819,98.
The index's prvious high was reached Monday, when it closed at
27,759.87, gaining a sharp 291.56 points.
   ``Apprehension over the market rising too quicky prompted
profit-taking, holding share prices back,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama
of Nikko Securities.
   During the first 15 minutes of trading, the Nikkei Index rose
almost across the board, surging 197.17 points, or 0.71 percent, to
27,957.04, mirroring the overnight advance on Wall Street, traders
said.
   Shimoyama said share prices picked up again just before the end
of trading, boosted in part on expectations that the U.S. trade
figures for March, due to be announced later today in Washington,
will show a moderate narrowing in the deficit.
   Popular issues included non-ferrous issues and oils.
Transportations, trading houses, automobiles were also higher.
Among the losers were constructions and housings.
   Trading was moderately active with volume on the first section
estimated at 1 billion shares, up from 850 million shares changed
hands on Monday.
   On the foreign exchange dealings, the dollar closed at 124.82
yen, up 0.09 yen from its finish on Monday. It had opened the day
at 124.89 yen and traded in a range of 124.75 yen to 124.93 yen.
   ``Trading was scattered throughout the day without any
directions to move the market,'' said a dealer at a major
commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Participants stayed away from making moves, waiting for the U.S.
trade figures for March, he said.
</TEXT>
