<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     05-17 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Plans to Challenge Mecham's Convention Credentials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Georgia congressman reportedly plans to
challenge ex-Gov. Evan Mecham's credentials as a delegate to the
Republican national convention.
   The Arizona GOP convention on Saturday elected Mecham, who was
impeached and removed from office, as one of the state's 33
delegates to the convention in New Orleans in August. Mecham came
in 17th in the secret balloting for 18 at-large seats.
   Mecham was removed from office April 4 when the state Senate
convicted him of two impeachment charges. He still faces trial in
criminal court on unrelated felony charges.
   The Arizona Daily Star in Tucson reported Monday that three
sources said Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., decided even before
Saturday to challenge Mecham's convention credentials if he became
a delegate.
   Neither Gingrich nor his spokeswoman in Washington returned a
telephone call seeking comment Monday.
   Mecham said he didn't believe Gingrich was familiar with the
situation in Arizona. ``We've got enough problems here in Arizona,
what with Republicans tearing apart Republicans,'' Mecham told the
Star on Sunday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Questions W.Va. Primary Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOGAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's campaign is questioning what
it says are more than 1,000 supporters missing from voter
registration lists in Logan County, W. Va.
   At the same time, the presidential candidate's campaign is
considering challenging the state's system of ignoring the popular
vote when it comes to convention delegate selection.
   Lewis Carter, a Jackson field aide, said Monday that voters who
registered during Jackson-inspired registration drives since 1986
were missing from Logan County voter registration lists.
   Carter said he has asked Jackson state campaign coordinators to
review the presidential candidate's vote totals in the southern
coalfield county.
   Secretary of State Ken Hechler said he did not think there was
anything to support Carter's allegations.
   Carter also said he thinks the state's system of selecting
Democratic convention delegates is unfair, a charge Jackson has
made of several states. Results from the presidential primary in
West Virginia have no effect on the selection of delegates, who are
voted on separately.
   Jackson captured 14 percent of the popular vote, but won no
delegates here.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Democrats Land the Aquarians While More Libras Lean to GOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aquarians tend to consider themselves Democrats
and Libras are more likely than others to lean toward the
Republican Party _ but don't tell the plurality of Americans who
reject astrology.
   The latest entry in the political debate over the influence of
the stars comes courtesy of Public Opinion magazine, a bimonthly
publication of the American Enterprise Institute for Public Policy
Research in Washington.
   Picking up on the discussion fomented by allegations that
astrology has played a role in President Reagan's schedule, Public
Opinion compiled data from past polls including these tidbits:
   _Democrats drew 47 percent of Aquarians but just 32 percent of
Libras in surveys done from 1985-87 by the National Opinion
Research Center.
   _Another 32 percent of Libras considered themselves Republicans,
but only 28 percent of Aquarians and just 25 percent of
Sagittarians backed the GOP.
   _Their sign aside, 47 percent of adults polled by the Roper
Organization in 1985 said they did not believe in astrology. Thirty
percent weren't sure, while 23 percent believed in the influence of
the stars.
   Public Opinion figured the breakdown of party identification
according to astrological sign by separating the Democrats,
Republicans and independents by birth date.
   Graham Hueber, assistant editor of Public Opinion, said the
survey was done ``because we never miss an opportunity to get
Public Opinion magazine's name in the press.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
