<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MudDumping     05-17 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mud Dumping,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fishermen Dump Ton of Fish to Protest Oakland Dredging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ton of fish heads was dumped here by
fishermen to protest the unloading of Oakland estuary mud in the
ocean off the San Mateo County coast.
   ``They're dumping on us, so we figured it wouldn't hurt to dump
on them,'' said Don Pemberton, owner of Pemberton's Fish Co. near
Half Moon Bay.
   The fish heads were dumped at a Port of Oakland marine terminal
on Monday, the day a San Mateo County judge halted a dredging
project the fishermen say will destroy rich fishing grounds.
   Workers spent several hours cleaning up a 4-foot-high
``pyramid'' of fish heads.
   Pemberton said he and another fisherman, Marcellino Costilino,
39, loaded the 2,000 pounds of fish on his flat bed truck near Half
Moon Bay.
   The Superior Court restraining order was in response to a
lawsuit filed Friday by San Mateo County against the port and the
California Coastal Commission. County officials alleged the
commission should have reviewed the dump site 12 miles west of Half
Moon Bay to make sure it conformed with the state's coastal use
plan.
   The judge's order blocks dumping until the case can be argued at
a hearing May 27.
   ``We have been given a chance to live,'' fishermen Steve Fitz
said of the judge's order.
   Fitz is the co-owner of the boat Ronny, one of 18 trawlers that
attempted without success to block the first barge full of material
from being dumped last Friday.
   Port of Oakland officials want to deepen the estuary to make way
for huge container ships by eventually hauling away 500,000 cubic
yards of sediment.
   ``What you're talking about is the whole viability of the Port
of Oakland,'' said port Executive Director Walter A. Abernathy.
``We are surrounded by competing ports in Southern California and
the Pacific Northwest that have deeper channels and can accommodate
these larger new ships.''
</TEXT>
