<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonRiot     05-17 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Riot,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Hostage Describes Inmate Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRINGTOWN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of eight guards taken hostage in a
2{-day prison siege says his heart ``skipped a beat'' when inmates
pressed a knife to his throat, and he may not go back to work
because of the ordeal.
   ``I made it through Vietnam, and I almost got killed in my own
hometown,'' said Corrections officer Ron Scott, who was released as
the insurrection ended Monday morning. ``I'm just glad I'm alive.
I'm going to try to live one day at a time.''
   Prison officials today investigated the riot and assessed damage
at the medium-security Mack Alford Correctional Center. Authorities
said it could cost as much as $5 million to replace a 160-bed
dormitory burned down during the riot.
   State lawmakers, who said the inmates should live with the
problem they created, vowed to take their time in rebuilding. Nine
inmates believed to be directly involved in the hostage-taking were
moved to the Lexington Assessment and Reception Center in Lexington.
   Scott, 36, and Sgt. Harold Yoder were held the longest of eight
guards who were taken captive by knife-wielding inmates late Friday.
   Scott said he was attending a briefing before taking his
position in a guard tower when the riot began.
   One guard was taken hostage as authorities attempted to round up
three inmates for discipline following a fight over a theft earlier
in the day.
   ``They wanted us to go out there and see what could be done
about it,'' Scott said.
   When inmates went on a rampage, Scott and six other officers
barricaded themselves inside the dormitory by putting a filing
cabinet against a metal door while inmates outside pushed against
it. Inmates got in through a side door.
   ``Before I knew it, several inmates came in with knives,'' Scott
said.
   The captive guards were moved in a line to another building.
Scott said he saw the first captured guard sitting with his hands
tied behind him and wearing inmate clothing.
   During the next several hours all but three of the guards were
released, but the inmates threatened Scott's life to persuade
negotiators to provide them with food.
   ``They had me down on my knees and they had the knife at my
throat,'' Scott said. ``At those times, my heart kind of skipped a
beat. My hands got a little sweaty.''
   A knife was held to his throat on two other occasions, once when
inmates feared that snipers waited on an adjacent building.
   Scott, a Choctaw Indian, said he feared for himself and fellow
captive Capt. Lewis McGee, a black man who was released about 10
p.m. Sunday. Inmates had displayed ``White Power'' signs from the
building they held. Yoder is white.
   ``If there was anybody who was going to get killed, it was going
to be us two,'' Scott said.
   Scott said his captors generally treated him well, offering him
food and providing fans to ward off heat and humidity. Temperatures
were in the 90s.
   Scott said he has not decided whether to return to his job at
the prison.
   ``I'll just have to sit and think about it a couple of days _
take a week off,'' he said.
</TEXT>
