<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ElectionsRdp     05-17 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elections Rdp,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters to Decide Fate of Proposed Denver Airport, Oregon Helmet
Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in suburban Denver will decide today whether the city can
build a new airport to replace crowded Stapleton International. In
Portland, Ore., Mayor Bud Clark was favored in his bid for a second
term, while voters statewide considered a mandatory motorcycle
helmet law.
   Backers have outspent opponents heavily in the campaign for a $3
billion replacement for Stapleton.
   Officials say that if Adams County voters approve the ballot
question _ whether to allow Denver to annex an unincorporated
45-square-mile site in their county _ it will virtually ensure that
the airport can be built.
   In Portland, Clark, the city's colorful barkeeper-turned-mayor,
has weathered the storms of his first term so well that he is given
a chance of winning a second term outright in the non-partisan
election and avoiding a November runoff. He has 10 challengers on
the ballot.
   His campaign focused on getting more than 50 percent today. A
poll published Sunday gave him 51 percent, with a 4.9 point margin
of error.
   Clark shocked the city four years ago when he stepped out of his
popular Goose Hollow Inn and mounted a grass-roots campaign to
unseat incumbent Frank Ivancie.
   In his first two years in office, however, Clark faced a series
of crises, mostly involving the city Police Bureau. Two police
chiefs resigned and Clark fired a third.
   Oregonians also voted on a proposal for a mandatory motorcycle
helmet law for adults. The current law applies only to those under
age 18.
   The measure would require drivers and passengers of motorcycles
and mopeds to wear protective headgear or face a $100 fine.
   Oregon congressional primaries are also being held. Four of the
five incumbents face no primary opposition. The fifth, Democratic
Rep. Ron Wyden, faces only a nominal challenge.
   The airport at Denver is the first major one planned in the
United States since Dallas-Fort Worth opened in 1974.
   Opponents contend jet noise generated by the airport would be
unbearable for homeowners, and say closing Stapleton would waste
money. Proponents, including Gov. Roy Romer, point to a study that
predicts a new airport would generate 54,000 jobs by 2010.
</TEXT>
