<DOCNO> AP880517-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Ozone     05-17 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Ozone,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet, U.S. Scientists To Investigate Hole In Ozone Layer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and American aircraft will make a series of
flights through a large hole in the Earth's protective ozone layer
next year so scientists can study whether there are harmful changes
in the world's climate.
   The two nations announced Monday that they have agreed to
coordinate the experimental flights over the Arctic in January and
February.
   S.G. Tilford, director of NASA's Earth science and application
division, told reporters the Soviets and Americans probably will
use separate aircraft for the experiment. But the two groups of
scientists and pilots will share information and coordinate flight
schedules.
   The mission was announced at a Moscow news conference by
American scientists from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and Soviet representatives from this country's
Academy of Sciences.
   Tilford said he hopes 10 to 20 flights can be made through the
ozone layer to collect data.
   Tilford said the aircraft have an altitude limit of 12{ miles,
but scientists estimate that the hole in the ozone layer extends to
31 miles.
   He said the U.S. scientists and pilots hope to be based
somewhere in Norway. It was undecided where the Soviets will be
based, he said, but ``we'll be in close touch, coordinating
schedules and flights.''
   Ozone in the atmosphere filters out the sun's ultraviolent rays,
making life on Earth possible.
   A NASA report in March said the ozone layer over the United
States has shrunk by about 2.3 percent since 1969. The report put
the blame on chlorofluorocarbons, chemicals used to power some
aerosol sprays.
   They were banned as aerosol propellants in the United States in
1978. But they continue to be used to clean computer chips and
other electronic parts, as refrigeration fluids and for making
plastic foams.
   The Environmental Protection Agency has estimated that a 1
percent thinning of the Earth's ozone shield means a 5 percent to 6
percent increase in skin cancer. If chlorofluorocarbon use
continued increasing at 2.5 percent per year, EPA said, 20 percent
of the ozone barrier could be gone in the next century.
   The Soviet Union has several chlorofluorocarbon plants under
construction and has won several temporary exemptions to a
31-nation treaty cutting emissions that damage the ozone layer.
   Academy of Sciences spokesman K. Kondratyev said scientists
differ on the effects of ozone depletion, but generally believe it
causes an increase in the Earth's temperature, leading to
deforestation in tropical areas, reduction in atmospheric moisture
and, eventually, deterioration of the Earth's soil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
