<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Angola     05-17 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Angola,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Says Cuban Troop Movement Threatening Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Magnus Malan
said that reported Cuban troop deployment in southern Angola is a
threat to further negotiations on regional peace.
   Angola's Marxist government is supported by an estimated 40,000
Cuban troops in its 13-year fight against UNITA _ the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola. South Africa and the
United States back UNITA.
   In remarks before Parliament on Monday, Malan cautioned against
a quick solution to the Angolan conflict.
   ``I am not optimistic that negotiations will be easy or that
they will succeed soon,'' Malan said.
   Malan was part of the South African delegation that met with
Angolan officials in Brazzaville, Congo, Friday to discuss ways of
ending Angola's civil war.
   He said that up to 9,000 Cuban troops recently have been
deployed in southern Angola near the border of South-West Africa,
the territory administered by South Africa.
   ``The Cubans are exceeding their mandate in Angola,'' Malan
said. ``They were not brought there, invited or sent there to form
a shield for SWAPO,'' the guerrilla group seeking independence in
South-West Africa.
   SWAPO, or South-West African People's Organization, has bases in
southern Angola from which it launches attacks into South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia. South Africa says it will not grant
Namibia independence until Cuban troops leave Angola.
   Malan said if the Cuban troops assist SWAPO ``this could be the
spark that starts the fire.''
   South Africa and Angola have said they plan to arrange a new
round of talks shortly. However, Malan and other leading South
African officials repeatedly have stated that no major
breakthroughs appear imminent.
   In Portugal, a U.S. Embassy official said on Monday that top
U.S. and Soviet negotiators on southern Africa will meet in Lisbon
this week to discuss the civil war in Angola and South Africa's
control of Namibia.
   Chester Crocker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state for
African affairs, and Anatoly Adamishin, a Soviet deputy foreign
minister, will open the talks Wednesday, embassy spokeswoman Susan
Clyde said. She said only Soviet and U.S. officials are expected to
take part in the talks.
   Crocker and Adamishin have met several times recently to discuss
ways of ending the conflicts in southern Africa.
   Also Monday, Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos said
Angola accepted the principle of a gradual withdrawal of the Cuban
military personnel from his country.
   In an interview with the official Angolan news agency ANGOP, dos
Santos said the United States is refusing to recognize Angola
diplomatically until the Cubans have left. He said that position
was ``absurd'' and ``without any logical explanation.''
   The ANGOP report, monitored in Lisbon, quoted dos Santos as
saying Namibian independence and the end of the Angolan war would
be decisive steps toward peace in southern Africa and the abolition
of racial segregation in South Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
