<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-17 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stormy Weather in the South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell from South Carolina to
New England today after strong storms in Dixie killed two men,
flattened buildings and knocked out power to thousands of people.
   Temperatures dipped into the 30s and 40s in the upper
Mississippi Valley and the upper Great Lakes this morning, and a
frost advisory was issued for northern Wisconsin.
   However, on Monday high-temperature records up to 95 years old
were broken in nine cities and tied in three, mostly in the West.
   The showers and thunderstorms which wreaked havoc in the South
on Monday afternoon and evening were abating today. Widely
scattered showers and thundershowers also lingered from the
southern High Plains to California.
   Fair weather prevailed across the central third of the country,
but brisk winds prevailed in the northern Plains.
   During Monday's storms, lightning struck a flag held by a
19-year-old University of Georgia freshman playing golf on the
Athens campus, killing him, officials said.
   Just east of Atlanta, a construction worker was killed and his
injured brother had to be rescued when high winds flattened the
two-story apartment building where they were working, authorities
said. Three others walked out of the demolished structure unharmed.
   The five men had moved into the building's breezeway for shelter
when they saw the storm heading their way, said DeKalb County Fire
Chief Thomas Brown. ``The building came down in what we call
pancake fashion, straight down on them,'' Brown said.
   In South Carolina, the storm produced winds reaching 63 mph that
flipped a mobile home in Santee, blew down a garage near
Chesterfield and downed large trees and power lines.
   In North Carolina, the storm knocked out power to nearly 4,000
people, utility officials said, and downed trees.
   Hail as big as golf balls fell in the Carolinas.
   In the West, a thunderstorm in northwestern Montana spawned a
tornado near Shelby. No injuries or damage were reported. A cold
front moving through eastern Oregon generated gusts up to 65 mph.
   Temperature records set Monday included a reading of 91 degrees
in Helena, Mont., where the old mark of 87 degrees was set in 1893.
Records in the high 80s or 90s were also set in Denver, the Montana
cities of Billings, Havre and Great Falls and Casper and Lander,
Wyo.
   It was a record 93 degrees in Fort Smith, Ark. Records were tied
in New Orleans, Scottsbluff, Neb.; and Worland, Wyo.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from New
York and New England to the middle and south Atlantic states and
Mississippi, and in parts of the northern and central Rockies, with
a few showers in the Pacific Northwest and windy conditions
prevailing from Idaho to the northern Rockies and the northern and
central Plains.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 70s or 80s over
most of the nation; 90 degrees in parts of South Carolina and
coastal sections of Alabama and Mississippi; 90s to around 100
degrees from southwest Texas to the desert Southwest; 50s or 60s
from the northern Rockies to the Pacific Northwest and northern and
coastal sections of California and from northern Minnesota to the
Great Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley and much of New England.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Sawyer Air Force Base in Marquette, Mich., to 86 degrees
at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 66 fair; Boston 54 foggy; Buffalo 53 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 66 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 50
foggy; Detroit 50 cloudy; Miami 73 cloudy; New York 58 foggy;
Philadelphia 61 cloudy; Pittsburgh 62 fair; Portland, Maine 50
drizzle; Washington 66 showers.
   _Central: Bismarck 58 fair; Chicago 47 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
72 fair; Denver 68 fair; Des Moines 48 fair; Indianapolis 51 partly
cloudy; Kansas City 59 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 44 fair;
Nashville 66 fair; New Orleans 72 hazy; St. Louis 56 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 64 partly cloudy; Anchorage 50 cloudy; Las
Vegas 81 windy; Los Angeles 57 partly cloudy; Phoenix 88 fair; Salt
Lake City 71 partly cloudy; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 53
windy; Seattle 50 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 showers.
</TEXT>
