<HEAD>Rebel Clashes Claim 25 Lives In Five Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Philippines-Foreigners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 5 more deaths reported
today, total of 27 over last five days. Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Col.
Enrique...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 communist rebels, some
shooting flaming arrows, raided a government outpost in the
northern Philippines in a clash that left 13 people dead, the
military said today.
   In the Bicol peninsula on the southern tip of Luzon island,
soldiers killed five guerrillas and wounded two in two separate
military offensives late Monday and early today, a military report
said.
   The reported deaths brought to at least 27 the number of people
killed in clashes with rebels during the last five days.
   The military said the rebel attack took place in the Mountain
Province town of Paracelis, 190 miles north of Manila.
   Col. Enrique Pilapil, regional constabulary commander, said
outnumbered soldiers at the outpost repulsed the attack on Sunday
by about 150 communist New People's Army rebels, killing eight
guerrillas during a six-hour gunbattle.
   Pilapil said five defenders were killed and five were wounded.
He added that the rebels fired flaming arrows at the detachment
before retreating.
   In another clash, troops backed by anti-communist vigilantes
repelled an attack by communist rebels Saturday, killing five
insurgents and wounding 12 in Makilala in North Cotabato, 600 miles
south of Manila on Mindanao island.
   On Panay island, 40 rebels ambushed a government patrol Friday
in the town of Leon, 285 miles southeast of Manila, killing four
militiamen. The military report did not say whether there were
casualties on the rebel side.
