<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea     05-17 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Korean Students Battle Riot Police For Second Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of radical students yelling
anti-government and anti-American slogans battled police with rocks
and firebombs in six cities today to mark a 1980 uprising.
   Waves of students hurling firebombs, rocks and bricks fought
riot police around college campuses in Seoul and the provincial
cities of Kwangju, Taejon, Chongju, Pusan and Chonju.
   Yonhap, the Korean news agency, reported that 22,000 students at
58 colleges took part in confrontations and peaceful protests, but
did not give a breakdown. News reports estimated 9,000 students
participated in the unrest that started Monday in Seoul and other
cities.
   ``Down with the military dictatorship,'' ``Yankee go home'' and
``Down with the murder regime,'' the students shouted in the
running clashes.
   Hundreds of riot police in green combat fatigues, black metal
helmets and gas masks fired volleys of choking tear gas to drive
protesters back. Armored vans with multiple tear gas launchers
fired salvos of tear gas bombs as martial arts squads charged
protesters.
   At least two students were injured in fighting at seven college
campuses in Seoul, but police declined to give any overall figures.
Several police officers were hit by firebombs.
   The clashes occurred on the eve of the anniversary of the May
18, 1980 anti-government uprising in Kwangju, where at least 191
people died in a suppression led by the military.
   Radical students and dissidents contend the death toll was in
the hundreds and demand that President Roh Tae-woo and other top
leaders, who were military commanders at the time, be punished for
suppressing the rebellion.
   About 4,000 students held a large rally today at Chonnam
University in Kwangju and then fought with riot police when the
students attempted to march off campus. Student leaders vowed to
hold daily protests for a week in Kwangju, 165 miles southwest of
Seoul.
   ``Punish culprit Roh Tae-woo,'' the students shouted.
   National police were on general alert because of the protests.
Security was increased in Seoul with riot police detachments
guarding key buildings and college campuses.
   Protesters chanted anti-American slogans because of their claims
the United States has supported military rule in South Korea. An
estimated 40,000 U.S. troops are based in South Korea under a
defense pact.
   Students burned effigies of Roh and the United States at Seoul
National University in Seoul. Protesters in Kwangju marched with a
large sign showing a broken American flag.
   ``Go home Yankees who supported the chief culprits in the
Kwangju massacre,'' students chanted.
   Roh, who took power Feb. 25 after winning election in December,
has promised to introduce full democracy and has ended many of the
authoritarian polices of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   But many Koreans are distrustful of the former general. Radical
students and dissidents still mount protests against the government
and demand a full accounting of the Kwangju revolt.
   Students and residents seized control of Kwangju in 1980 during
anti-government demonstrations shortly after Chun and the military
seized power. The military moved in combat units and crushed the
revolt, leaving a legacy that traumatized Korean society.
   In another development today, the trial of a former police
officer charged with sexually torturing a female dissident in 1986
was interrupted at least 20 times in 90 minutes.
   About 150 people repeatedly disrupted the trial in Inchon, a
port city west of Seoul, of Moon Kwi-dong. They threw eggs and
shouted insults and anti-government slogans. A pair of scissors was
seized from a woman who said she wanted to attack Moon.
</TEXT>
