<HEAD>Squatters Dispersed By Police After Rent Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 6th graf pvs, ``Authorities
decided...'' to UPDATE with strike violence. Picksup 7th graf pvs,
``In another...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas and
birdshot to disperse black squatters who have been protesting a
decision to charge them rent for their shacks, authorities said
today.
   Officers used tear gas against a group of black protesters who
gathered Monday at the Weiler's Farm Shantytown, then later used
birdshot to disperse blacks who threw stones at buses and taxis,
police said.
   The Sowetan, a black-oriented newspaper, said thousands of
Weiler's Farm residents stayed away from work Monday to protest the
imposition of a $17 monthly rent. Many of them earn less than $50
per month.
   The Sowetan said a female protester was arrested and a man was
hospitalized after he was bitten by a police dog.
   Weiler's Farm is designated as an temporary squatter camp.
Whites in the area, 25 miles south of Johannesburg, have complained
about the settlement, and its estimated 7,000 residents are
scheduled to be moved later this year.
   Authorities decided in March to begin charging rent. Community
leaders say a lower rent might be acceptable, but the Transvaal
Province Administration contends that it must charge the $17
monthly to cover the cost of services.
   In an unrelated clash Monday, at least five black workers were
injured when police fired rubber bullets and tear gas at strikers
trying to stop delivery trucks from leaving a Coca Cola bottling
plant in Durban, union officials said. Police reported six injuries
and said strikers had thrown chairs at the trucks.
   The Food and Allied Workers Union says 2,500 workers are
striking against Amalgamated Beverage Industries at five plants to
protest alleged unfair labor practices. The stoppage began in
Durban two weeks ago. No other details were available.
   In another incident, police said three black men were stabbed to
death by black youths on Monday in Natal province.
   This followed five killings in the area Sunday, and indicated a
possible escalation of feuding between militant anti-apartheid
factions and the more moderate Inkatha, the Natal-based political
organization of Zulu chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi. Buthelezi,
although critical of apartheid, is considered too conservative by
many activists.
   More than 500 people have died in the Natal conflict in the past
18 months. Among those killed on Sunday was the son of Abdul
Awetha, a prominent Inkatha leader who is accused in court papers
of involvement in attacks on militants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
