<HEAD>President Invites Pope To Visit Angola</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of cardinal's name in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Eduardo dos Santos of
Angola invited Pope John Paul II to visit his country.
   Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, a papal envoy, announced the
invitation Monday after an audience with the president in the
Angolan capital of Luanda, the official news agency ANGOP said in a
report monitored in Lisbon.
   The report did not say if the pope accepted the invitation to
travel to the south African nation, which has been beset by civil
war for 13 years.
   Guerrillas of the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, supported by South Africa and the United States, have been
fighting to topple the Cuban- and Soviet-backed Marxist government
since 1975.
   Roman Catholicism was introduced to Angola by the Portuguese,
the country's colonial rulers until 1975, and remains the principal
religion.
   The pope has never visited Angola. He will travel to Mozambique,
Zimbabwe, Botswana, Lesotho and Swaziland in September.
