<HEAD>With PM-Meese-Eastland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum Renews Calls for Meese's Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Senate Judiciary Committee
today renewed his call for Attorney General Edwin Meese III to
resign, saying he is ``an embarrassment to the country.''
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, made his comments one day after
Meese fired the department's chief spokesman, Terry Eastland, for
allegedly not defending the attorney general aggressively enough.
The firing prompted the head of Meese's speech-writing unit,
William Schambra, to quit.
   ``It just appears that Ed Meese wants to fire anybody who
disagrees with him or if he doesn't fire them they seem to be
resigning on their own,'' Metzenbaum said on CBS's ``This Morning''
show.
   ``I think it's time for Ed Meese to clean house and start at the
top and it's time for Ed Meese to resign. I think he's an
embarrassment to the administration. Frankly, I think he's an
embarrassment to the country,'' the senator said.
   Metzenbaum, noting an editorial in the politically-conservative
Washington Times today that urges the attorney general to resign,
said: ``I think the conservative backers across the board are
walking away from Ed Meese.''
   ``I think they recognize that he's bad news as far as being able
to stand up for conservative principles, to speak out for them and
I think they recognize that the sooner he gets off the ship the
better it will be for the Reagan administration,'' he said.
   Metzenbaum intially called for Meese's resignation in late March
after Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and criminal division
chief William Weld quit out of concern that Meese's continued
tenure as attorney general in the face of a criminal probe was
hurting the Justice Department's operations.
</TEXT>
