<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to update with dollar skyrocketing after
trade report, and pound plunging after British banks cut base rate;
picks up 15th graf pvs, `Gold opened ....' Also moved on the
financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar skyrocketed in Europe today after the
U.S. government reported that the U.S. merchandise trade deficit
improved sharply in March.
   The pound plunged after British commercial banks cut their base
lending rate by half a percentage point to 7.5 percent, heeding a
signal from the Bank of England.
   The combination of the two developments pushed the dollar up
more than three cents against the British pound.
   The Commerce Department reported that the merchandise trade
deficit shrank to $9.7 billion in March from $13.8 billion in
February.
   The figure was dramatically better than the markets had been
expecting. The consensus had been for a deficit of between $12
billion and $13 billion.
   The markets were surprised by today's cut in British interest
rates, engineered earlier by the central bank apparently to stem
the recent rise in the pound.
   In London, it cost $1.8540 to buy one pound after the cut and
trade report, cheaper than $1.8855 in the morning, and sharply
lower than the $1.8915 of late Monday.
   The dollar was quoted at 125.85 yen in London after the report,
compared with 124.95 yen before.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 124.82 yen, up from 124.73 yen late Monday.
   Other dollar rates after the report, with midmorning rates in
parentheses and compared with late Monday's rates, were: 1.7050
(1.6875) West German marks, up from 1.6860; 1.4155 (1.4025) Swiss
francs, up from 1.4013; 5.7639 (5.7205) French francs, up from
5.7170; 1.9065 (1.8917) Dutch guilders, up from 1.8890; 1,262.00
(1,254.75) Italian lire, up from 1,253.45; 1.2375 (1.2328) Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2322
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $452.60 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $453.15. Both were down from late Monday's bid
of $455.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $453, down from $454 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 57 cents to close at a bid
$454.67.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.58 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $6.70.
</TEXT>
