<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Sudan Explosion,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Office Names Fifth Briton Killed In Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office today identified a fifth Briton
killed in terrorist attacks in Sudan and warned British citizens
against traveling to Khartoum, the capital city.
   Police in Khartoum arrested three foreigners armed with
automatic pistols and submachine guns in connection with the
attacks on the Acropol Hotel and the nearby Sudan Club.
   The attacks occurred Sunday night. First, two bombs went off
near the dining room of the Acropol and then gunmen raided the
Sudan Club.
   A Foreign Office spokesman said Sally Rockett, a 32-year-old
British teacher, was killed in the Acropol.
   Earlier, officials said a British family of four and two
Sudanese had died in the Acropol attack.
   The Foreign Office spokesman, who by custom was not identified,
said 26 people were injured in the hotel attack but only four
needed hospital treatment.
   In the attack on the Sudan Club, frequented by Britons and
members of the British Commonwealth, the Foreign Office said a
Sudanese was badly injured but no one was killed.
   Police in Khartoum earlier had said one man died in the Sudan
Club raid but today it appeared that no one had died at the club.
   The Foreign Office issued a warning against travel to Khartoum
but stressed this applied only to the capital, not to the entire
country.
   ``Anyone who has imminent business in Khartoum should consider
whether it is urgent. If not urgent, then defer for a few days
until the situation becomes clearer,'' the Foreign Office said.
   The other Britons killed at the Acropol Hotel were Chris Rolfe,
35, his wife, Clare, 37, and their children Thomas, 3, and Louise,
1. The couple had been working for the Ockenden Venture, a private
British relief charity.
   The dead Sudanese were identified as a brigadier in the Sudanese
army and a waiter.
