<HEAD>Subway Station Evacuated After Smoke From Fire Fills Tunnels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with service back to normal, two stations
evacuated. EDITS to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred rush-hour commuters were evacuated
from two of London's busiest subway stations this morning after
smoke from an electrical fire filled tunnels and spread onto the
platforms.
   ``As far as we know there were no injuries,'' said a spokesman
for the London Fire Brigade, who by custom was not identified.
   Police and firefighters, using loudspeakers, cleared choking
commuters from Embankment Station, where the fire started, and
Waterloo Station just across the River Thames, where smoke spread
through underground tunnels, the spokesman said.
   Acting police inspector Peter Bird said smoke was spotted
shortly after 7 a.m. in a cable duct under the southbound Bakerloo
Line at Embankment Station. ``It was not a serious fire,'' he said.
   But the Fire Brigade spokesman said the smoke ``caused
considerable distress to passengers.''
   ``We had 25 firefighters at Embankment and another six at
Waterloo leading passengers away and checking that stations were
clear,'' he said.
   Richard Peace, divisional fire officer, said firefighters
discovered the source of the blaze by using special thermal imaging
cameras that pick up heat. He said the fire had been put out and
the spread of smoke had been contained before the rush hour reached
its peak.
   Trains were stopped on either side of Embankment station during
the fire.
   London Transport, which operates the subway system, said both
stations were reopened at 10 a.m. after damaged cable had been
replaced at Embankment.
   A subway fire Nov. 18 at the King's Cross station, London's
busiest, killed 31 people and injured about 80. A pre-World War II
escalator at King's Cross caught fire and flames leaped upward,
engulfing the ticket hall and sending clouds of smoke into tunnels
and platforms.
</TEXT>
