<DOCNO> AP880517-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs 1stLd-Writethru a0483 05-17 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commandos Raid Temple Building; 44 Dead in Highest One-Day Toll</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with commandos raiding temple
building. PICKS up 12th graf, `The two ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 90 Indian commandos pushed into the
Golden Temple complex today to try to dislodge Sikh militants from
two towers overlooking the golden-domed shrine, police said.
   It was the first major probe into the complex, Sikhism's holiest
shrine, since a police siege of the shrine began May 9.
   The advance came after Sikh extremists, in an apparent effort to
divert attention from the besieged temple complex, killed 44 people
Monday and early today in the highest 24-hour toll in their
6-year-old campaign to form an independent nation in Punjab.
   Punjab Police Chief K.P.S. Gill told a news conference tha
anti-terrorist Black Cat commandos had taken over the upper
basement of a building, which is attached to the temple's dining
hall, east of the pool surrounding the temple.
   Militants have been using the building's two towers to fire down
on security forces surrounding the shrine's perimeter.
   About six Sikh extremists were believed trapped in a lower
basement, Gill said.
   The building is not considered the temple's inner sanctum.
   Any attempt to storm the inner sanctum would be viewed by devout
Sikhs as the gravest desecration.
   Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was assassinated by Sikh bodyguards
on Oct. 31, 1984, four months after she ordered the army into the
Golden Temple to uproot armed Sikh militants. More than 1,200
people, mostly Sikhs, were killed in that assault.
   Today, security forces fired scores of incendiary shells and
machine gun rounds at the 120-foot towers to force the militants to
retreat to the basements.
   Small groups of commandos had gone to the rooftop and upper
stories of the dining hall starting Sunday.
   Meanwhile, 18 people were shot to death when militants opened
fire with AK-47 automatic rifles in the market of the village of
Samana in Patiala District, Indian newspapers reported.
   At least 18 others were injured in Samana, 140 miles southeast
of Amritsar near Punjab's border with Haryana state, news reports
said.
   Details were not immediately available on the remaining dead.
   In the previous highest one-day toll, 37 people were killed by
Sikh extremists on April 1. The latest figures raise to at least
1,008 the number of deaths blamed on Sikh extremists in Punjab this
year. About 1,030 deaths were attributed to the militants in all of
1987.
   Earlier today, the 2,800 security troops surrounding the Golden
Temple complex called a cease-fire and urged the estimated 40 to 50
Sikh extremists inside the shrine to surrender.
   Instead, the militants used the lull in the security forces'
firing to try to replenish their supplies.
   An Associated Press reporter, watching from a nearby rooftop,
saw two Sikhs run out of the temple with their hands in the air as
if to surrender. The inner sanctum of the temple is where most of
the gunmen are believed to have taken refuge in recent days.
   The two men darted into a nearby building and then moved several
sacks to the temple's walkway.
   Police said they believed the sacks contained food and
ammunition and opened fire to prevent the two men from returning to
the temple. The men retreated to the storage building and it could
not be determined if they had been hit.
   Three other Sikhs were seen using pails to pull water from the
pool around the temple during the cease-fire.
   Chaman Lal, inspector-general of Punjab police, made the call
for surrender. He was joined by six people, all relatives of those
still inside the shrine, who were among 146 who surrendered to
police on Sunday. Similar appeals were made during two cease-fires
Monday.
   Although a majority in Punjab, Sikhs form only 2 percent of
India's population of 800 million. The militants say they are
discriminated against by the Hindus, who are 82 percent of the
population.
   Eight hundred people, most of them pilgrims or temple workers,
were brought out of the temple May 10.
   The siege began after Sikh gunmen inside the temple opened fire
on a party of police commanders who had gone to nearby roofs to
inspect what appeared to be a new bunker outside the temple walls.
   At least 35 people, mostly Sikh militants, have died since the
siege began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
