<1ST_LINE>u a PM-JailedFarmer 1stLd-Writethru a0499 05-17 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jailed Farmer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Family Leaves Quietly Before Eviction Deadline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with family leaving before
eviction deadline; picks up 9th graf, `On hand ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMBOY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of an embattled farm family enjoyed a
ceremonial ``last meal'' with about 200 friends and relatives, then
packed up and left before a sheriff arrived today to evict them
from their home of four decades.
   Shortly before the eviction deadline of 7 a.m., Kenneth
Leffelman left his empty farm in his pickup truck, and his wife
Marguerite drove off in a school bus, which she drives every
morning.
   ``I don't know where we are going to go,'' Mrs. Leffelman, 57,
said. ``We might have to pitch a tent; the bank took all our
money.''
   The Leffelmans' younger son, Terry, stood in a pasture looking
at the farm.
   ``In the long run I think our family won,'' he said. ``It drew
us a lot closer together.''
   Lee County Ciruit Judge Martin Hill had ordered the Leffelmans
to leave the 440-acre farm where they've lived for 39 years by 7
a.m. today or face trespassing charges. In addition, Leffelman's
son, Edward, and his wife, Susan, were ordered to vacate a house on
the property.
   Lee County Sheriff Tim Bivins said the two houses on the
property were empty and the Leffelmans were gone when authorities
arrived to carry out the eviction.
   ``They fought long and hard for their farm,'' Bivins said. ``I
respect that and appreciate their cooperation.''
   Leffelman, 59, spent two months in the Bureau County Jail last
winter after refusing to disclose the location of assets sought by
the First Bank of Princeton.
   The eviction stems from the bank's attempt to settle a debt that
once stood at $782,259.
   In a telephone interview Monday night, Mrs. Leffelman said about
200 people turned out for the ``last-meal'' pot-luck dinner that
included such offerings as ham, meat loaf, chicken and roast beef.
   On hand, she said, were ``family, friends from the southern part
of Illinois to the northern part. I think there were some people
from Iowa here, too.''
   ``It was great to see how many friends were out there,'' she
said.
   ``We have no place to go,'' Mrs. Leffelman said, but added that
they could stay with family or friends for a week or two.
   The dinner, held in a farm machine shed, was sponsored by the
Farm Support Group of Sterling.
   ``We want to be there to share together, meet together and pray
together,'' said the Rev. Clark Moushon, pastor of the Broadway
United Methodist Church in Sterling, which coordinated the dinner.
   The Leffelmans recently were denied their request for Chapter 12
bankruptcy, a special section of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code developed
for farmers.
   After the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Rockford ruled that the
Leffelmans didn't qualify under Chapter 12, the First Bank of
Princeton asked the judge to order the eviction to satisfy the
remaining $600,000 debt. It already has received cash and 220 acres
of farmland toward a related debt in Bureau County.
   The case attracted attention last fall when farmers held
demonstrations.
   The bank sold livestock and took title to 680 acres of land,
three homes and machinery, although the property has remained in
Leffelman's hands.
   Leffelman was jailed on a contempt charge Oct. 19 by Bureau
County Circuit Judge James Wimbiscus after Leffelman refused to
comply with a court order to pay $75,000 toward a $95,591 debt to
the bank and disclose the location of assets sought by the bank.
   Leffelman maintained he did not have $75,000 and did not own the
assets in question because they had been placed in the Lazy ``L''
Farm Preservation Trust, of which Leffelman's daughters-in-law,
Susan and Nancy Leffelman, and family adviser Donald Tangwall were
trustees.
   Leffelman was released after complying with the court's order.
</TEXT>
