<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Leaders     05-17 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Leaders,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party to Consider Limiting Term Of General Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national Communist Party conference next month
will consider limiting the term of the general secretary in what
would be a major departure from the usual Soviet practice of
lifelong tenure, a top official said.
   Dmitri A. Lisovolik, a deputy to party Central Committee
secretary Anatoly F. Dobrynin, told a group of American business
leaders that proposals have been introduced to limit the party
leader to two or three terms of eight years each.
   General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev raised the idea of
creating a mechanism to replace aging officials in top party jobs
at a January 1987 meeting of the Central Committee, but it
apparently met with opposition then because the meeting's final
documents only made passing reference to it.
   The Soviet leader has said more freqent turnover would make
officials more accountable to the people.
   Many letters have appeared in recent weeks in the Soviet press
proposing fixed terms and age limits for the country's leaders, an
indication the idea is being brought back under consideration.
   Lisovolik, speaking at a reception Monday night to several
members of the Young Presidents Organization as well as a reporter,
did not mention the proposals for age limits. He said he could not
predict whether the proposals for fixed terms would be adopted, but
indicated support has been growing for this.
   The Young Presidents Organization is a group of American and
some foreign business leaders. A delegation of the group arrived in
Moscow on Saturday.
   Lisovolik, 50, has been chief of the U.S. section of the
International Department of the Central Committee since December
1984. He served briefly in the Soviet Embassy in Washington under
Dobrynin, who was ambassador from 1962 to 1986. Dobrynin is now
Central Committee secretary in charge of foreign affairs.
   The Washington Post today quoted Georgi A. Arbatov, another
member of the Central Committee, as saying in an interview that
there is a ``good chance'' the group will introduce proposals at
the June 28 party conference limiting the general secretary's term.
   Arbatov said the changes would not indicate any setback for
Gorbachev, who has been general secretary since March 1985.
   Communist Party general secretaries commonly serve life terms.
An exception was Nikita S. Khrushchev, who was forced from office
in 1964.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
