<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Says He's Still Sure God Called Him to Run</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 9 grafs with Robertson comments, picking up in
3rd graf pvs, Robertson returns; cuts last 3 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson said today the failure
of his Republican presidential bid hadn't shaken his certainty that
God had called him to make the race.
   Robertson, who rejoined the Christian Broadcasting Network
today, said on the network's ``700 Club:''
   ``Obviously the question is, If he called you, why didn't you
win? Well, there's no doubt in my mind, absolutely none whatsoever,
that the Lord led me to do this. I mean, if I had any leading
whatsoever in starting CBN, I had a stronger leading to get
involved in this race for the presidency. No question.''
   Robertson said his first television venture ``fell flat on its
face.''
   ``I'm used to one start, then the next one and the next one,''
he said. ``Sometimes the Lord perfects us and encourages us through
experience and trials.
   ``Was the calling there? Yes. Was I overly optimistic? I thought
we were going to see wonderful things happen. In Iowa, I thought it
was happening.''
   Robertson finished second to Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas and ahead
of Vice President George Bush in the Iowa caucuses on Feb. 8.
However, he finished fifth the next week in New Hampshire and
quickly became an also-ran in the Republican race that Bush has now
sewn up.
   The former television evangelist said that later in the week he
would show videotapes and make further comments on several
controversies that marked his campaign, including his allegations
that his network uncovered information about U.S. hostages in the
Middle East.
   He said he would show a videotape of a deposition by former Rep.
Paul McCloskey, R-Calif., concerning McCloskey's allegation that
Robertson used his father's influence to avoid combat in the Korean
War. Robertson sued McCloskey over that allegation but dropped the
suit in March, saying it was unfair to have to go to trial while
trying to win the nomination.
   Robertson returns to the network he founded nearly 30 years ago
as it is facing a financial crisis. Last year, 645 employees were
laid off because of plummeting donations.
   At the same time Robertson was preparing to announce the
suspension of his campaign Monday, more CBN employees were being
let go.
   When asked what would be done to halt the slide, Robertson said
the operation would become leaner.
   ``After today, I hope we nevr again have to lay off people,'' he
said.
   Robertson refused to say how many employees were laid off, and
CBN officials would not comment on the layoffs.
   Robertson left the ``700 Club'' _ the network's most popular
program in terms of viewership and fundraising _ in 1986 to begin
preparatory work on his campaign.
   Donations began to fall then; the dramatic drop came last year
with the scandals involving other television evangelists and
Robertson's official announcement of his candidacy.
   He resigned as chief executive officer in October when he gave
up his Southern Baptist ordination and became an official
candidate. His son Tim was elevated to the post.
   ``I assumed that I had built a very competent staff,'' Robertson
said in an earlier interview. ``And that they would be able to run
CBN in my absence. I did not realize that my personal presence on
the `700 Club' is as important as it is to the audience.''
   In announcing the suspension of his presidential campaign that
spent $22 million to gain 46 delegates to the national convention,
Robertson said he planned to remain active in the party.
   ``I suspend my candidacy... but I do not now, nor will I ever
suspend, my advocacy of conservative and moral principles,'' he
said.
   Robertson used the occasion to announce the formation of a new
political action committee, Americans for the Republic, to fund and
train conservative Christian political candidates.
   ``I will work for the election of conservative Republicans to
city councils, school boards, legislatures, the House of
Representatives, and the Senate,'' he said.
</TEXT>
