<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-PumpkinPapers     05-17 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pumpkin Papers,500</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at Noon EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hodel Designated `Pumpkin Papers' Farm a National Historic
Landmark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel today
designated as a national historic landmark the Maryland farm where
the ``pumpkin papers'' that led to the conviction of Alger Hiss
were hidden.
   Whittaker Chambers, the late owner of the farm and the man who
hid the stolen State Department documents in a hollowed-out
pumpkin, was ``an historical figure of transcendent importance in
the nation's history,'' Hodel said.
   In a speech at the Heritage Foundation, a think-tank promoting
conservative causes, Hodel noted that the Avdisory Board of the
National Park Service on April 26 had opposed landmark status on
the grounds that 50 years had not passed since the significant
events in question, the discovery of the papers in 1948 by a young
congressman named Richard Nixon.
   ``I appreciate that the board disagrees but I do not choose to
follow its advice in this instance,'' said Hodel, who nominated as
a landmark the 220-acre farm at Westminster, Md., some 30 miles
northwest of Baltimore, now owned and worked by Chambers' son, John.
   The service generally prefers the passage of 50 years to permit
an assessment of the signifance of a property without the pressure
of judgments made at the time.
   John Chambers, deputy staff director of the congressional Joint
Committee on Printing, said when informed of Hodel's action, ``We
are deeply honored by this designation and very pleased by the
secretary's action.''
   Hodel noted that National Park Service Director William Mott had
written him on April 28 that the staff of the service concluded
``that Whittaker Chambers was exceptionally significant and that
the farm represents that significance with the requisuite degree of
historical integrity.''
   Both the Maryland state historic presevation officer and a
professional review committee for the landmarks program, including
historians outside the National Park Service, had supported
landmark designation for the farm, Hodel said.
   Chambers, then an editor of Time magazine, accused Hiss, a
former State Department official then serving as president of a New
York foundation, of being a fellow member of a communist spy ring
in the late 1930s.
   In testimony before the House Un-American Activities Committee,
Hiss denied the allegation and sued Chambers for libel. Chambers
then produced from the pumpkin copies of 1937 State Department
documents he said Hiss had given him.
   The government won a perjury conviction against Hiss for lying
to Congress in his denial that he had been a spy. The pumpkin
papers were key evidence _ prosecutors proved they had been typed
on a typewriter owned by Hiss.
   Hiss, who lives in New York, served 44 months. He dropped his
libel case against Chambers, who died in 1961. Hiss maintains his
innocence to this day, and has declined comment about the landmark
designation.
   Designation as a national landmark brings the owner a plaque and
no obligation except to maintain the historical integrity of the
property. The National Park Service may take back the plaque if it
is not so maintained. Some 1,800 properties have been awarded
plaques.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
