<2ND_LINE>PM-Fugitive Captured,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most-Wanted Fugitive Captured After Escaping Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUPITER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prisoners watching a ``most wanted''
television show spotted one of their own jailmates _ a six-time
escapee _ serving a minor sentence under an alias.
   They promptly told jail officials who arranged to put the inmate
in a more secure facility. But, on the way, the inmate made his
seventh escape.
   In the end, however, justice prevailed.
   An off-duty sheriff's deputy spotted the new escapee at a nearby
mall the next day and recaptured him.
   Inmates were watching ``America's Most Wanted'' Saturday when
they recognized Mark Austin Goodman, a career criminal wanted for
10 bank robberies in Oklahoma among other charges, and informed
corrections officers, said sheriff's spokesman Bob Ferrell.
   Authorities decided to transfer Goodman Sunday night to more
secure quarters at the county jail while they tried to determine
his true identity. But Goodman, who has a deformed right arm,
slipped out of his handcuffs on the way to the van and scaled an
eight-foot fence topped with barbed wire.
   Monday afternoon, however, he was spotted by the off-duty
officer at a mall and arrested, said Ferrell.
   Goodman, a six-time escapee, was serving a 75-day sentence under
the alias James Ron Eide for a burglary charge and was due to be
released May 21 from the Palm Beach County Stockade.
   Goodman was turned over to the U.S. Marshal's Service and taken
to a federal correctional center in Miami, where he'll be held
pending extradition to Oklahoma.
   Goodman escaped Oct. 30 from the Federal Correctional
Institution in El Reno, Okla., where he was awaiting trial on
charges of robbing 10 Oklahoma City-area banks last year.
   He escaped Feb. 29 from the Pinellas County Jail in Clearwater,
where he was held on 11 charges, including grand theft and burglary.
   Goodman, 27, of Missoula, Mont., has prior convictions dating
back to 1979 in Washington, Oregon and Nevada for felony
hit-and-run, burglary, auto theft and escape.
</TEXT>
