<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF-ParkingBan     05-17 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Parking Ban,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Plant Orders Drivers of Other Cars to Park Elsewhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVONIA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has decided not to
make salaried workers take a hike if they don't drive GM cars.
   Supervisors issued a stern memo last week ordering salaried
employees at the Indland parts division who drive something other
than a GM car to park it with the hourly workers _ on the other
side of the plant.
   But the order was reversed without explanation Monday.
   The memo said the sight of non-GM cars ``does not convey a
positive image to other salary employees or guests who visit the
plant, and it has a negative impact on our share of the car
market.''
   Offending cars, the memo said, would be towed away at owners'
expense.
   At Ford Motor Co., there is no restriction on vehicles employees
can park in company lots. Chrysler Corp. reserves special lots for
non-Chrysler products, and the special lots tend to be farther from
Chrysler buildings than other lots, a spokesperson said.
</TEXT>
