<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LifeintheUSSR Advisory   05-17 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Life in the USSR, Advisory,</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union that President Reagan will visit later this
month has undergone tremendous changed since Mikhail S. Gorbachev
assumed power. `Glasnost' has brought a new openness to Soviet
society, but the better life promised under Gorbachev's economic
reforms _ ``perestroika'' _ has not materialized.
   AP correspondents in Moscow set out across the Soviet Union to
explore what life is like in the Soviet Union _ from the vice in
Odessa to a factory in Dushanbe, a farm in Kanevskaya, a home in
Tynda and a store in Moscow.
   Their four-part series, Life in the USSR, will move Wednesday
for release Sunday May 22 through Wednesday PMs, May 25.
   The stories are illustrated with LaserPhotos.
   Here is a description of the series.
   
   Sunday
   
   MOSCOW _ An editor on an influential Soviet newspaper told his
dinner guests how he had spent the afternoon arguing heatedly with
his colleagues about a particular article. ``It was wonderful,'' he
said. ``I get drunk on glasnost.''
   Slug: BC-Life in the USSR-Gorbachev's Country. By Michael Putzel.
   
   Monday PMs
   
   MOSCOW _ When Olga Boguslavsky's friend came to Moscow on a
recent buying trip from the Ural Mountains, the winter coat she
found at the GUM department store on Red Square cost 730 rubles
($1,170. For the same amount of money, almost four months pay for
the average industrial worker, she could buy enough meat at
state-subsidized prices to last for six years.
   Slug: PM-Life in the USSR-Consumers. By Mark J. Porubcansky.
   
   Tuesday PMs
   
   KANEVSKAYA, U.S.S.R _ From the two swimming pools in its sports
complex to the fleet of buses that take workers to the fields, the
Victory Collective Farm would not be familiar to most U.S. farmers.
   Slug: PM-Life in the USSR-Farm. By Mark J. Porubcansky.
   
   Wednesday PMs
   
   ODESSA, U.S.S.R. _ The body of old Odessa is decaying and
neglected, but looks are deceiving. The soul of the Ukrainian city
known as the ``Mama'' of dealers, drifters and orphans in the 1920s
still spills vice from darkened recesses into the open marketplace.
   Slug: PM-Life in the USSR-Vice. By Carol J. Williams.
   
   The AP
