<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Fitzwater-Television     05-17 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fitzwater-Television,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Spokesman Says TV `Distorts Information'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater today
refused to allow television coverage of a pre-summit White House
briefing, saying television ``distorts information.''
   Fitzwater was responding to a request to admit television
cameras to an on-the-record briefing being given by Rozanne
Ridgeway, the assistant secretary of state for European affairs.
   The briefing is one of a series being held in advance of
President Reagan's May 29-June 2 meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev in Moscow. Most have been held under ``background''
rules, which do not permit the briefers to be identified.
   Afer turning down the request for television coverage, Fitzwater
said he would be willing to take the request up with Ms. Ridegway
and that he would consider a request to permit radio coverage.
   The spokesman was also asked why he does not routinely permit
television camers in his own on-the-record briefings, as spokesmen
for the State Department do.
   ``They have more courage than we do,'' he replied. ``It is too
high a risk for me. You can't talk on camera; you can't discuss
issues; you end up with a very stilted kind of conversation, and
also I don't think press spokesmen ought to become television
personalities.''
   ``You open yourselves up to all sorts of problems unique to the
power of television,'' he said. ``It distorts information and
portrays information that is different than real substance.''
   After several television reporters protested his decision,
Fitzwater turned to his staff and said, ``We should have gone to
background, like we did all the rest.''
</TEXT>
