<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0475 05-17 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls for Defense Cuts to Fund Elder Programs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with Dukakis comments today; pick up 3rd graf
pvs bgng ``Although Dukakis...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis called today for cuts in defense spending to pay
for elderly care, saying ``these are the choices we've got to
make.''
   The Massachusetts governor, favored to win today's Democratic
primary in Oregon against Jesse Jackson, addressed more than 1,000
senior citizens before returning to the Statehouse.
   Dukakis also scheduled a late afternoon meeting with California
Rep. Mel Levine, a House Foreign Affairs Committee member and
authority on U.S.-Israel relations, another in a series of
consultations with leading congressional Democrats.
   Dukakis told the conference on aging that in order to assist the
elderly with affordable housing, long-term health care and public
transportation, he would reduce or eliminate an array of military
programs, including the ``Star Wars'' missile defense, more
supercarrier task forces, the Midgetman missile and a proposed
``space plane'' that could fly from Washington to Tokyo in three
hours.
   ``These are the choices we've got to make, and we haven't been
making them,'' Dukakis said.
   He also said he would not try to balance the federal budget by
denying cost-of-living increases in Social Security.
   ``Nobody's going to tell me Social Security is a middle-class
entitlement. It's the difference between dignity and poverty,''
Dukakis said.
   Later, talking to reporters, Dukakis said he believed that
wealthy senior citizens should have to pay taxes on their Social
Security benefits.
   On Monday, Dukakis brushed off polls that said he would fare
well in a November battle with George Bush and said ``I've got to
win this nomination first.''
   Although Dukakis spent little time in Oregon compared with
Jackson, he said he wasn't taking anything for granted. ``This is
going to be a long, tough and contested race,'' he told reporters
on Monday.
   Dukakis has won eight of the last nine primaries, and is far
ahead of Jackson in the delegate race.
   A CBS-New York Times poll published today suggested Dukakis had
a comfortable lead over Bush, the apparent Republican nominee, in a
hypothetical matchup. A Louis Harris & Associates poll released a
day earlier showed similar results.
   Forty-nine percent of the 1,382 adults interviewed by telephone
May 9-12 in the CBS-Times poll favored Dukakis, 39 percent favored
Bush and 10 percent were undecided, CBS reported Monday night. The
margin of error was 3 percentage points.
   In the Democratic race, Jackson has been complaining that the
proportion of ``super delegates'' backing him has not been in line
with the percentage of the popular vote he has received.
   Dukakis also has won the majority of endorsements by ``super
delegates'' _ Democratic Party leaders and elected officials who
are convention delegates but not bound by primary results in their
home states.
   ``Fairness is a reasonabale expectation,'' Jackson said Monday
in New Jersey, which, like California, holds its primary June 7.
   ``I don't agree with him,'' Dukakis said when told of Jackson's
objections. ``We all knew what the rules were. This is a campaign
for delegates as well as votes.''
   The Massachusetts governor was brushing off questions about his
budget problems at home, contending revenue shortfalls are a
national problem.
   Figures released Monday indicated the state has a $243 million
shortfall for the fiscal year ending June 30, $166 million more
than had been projected a month ago.
   The governor, who has made his fiscal competence a campaign
selling point, said Massachusetts would trim planned program
expansions and tap cash reserves that were to go to capital
improvements and other projects to balance the current budget. He
said he would have to substantially trim his proposed budget for
next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
