<DOCNO> AP880517-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-OnToCalifornia Bjt   05-17 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-On To California, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Makes Final Bid in California as Dukakis, Bush Look Beyond</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Jesse Jackson, California offers a
last hope of blunting Michael Dukakis' momentum. But for Dukakis
and Vice President George Bush, the state's June 7 primary is a
trial run for the fall race for the White House.
   Jackson is throwing nearly all of his remaining resources, both
time and money, into his campaign for the 314 Democratic delegates
at stake in California.
   He plans to outspend Dukakis by as much as 3-1 on television
advertising in the state during the next three weeks, and he is to
spend at least 15 days, about twice as much time as the
Massachusetts governor, in his final push for California votes.
   Still, the most recent Gallup Poll reported Dukakis leading
Jackson among California Democrats by 67 percent to 26 percent.
   Dukakis' Western states political director, Richard Ybarra,
predicts that California's election night returns will put Dukakis
over the total needed to clinch the Democratic nomination. New
Jersey, New Mexico and Montana also have primaries June 7.
   ``We believe we can clinch it here that night. ... I'm talking
about going over 2,081,'' says Ybarra, a longtime California
political activist and the son-in-law of farm labor leader Cesar
Chavez.
   On the Republican side, Bush is campaigning as intensely as if
he still had active primary opponents and needed California's 175
GOP delegates. But Bush is clearly aimed at the fall campaign, in
which California's 47 electoral votes could be pivotal.
   California has ended up in the Republican column in eight of the
last nine presidential elections, and Republicans have cut the
Democratic registration lead in half in the past decade. However,
Bush trailed Dukakis by 10 percentage points in the most recent
poll of California voters.
   Neither Bush nor Dukakis has any political roots or strong ties
to California, and pollsters say the support for both in the Golden
State is soft and still tentative. That has led both men to plan
intense primary campaigns in California.
   Jackson, meanwhile, isn't conceding California or the Democratic
nomination to Dukakis, despite the long odds.
   ``Why do I run against the odds? I've faced odds all my life,''
Jackson told supporters at rallies in a California trip last
weekend. ``You must not surrender. We really can win.''
   Sounding the same, don't-give-up theme, Jackson's California
co-chairman, state Assemblyman Tom Bates, told other supporters,
``We can dream the impossible dream and make it happen in
California.''
   But pollster Mervin Field, who has been surveying and analyzing
California voters for over 40 years, said last week that a Jackson
victory in California ``would be a monumental upset ... ranking as
one of the biggest political happenings since the country was
founded.''
   Still, a number of factors give encouragement to Jackson's hopes
for a California upset, not the least of which is the demonstrated
willingness of California Democrats to vote for black candidates.
   Although blacks constitute only 8 percent of California's total
population, a black man, Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley, has won the
Democratic nomination for governor the past two elections, and
other blacks have been elected in recent years as lieutenant
governor and state schools chief.
   The lack of other major issues on the June 7 ballot also could
help Jackson if his strongly motivated supporters turn out in
greater percentages than other voters.
   California Democrats also have shown no inclination in recent
years to join a front-runner's bandwagon. In the past three
presidential campaigns, the Democratic nomination was clinched
before California's last-in-the-nation primary, and in all three
cases a majority of California went for the already-vanquished
underdog candidate.
   But other strong forces are against Jackson's chances in
California.
   The state's strong economy, with unemployment near a 20-year
low, blunts the impact of Jackson's appeal to the economically
disadvantaged. And the Spanish-speaking Dukakis has hopes of a
strong showing among Hispanics, who by far are California's largest
minority.
   Finally, pollster Field suggests that Jackson's greatest
strength, his charismatic oratorical skills, may be less of an
advantage in California than elsewhere, because Californians have
had more experience with charismatic leaders and have greater
reservations about them.
   ``California voters had their fascination with Ronald Reagan as
a detached governor and detached president. They had their fling,
their love-hate relationship with Jerry Brown, who intrigued them
and promised a lot (as governor) but delivered very little,'' Field
said.
   ``But I sense the mood of the state today is one where there's
less toleration for that, and they want demonstrated competence.
... Dukakis, I would say, fits the mood of today's California
voters.''
</TEXT>
