<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   05-17 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amal Regains Ground in Counterattack</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A counterattack by Amal fighters gained
ground against the rival Hezbollah militia Tuesday in the 12th day
of their war for control of south Beirut's Shiite Moslem slums.
   The battle raged in violation of another cease-fire sponsored by
Syria and Iran. Syria supports the mainstream Amal and Iran backs
the radical Hezbollah, whose name means Party of God.
   Police said 15 people were killed and 51 wounded on Tuesday.
They put the number of total casualties at 240 dead and 757 wounded
since fighting began May 6 in the 16 square miles of slums, where
groups affiliated with Hezbollah are believed to hold most of the
nine Americans and nine other foreigners missing in Lebanon.
   Sounds of exploding artillery shells, mortar rounds and
rocket-propelled grenades carried throughout Beirut, which has been
battered by 13 years of civil war.
   The latest truce, the seventh since fighting began, was called
for 11 p.m. Monday after Syria massed 7,500 soldiers and 500 tanks
and armored vehicles on the edges of the enclave next to the
airport. The Syrians have about 25,000 soldiers in north and
Lebanon and 7,500 in Moslem west Beirut.
   Syria agreed to give political efforts a chance after Iran's
acting foreign minister, Ali Mohammed Besharati, held several
meetings Monday with government and military leaders in Beirut and
Damascus, capital of Syria.
   A meeting he called for Tuesday between representatives of Amal
and Hezbollah to discuss a political settlement did not take place,
however, because Amal refused to attend.
   Hezbollah had driven Amal to the fringes of the slums, but a
police spokesman said the counterattack Tuesday regained most of
Shiyah, one of the slum neighborhoods.
   ``Amal militiamen inched across Shiyah and regained most of the
district in fierce house-to-house clashes, but ... Hezbollah
remains in control of 90 percent of south Beirut,'' said the
spokesman, whose name was withheld in keeping with regulations.
   An Amal official said the militia, commanded by Justice Minister
Nabih Berri, refused to send a representative to the
Besharati-sponsored meeting at the Iranian Embassy in Moslem west
Beirut.
   ``We told them that we do not accept a meeting at the Iranian
Embassy,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``The
affairs of the Shiite community should only be discussed at the
(Lebanese) Supreme Shiite Council.''
   Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddin heads the council. He reiterated
that Syrian forces should move into south Beirut and disarm the
warring militias.
   In a statement broadcast by Beirut radio stations, he said:
``The plight of the population is my main worry. This suffering
will end only when the Syrians move in. Every other method is just
a waste of time, helping only to prolong the plight of the
population.''
   Interior Minister Abdulla Rassi also urged the Syrians to take
over the slums.
   ``Political solutions have failed to end the fighting,'' he
said. ``These clashes will only come to an end when the regular
(Syrian) force moves in to enforce law and order.''
   The Amal official said Berri and senior aides would meet in
Damascus with President Hafez Assad of Syria, who has become
Lebanon's main power broker.
   Assad supports Iran in its war with Iraq but has grown concerned
recently about the Iranian challenge to his influence among the 1.2
million Shiites who make up Lebanon's largest sect.
   About 20,000 Shiites demonstrated in the southern port of Tyre.
They waved posters of Assad and Berri, calling on the Syrians to
occupy south Beirut.
   ``We don't want Iranians! We don't want Hezbollah!'' marchers
chanted.
   One banner said: ``We call on the Syrian command to save our
children in south Beirut.''
   Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, chief of Syria's military intelligence
in Lebanon, met with Besharati at the Iranian Embassy in Beirut and
told reporters without elaboration:
   ``We are searching for solutions and means to apply these
solutions. We shall exert efforts and take all the appropriate
measures. We are seriously searching for solutions to overcome this
crisis.''
   Besharati said: ``In light of these meetings I do not believe
there is a need for the deployment of Syrian forces in south
Beirut. The cease-fire will be respected, after which we will work
to withdraw the gunmen.
   ``We are working with the Syrians to prevent the recurrence of
such differences in the future.''
   Asked whether they discussed the hostages and their possible
release, Besharati said: ``All issues could be raised in these
these meetings. We hope this crisis will be over.'' He did not
elaborate.
</TEXT>
