<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Hangings     05-17 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Hangings,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Urge Campaign Against Capital Punishment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activists on
Tuesday urged South Africans to speak out against capital
punishment to reduce a record-high rate of hangings.
   Last year, 164 people were hanged, the most in South African
history, and 59 people have been hanged so far this year. Of those
prisoners, 10 were white and 213 were black or mixed-race.
   Law professor John Dugard and defense attorney Jules Browde
joined Sheena Duncan of the Black Sash civil rights group at a
protest meeting Tuesday in calling for greater public pressure
against executions.
   The activists said the issue was urgent because of the large
number of people _ 274 _ on Death Row.
   Of the condemned, 53 were sentenced in killings arising from
political unrest, according to the Center for Applied Legal Studies
at Johannesburg's University of the Witwatersrand. These include
the ``Sharpeville Six'' _ five men and a woman whose deaths
sentences in a 1984 mob killing have provoked an international
outcry.
   According to official statistics, more people are executed in
South Africa than any other nation. Amnesty International has said
the actual number of executions in some countries, such as Iran,
could be much higher.
</TEXT>
