<DOCNO> AP880517-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     05-17 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls for Defense Cuts to Fund Elder Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis told enthusiastic home-state senior citizens
Tuesday that military spending should be deeply cut to pay for
services for the elderly.
   ``The next president is going to inherit an awful fiscal mess,
and hard choices are going to have to be made,'' Dukakis told more
than 1,000 people gathered for the sixth annual Governor's
Conference on Aging.
   ``Are we going to spend $6 billion on Star Wars and MX missiles
on railroad cars, or are we going to build affordable housing for
families of low- and moderate-income and the elderly?'' he asked.
   ``Are we going to spend $36 billion for new supercarrier task
forces that we don't need and can't afford, or are we going to
begin to do something about long-term care for elders and the
disabled in this country?''
   Later, Dukakis was returning to the Massachusetts Statehouse in
Boston to meet with Rep. Mel Levine. The California Democrat, a
member of the Foreign Affairs Committee and an expert on
U.S.-Israeli relations, is the latest in a string of visitors to
Dukakis' office.
   Last week, Dukakis met privately at the Statehouse with Sen.
Bill Bradley, D-N.J., to discuss the Soviet Union.
   Dukakis, who was favored to win Tuesday's Democratic primary in
Oregon over Jesse Jackson, again shrugged off Jackson's criticism
of the party's delegate selection process, saying all the
candidates knew the rules when they entered the race. If changes
are needed, Dukakis said, they should be made after this fall's
election.
   Asked about recent polls indicating that Dukakis holds a lead
over Republican Vice President George Bush in a hypothetical
general election, Dukakis offered a rare comment on poll results:
``All I can say is I think there's something cooking out there.''
   He quickly added that he thinks poll results ``mean very
little.''
   In his speech, Dukakis also suggested he would cut funding for
the Midgetman missile and a proposed ``space plane,'' using the
money instead for improved public transportation and human services.
   ``These are the choices we've got to make, and we haven't been
making them,'' Dukakis said.
   The Massachusetts governor also expressed strong support for
Social Security, but said wealthy recipients should continue to pay
taxes on their benefits.
   He said he recalled being asked by a reporter in Iowa whether he
favored continuing federal support for ``middle-class
entitlements.''
   The governor said he was puzzled by the question because
``two-thirds of Social Security recipients live on that check and
that check alone.''
   ``Nobody's going to tell me Social Security is a middle-class
entitlement. It's the difference between dignity and poverty,''
Dukakis said, to applause.
   Afterward, talking to reporters, Dukakis said he believed that
better-off senior citizens should continue to pay taxes on their
Social Security benefits, but he argued against trying to balance
the federal budget by denying cost-of-living increases to Social
Security recipients.
   In the speech, Dukakis endorsed legislation filed by Rep. Claude
Pepper, D-Fla., intended to expand health and other services to
elderly patients in their homes.
   Dukakis said he was proud that Massachusetts is one of the few
states sing state money to support ``home care'' for elders and
said the time had come to expand the approach nationwide.
   ``I think it's about time we reached out to millions of seniors
across this country,'' he said, arguing that home care provides
many elderly citizens with needed services while allowing them to
remain independent in familiar surroundings.
   ``In the long run, it's a money-saver as well,'' Dukakis said.
But, he added, ``None of this, unfortunately, is going to come on
the cheap.''
</TEXT>
