<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimaryRdp Bjt   05-17 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt,400-850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Primary: Warm-Up for June 7 Sweepstakes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close 11 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRAD CAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis
battled Jesse Jackson in the Oregon presidential primary on
Tuesday, a West Coast warm-up for their final election showdown
early next month in California.
   Dukakis was heavily favored to defeat his sole remaining rival
and win the majority of the 45 delegates at stake, just as he has
won every primary but one over the past seven weeks to assume
unquestioned control of the Democratic race.
   Dukakis also looked to Oregon to help him inch toward the 2,081
delegates needed to gain the Democratic nomination. He has 1,613
delegates to 956 for Jackson, and his aides express confidence that
he will control a nominating majority by the time the primaries end
next month.
   Vice President George Bush, who already owns a delegate majority
on the Republican side, looked to add Oregon to his column in the
GOP primary. His final active opponent, once and future television
evangelist Pat Robertson, suspended his campaign on Monday.
   Dukakis was so confident of his success in Oregon that he
decided against airing television advertisements and limited his
personal campaigning in the state to parts of two days.
   Jackson devoted more time than that to Oregon, and seemed to
needle Dukakis when he said, ``I earn my votes every day.'' But he
posted no predictions of victory, has won only the District of
Columbia's primary since March 8, and more often than not has been
buried by Dukakis landslides in recent weeks.
   Oregon seemed little more than a sidelight to neighboring
California and its huge cache of 314 delegates.
   Both Jackson and Dukakis turned the state into something of a
stopover point in and out of California, which is one of four
states holding Democratic primaries on the final day of the primary
season June 7.
   Jackson plans to invest heavily there in hopes of defeating
Dukakis, although public opinion polls indicate the Massachusetts
governor holds a strong lead.
   Dukakis also is making a major effort in California, in part to
hold off Jackson's challenge but also to lay the groundwork for his
expected fall campaign against Bush.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
