<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LawyerAid     05-17 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lawyer Aid,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Launch Consumer Law Magazine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking for a lawyer? Interview several, learn
their backgrounds and specialities, bargain with them over fees and
get any agreements in writing.
   That is some of the advice on lawyer-shopping from Everyday Law,
a new consumer-oriented magazine published by the nation's trial
lawyers.
   Some newspapers and magazines have regular law columns, but this
will be the first full-time consumer law magazine, said Anne Grant,
who pioneered its development and is editor.
   ``People are gradually becoming aware that they need to know
more'' about the law, she explained, so it was a ``natural
connection'' for the Association of Trial Lawyers of America to
launch the magazine.
   Trial lawyers specialize in suits between people and in
defending people accused of crimes. Thus, the group is oriented
toward consumer and individual issues, Grant said.
   But how will association members react to a magazine that
advises potential clients to consider mediation instead of
lawsuits, to shop around for lawyers and to bargain with them over
fees and services?
   The advisory board, which includes consumer advocates, lawyers
and others, was pleased with the first issue, said Grant.
   They ``feel if you can get out of the (legal) system things that
don't belong in there, the system will operate more efficiently ...
we want to (help people) avoid problems. Some will arise anyway,
but we want to avoid those that are avoidable.''
   In addition to advice on choosing a lawyer, the first issue
explains the legal aspects of product warranties, discusses the
Taxpayers Bill of Rights under consideration in Congress, examines
the legal ramifications of sexually transmitted disease, advises on
dealing with real estate developers, gives an overview of the
Consumer Federation of America and has an interview with People's
Court judge Joseph A. Wapner.
   Future issues will consider prenuptial agreements, sports
officiating, lemon laws, dealing with dentists, insurance
adjustors, car insurance, laws affecting boating and government
accountability.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Eds: Everyday Law is published in Washington, but is sold
through Circulation Department, Everyday Law, 5615 Cermak Road,
Cicero, Ill. 60650.
</TEXT>
