<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Young     05-17 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Young,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Reaching Out to Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After listening to a Jesse Jackson speech that
stirred him to tears, Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young embraced Jackson
and then wrote a letter to the man with whom he has often clashed.
   ``You make me feel proud and humble when I hear you speak,''
Young wrote. ``Martin (Luther King Jr.) would be proud too. You
have my full endorsement as the moral voice of our time.''
   The letter, written after Jackson's speech at a recent
fund-raiser in San Francisco, marked just one of several times that
Young has reached out to the Democratic presidential candidate in
the past month.
   He called Jackson's home in Chicago after the New York primary
to express concern over Jackson's fatigue and to congratulate him
on what Young considered the dignified way he had run his campaign
despite attacks by New York Mayor Ed Koch.
   ``His followers have been telling me that he really is out there
alone, that the people around him are pulling at him for power, and
he really needs some people who just love him and are concerned
about him to tell him that he's doing good,'' Young told The
Atlanta Constitution in an interview published Tuesday.
   ``And so a number of people in the last month or so have been
saying that, from time to time, I ought to call him and just tell
him what I think.''
   Young said many people have misunderstood his differences with
Jackson and he believes Jackson shares that misunderstanding. ``I
think he feels that I am standing in judgment,'' the mayor said.
   Young was among those who publicly disputed Jackson's first
account of his role in the minutes that followed the 1968
assassination of King in Memphis, Tenn. He has said Jackson was not
the last person to speak to King, was not on the balcony when King
was shot and did not cradle the dying man in his arms.
   The Atlanta mayor also was among the black leaders who
criticized Jackson's decision to run for president in 1984, calling
it at one point an ``extremely dangerous'' strategy that would
build up and then deflate the hopes of poor Americans.
   And Young has questioned whether someone who has never held
elective office would have the preparation needed to handle the
presidency.
   In the interview, Young acknowledged the help Jackson has given
him in his own election campaigns and added, ``By the same token, I
think I have been his defender, too. That part never gets
publicized. The public does not know about it.''
   ``If I said anything questioning what Jesse did or said _ and it
wasn't even questioning _ the fact that I would not be a true
believer made me an enemy and I have just resented that. I don't
buy that.''
</TEXT>
