<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OverdueBooks     05-17 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Overdue Books,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Librarian Says She'll Send Others to Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESTER, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The librarian who signed a warrant for the
arrest of a woman who had two books that were 52 days overdue says
the publicity has other overdue books pouring in.
   ``We had a lady come in who had books out since 1985,'' said
Chester County Library Director Ann Ramsey. ``We've had a lot of
calls from people saying, `I'll bring the books in, but please
don't put me in jail.'''
   Ms. Ramsey said Tuesday that close to 100 overdue books have
been returned in the last two days.
   ``Nobody here can remember collecting as many fines in one
day,'' she said. She said about $50 in fines were paid Monday and
about $50 was paid to replace lost books.
   Ms. Ramsey signed the warrant for the arrest of Sharon Adams of
Fort Lawn.
   She said she didn't realize it was an arrest warrant, ``but in
retrospect, it doesn't matter because it was within our rights.
I'll probably do it again before the end of the month.''
   Ms. Adams was arrested May 10 by state Trooper Robert Neely for
failing to return ``Trapping _ A Practical Guide'' and ``The
Complete Book of Trapping'' within 15 days of receiving an official
notice they were overdue. She was handcuffed, fingerprinted and
taken to jail.
   State law makes it a misdemeanor to fail to return a library
book within 15 days of written notification.
   Ms. Adams, 36, returned the books Friday and was found guilty by
Chester County Magistrate Court Judge James Turner and given a
one-day suspended sentence.
   She said she plans to appeal.
   Ms. Adams has said she had asked the library to order the books
from the state library on Jan. 27. She said her boyfriend, Roy
Turner, picked up the books from the library Feb. 22 without her
knowledge or library card.
</TEXT>
