<DOCNO> AP880517-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Lefebvre     05-17 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Lefebvre,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican, Rebel Bishop Reportedly Reach Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre and the Vatican
have reportedly reached an agreement that will end a
schism-threatening dispute that dates back to the reforms of Second
Vatican Council in the 1960s.
   The Italian news agencies ANSA and AGI, without indicating their
sources, reported Tuesday that an official announcement of the
settlement was expected soon, possibly after Pope John Paul II's
return on Thursday from South America.
   The Milan-based newspaper Il Giornale and Il Resto del Carlino
of Bologna carried similar, unattributed reports this week.
   Lefebvre's case has been handled by Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger,
who as head of the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, is
the Vatican's guardian of theological orthodoxy.
   Officials of the congregation declined to say if an agreement
had been reached with the 82-year-old French bishop, who was
suspended by Pope Paul VI in 1976 from his priestly duties,
including saying Mass. They referred inquiries to the Vatican press
office, which said it had no comment.
   In defiance of the Vatican, Lefebvre has ordained priests and
celebrated the Tridentine Mass, a banned, 16th-century liturgy in
Latin. He claims millions of followers and sympathizers and much
enthusiasm for the Latin Mass.
   John Paul II wrote Ratzinger in April in which he said he was
hoping for a settlement with the rebel archbishop.
   The news reports said Lefebvre had agreed to accept the
conclusions of the Second Vatican Council. Among the council's
legacy to the Roman Catholic church is the present custom of
celebrating Mass in the local language, an emphasis on ecumenism,
or promoting better relations between various faiths and Catholics,
and a broader, more active role by lay people.
   Lefebvre had agreed to accept the council's reforms but without
renouncing traditional ways, the reports said.
   The agreement, which ANSA said was reached after Lefebvre and
Ratinzger met in Rome in early May, reportedly would allow the
archbishop to consecrate bishops.
   Lefebvre was quoted in February as saying he planned to
consecrete three bishops in June. That act, without Vatican
permission, would lead to excommunication from the church and set
the stage for a possible schism.
   Lefebvre has ordained more than 200 priests in the past 15 years
without Vatican permission.
   His traditionalist Pius X Fraternity, based in Switzerland,
would again have Vatican approval, according the the reports.
   In October, Pope John Paul II gave Cardinal Edouard Gagnon the
task of working toward a settlement in the case.
   In his letter to Ratzinger in April, the pope, possibly
establishing the framework for the reported agreement, cited
possible problems and advantages of both conservatism and
``progressism'' in the church.
   Progress sometimes does not take into account the function of
tradition, the pope wrote, ``which is fundamental to the church's
mission.''
   On the other hand, John Paul wrote, conservatism ``stops at the
past itself, without taking into account the correct aspiration to
the future.''
   In Switzerland, spokesmen at the fraternity's Rickenbach
headquarters and at the traditionalist seminary in Econe declined
comment. They said Lefebvre was in France and the fraternity's
superior general, the Rev. Franz Schmidberger, was in the United
States until June.
   A well-placed traditionalist source who insisted on anonymity
said he considered the reports of a reconciliation to be
``credible.''
   The French Catholic monthly Trente Jours reported that a secret
meeting in Rome April 11-13 between Vatican experts and
traditionalists gave ``new hope for peace between Econe and the
Vatican.''
   It quoted an ``authorized Vatican observer'' as saying that
there were only two potential obstacles in the way of a
reconciliation: an extremist group in the traditionalist movement
that might make Lefebvre change his mind or ``some national
episcopates'' opposed to recognizing Lefebvre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Intelligence     05-17 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Intelligence,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Backs Push to Upgrade Intelligence-Gathering</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arms Treaty Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Tuesday the United
States must modernize its intelligence-gathering system, regardless
of what arms control treaties are negotiated with the Soviet Union.
   ``It is important for our national security interests that our
country have all of the means necessary to assure compliance with
these agreements,'' Reagan said in a statement.
   ``With or without future arms control agreements, it is
important to our national security interests that we keep pace with
changes in technologies in other nations.''
   The president's statement supported bipartisan efforts in
Congress to upgrade the so-called ``national technical means,'' the
system by which this country, among other things, uses
sophisticated satellite technology to monitor compliance with arms
control agreements.
   Reagan's comments were released shortly after he met privately
with the two ranking members of the Senate Intelligence Committee,
and as the Senate prepared to open floor debate on the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., the committee's chairman, told
reporters that Reagan gave him and Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, ``a
real commitment to make sure that our national security interests
are protected by continuing to modernize our national technical
means.''
   In his statement, the president said, ``I welcome bipartisan
support to start this year on a multi-year program to improve these
systems.''
   ``I will also include funding for the second year of this
program in the final budget which I submit to Congress,'' he said,
``and I will urge the next administration to assure continuity of
this vital effort. After 1989, the funding for this program should
be additive to the 2 percent real growth objective for national
security spending.''
   Neither Reagan nor the senators indicated how much money was
being envisioned for the modernization program.
   Boren said the congressional Armed Services and Intelligence
committees have been concerned about ``the need to improve our
national technical means, to modernize those systems, to keep
pace'' with changing weapons technology.
   The changes are needed not only to ensure compliance with arms
control pacts, but also to ``have a good assessment of what's going
on the world,'' he said.
</TEXT>
