<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OldDresses     05-17 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Old Dresses,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Antique Dresses Found in Stable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of dresses from the 1920s and 1930s, some
by top designers like Coco Chanel, have been found in trunks left
in a stable in 1937 by one of the first Britons to sell elegant
second-hand clothes.
   Textile specialist Anne-Marie Benson of auctioneers Phillips
said Tuesday the collection of about 600 dresses will be sold at
auction June 2. She estimated the dresses, including 80 to 100 by
top Paris couturiers, would bring nearly $40,000.
   The dresses come from the estage of Robina Wallis, who died last
year at age 87. In the 1930s, her mother, Ellen Mary Wallis, began
selling clothes by designers such as Chanel, Worth, Callot Soeurs,
Vionnet and Molyneux that had been worn by socialites and
ladies-in-waiting at Buckingham Palace. At the time, second-hand
sales were very new and very discreet.
   When Mrs. Wallis' husband died in 1937, she and her daughter
moved from Devon to Wartha Manor on the Cornwall peninsula and
trunks containing hundreds of dresses were put in the stables.
   Miss Benson said the silk, velvet and chiffon dresses, many
hand-beaded and embroidered, remained untouched for a half-century,
when they were found by the executors of Miss Wallis' estate.
   ``The trunks had been stepped on, the horses had kicked them and
cats had been sleeping on them. ... The newspaper lining the trunks
was dated 1937,'' Miss Benson said.
   ``Although some dresses are slightly damaged, many are in
excellent condition,'' she said. ``This was a very exciting find.''
   ``They're more sort of cocktail and dinner party dresses than
ballgowns, but you'd look very swish in one of these today.''
</TEXT>
