<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Nunn-VP     05-17 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nunn-VP,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Democratic Leaders Want Nunn for VP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia is a solid
choice of Southern Democratic party leaders as a running mate for
likely presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, according to
interviews by The Charlotte Observer.
   The party officials, in 14 Southern and border states, also say
that a ticket including Jesse Jackson would hurt Dukakis in their
states, though most say promising Jackson a lesser but key role in
a Democratic administration would help.
   The 11 Southern states and three border states _ Kentucky,
Missouri and West Virginia _ offer 164 electoral votes, 30 percent
of the total and more than half the 270 needed for nomination. No
Democrat this century has won the White House without carrying a
majority of Southern states.
   Officials in seven states want Nunn as their first choice. Those
in four others rank him second to favorite sons: Sens. Bob Graham
in Florida, Lloyd Bentson in Texas, Albert Gore Jr. in Tennessee
and Rep. Richard Gephardt in Missouri.
   Other names often mentioned favorably by party leaders include
Sens. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas and John Glenn of Ohio and Arkansas
Gov. Bill Clinton.
</TEXT>
