<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GayRights Bjt   05-17 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Rights, Bjt,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baltimore City Council Moves toward Passage of Gay Rights Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of gay rights legislation say they
are thrilled the Baltimore City Council gave the bill preliminary
approval after twice rejecting it in the last eight years.
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' said Curt Decker, a lobbyist for the Baltimore
Justice Campaign, after Monday night's 12-6 vote in an overflowing
council chamber. ``I've worked on this eight years. It's time that
it happened.''
   Decker predicted final passage when the bill is taken up again
next week. The Baltimore Justice Campaign, which handles issues
facing the gay community in this largely Roman Catholic city, began
working in December to marshal support for the bill. It prohibits
discrimination against homosexuals in housing, employment,
education, health and welfare services.
   Similar bills have been passed in several other cities,
including New York, Philadelphia, Washington, D.C., and Atlanta.
   Baltimore's Catholic leadership has opposed the bill, but this
time gay rights advocates got critical backing from Mayor Kurt L.
Schmoke and City Council President Mary Pat Clarke. During his 1987
mayoral campaign, Schmoke promised support for the measure, which
his predecessor in City Hall, Gov. William Donald Schaefer, had
never endorsed.
   Opponents, including placard-carrying parents pushing their
children in strollers in front of City Hall on Monday, immediately
vowed to collect enough signatures to force the issue to a
referendum.
   An amendment exempted religious organizations from the bill,
based on the doctrine of the separation of church and state, Mrs.
Clarke said.
   ``We leave some judgments to God,'' she said, but try to give
everyone an equal position ``at the starting gate.''
   Councilman Mike Curran, explaining his negative vote, said he
had asked himself, ``is this a civil rights matter or is it a
special rights matter?'' and concluded it ``would confer special
rights on certain people.''
   Councilman Joseph T. Landers III said it came down to voting his
conscience.
   ``I think we need to send a message out,'' he said. ``Even if it
only affects the lives of half a dozen people ... we will be
recognizing justice.
   ``We tried to protect religious principles. We've also looked at
the issue of discrimination. In my heart, I know from all of the
values I was brought up with, I can't deny there is
discrimination.''
   John Glorioso, sporting a Baltimore Justice Campaign sticker,
said opponents who gave religious arguments for their opposition
were failing to show Christian attitudes.
   ``Their concerns are really unjustified. They're unable to be
rational. They're really fixated on parts of the Bible and seemed
to ignore other parts of the Bible. Basically it's a hysterical
issue,'' Glorioso said.
   Nonetheless, supporters and opponents peaceably sat side by side
during the council session.
   Next to Glorioso, wearing ``Vote No'' stickers, were Susan Walsh
and her husband, Mike Walsh.
   Although they have no children, Mrs. Walsh said they were
``concerned about the effect it's going to have on our children.''
   She said opponents feared the precedent set by establishing
homosexuals as a minority. If students are taught the history of
such minorities as women and blacks, ``then you could have
Homosexual Week and teach about how they got started and what they
do,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
