<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TortureVictims     05-17 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Torture Victims,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Tortured By Drug Dealers Over $90 in Missing Crack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two suspected drug dealers trying to recover $90
worth of crack cocaine stabbed and tortured three people, dousing
one with boiling water before rubbing salt into his wounds,
authorities said.
   A 28-year-old man was in fair condition Tuesday at Parkland
Memorial Hospital with multiple knife wounds and second-degree
burns on his back and buttocks, said hospital spokesman Tom Geddie.
   He was cut and stabbed in the chest and legs more than 80 times
Sunday, officials said. His 27-year-old wife was bound and whipped,
and a 17-year-old man was treated for second-degree burns he
suffered when boiling water was poured on him, Geddie said.
   Police said the victims told them they sold crack and cocaine,
and two suppliers were trying to recover either the crack or $90.
The assailants came to an apartment occupied by the older man to
collect daily drug-sale proceeds, according to police reports.
   One victim said the crack had been flushed down a toilet the
night before because of a rumor of a police raid. No raid occurred,
but one victim said the apartment was ransacked to make it appear
there had been one so the suppliers could be told police had seized
the drugs.
   But the assailants did not believe the story, said police.
   No one had been arrested Tuesday.
</TEXT>
