<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Embezzle     05-17 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Embezzle,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Late Jewish Leader Suspected of Embezzling Reparation Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former leader of West Germany's
Jewish community is suspected of embezzling millions of dollars
from government reparations to Nazi Holocaust survivors, his
successor said Tuesday.
   Werner Nachmann is suspected of stealing more than $6 million in
interest accumulated from Holocaust survivor funds before his death
in January, said Heinz Galinski, Nachmann's successor as president
of the Jewish Council of West Germany.
   ``I am shocked, horrified and furious that such a thing could be
even possible,'' Galinski said.
   Hessischer Rundfunk radio in Frankfurt reported the Jewish
Council believes Nachmann embezzled about $19 million from West
German government funds for Holocaust survivors between 1980 and
1987 but Galinski said the radio's figure was ``pure speculation.''
   About $236 million were made available by the West German
government in 1980 for Holocaust survivors all over the world who
had never made reparations claims.
   The funds were in addition to about $47 billion already paid out
by West Germany to Holocaust survivors or victims' families who had
applied for reparations.
   ``After the death of Werner Nachmann, financial irregularities
of considerable proportions were discovered'' in transactions
involving the funds approved in 1980, Galinski said.
   ``Learning of this surprised and dismayed the council's
directorate, which immediately informed (West German) government
leaders,'' he said in an interview from his West Berlin office.
   Galinski said the Jewish Council has hired financial experts to
look into the accusations, and the investigation is expected to
take two to three weeks.
   Nachmann was in charge of the funds to be handed out to
Holocaust survivors, Hessischer Rundfunk radio reported.
   The radio said the Jewish council believes Nachmann transferred
millions of dollars to dummy corporations ``which seem to be
unknown to anyone.''
   Galinski said the Jewish Council has asked a civil court in
Karlsruhe to freeze money from Nachmann's estate pending an
investigation into the allegations.
   A court spokesman said no action has yet been taken on the
council's application.
   ``This is still in a preliminary stage,'' spokesman Alfred
Mueller said. ``More documents and other information will be coming
in on this matter.''
   Mueller said that if the allegations against Nachmann are proven
true, the money would have to be repaid from the deceased Jewish
leader's estate.
   Galinski said he was deeply upset about the possibility that
Nachmann may have embezzled money from the accounts.
   ``This has presented me with the most serious problem I have
ever faced in my 40 years of working for the Jewish community,'' he
said.
   The 62-year-old Nachmann died Jan. 21 of a heart attack at his
home in Karlsruhe.
   He had been active in trying to help heal wounds in West Germany
left by the Holocaust, in which about 6 million Jews were killed
during Nazi rule.
   Nachmann's family fled Nazi Germany to France in 1938. He
returned to Karlsruhe in 1945 and began working toward
re-establishing Jewish communities in the country.
   About 525,000 Jews lived in Germany when the Nazis took power in
1933. West Germany has about 30,000 Jewish residents today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
