<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Houston,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renovations On Whitney Houston's House Upsets Some Neighbors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENDHAM TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renovations and landscaping work
on singer Whitney Houston's new home has upset neighbors who don't
like the construction vehicles parked there.
   Houston, who was born in Newark, bought the five-acre estate
last summer and began installing a swimming pool, sound studio and
tennis courts in the fall, said township officials.
   Residents are not opposed to having a celebrity move in, but the
trucks have disrupted the quiet neighborhood, said Ruth Kollmer,
who lives four houses away.
   But Mayor Marian R. Wysong said the problem has been
exaggerated, and many of the construction vehicles are parked on
the singer's property.
   Police have gone to the site several times but the vehicles have
been legally parked, Police Chief F. Herbert Herron said Tuesday.
   The 24-year-old singer has missed much of the flap because she's
been on a European tour since mid-April.
   Sylvia Weiner, a spokeswoman for Houston, said she can't
comment. ``Her private residence is not something we are given
information on,'' she said.
