<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Reforms     05-17 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reforms,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party to Consider Limiting Leader's Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party conference next month will
consider setting limits on the length of time its top leader stays
in power, a top official said.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev, whose job as party general secretary is
that which may be limited if the party acts, himself has said the
party needs to find ways to replace aging officials.
   Dmitri A. Lisovolik, a deputy to party Central Committee
secretary Anatoly F. Dobrynin, told members of the Young Presidents
Organization and a reporter Monday night that proposals have been
introduced to limit the party leader to two or three terms of eight
years each.
   He did not mention proposals for age limits, and said he could
not predict whether the proposals for fixed terms would be adopted.
   Lisovolik indicated that support had been growing for limits to
the terms of Communist Party leaders.
   A second official told a U.S. newspaper that if limits are
adopted, it should not be considered a blow to Gorbachev.
   Many letters have appeared in recent weeks in the Soviet press
proposing fixed terms and age limits for the country's leaders, an
indication that the idea is being brought back under consideration.
   Gorbachev raised the idea of limits in the highest echelons of
Soviet power creating a mechanism to replace aging officials in top
party jobs at a January 1987 meeting of the Central Committee.
   He apparently met with opposition then because the meeting's
final documents only made passing reference to it.
   The Soviet leader has said more freqent turnover would make
officials more accountable to the people. He has criticized
middle-level officials for falling behind his calls for a
restructuring of Soviet society, and says that confusion about his
reform policy reaches to the highest levels of the Communist Party.
   Gorbachev has pushed aside many older Communist Party leaders
who were uncomfortable with his policies, but still faces stiff
opposition.
   He has sharply criticized the 1964-82 rule of former Communist
Party chief Leonid I. Brezhnev as a period of economic stagnation
and corruption.
   Dictator Josef V. Stalin's abuses during his 29 years in power
also are coming under increasing criticism as Soviets re-examine
their past.
   The party conference that begins June 28 is considered to be a
key opportunity for Gorbachev to strengthen his hand in the
policy-making Central Committee.
   In its Tuesday's editions, The Washington Post quoted Central
Committee member Georgi A. Arbatov as saying there is a ``good
chance'' the party conference will back proposals limiting the
general secretary's term.
   Arbatov said the changes would not indicate any setback for
Gorbachev, who has been general secretary since March 1985.
   The Young Presidents Organization is a group of foreign business
leaders, including Americans. A delegation of the group arrived in
Moscow on Saturday.
   Lisovolik, 50, has been chief of the U.S. section of the
International Department of the Central Committee since December
1984. He served briefly in the Soviet Embassy in Washington under
Dobrynin, who was ambassador from 1962 to 1986. Dobrynin is Central
Committee secretary in charge of foreign affairs.
</TEXT>
