<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     05-17 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial of Accused TWA Hijacker to Start in July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi, indicted in
the United States in the 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner, will
stand trial in a West German juvenile court in July on charges
stemming from the air piracy.
   U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was shot to death during the
hijacking that began on June 14, 1985, on a flight from Athens to
Rome, and ended up in Beirut. Thirty-nine Americans were held
captive for 17 days in the ordeal.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, was indicted in the United
States on air piracy and murder charges related to the act.
   West Germany turned down a U.S. extradition request last year,
but after two West Germans were kidnapped in Beirut by the
defendant's brother, West Germany said he would be tried here.
   Hamadi was arrested in Frankfurt on Jan. 13, 1987, while
carrying liquid explosives and false documents, and has been jailed
in Frankfurt since then. He was charged by West German officials on
Feb. 8 with air piracy, murder, illegal possession of explosives
and carrying a false passport.
   On Jan. 17, 1987, West German businessman Rudolf Cordes was
kidnapped in Beirut and three days later another West German,
Alfred Schmidt also was abducted in Lebanon.
   Hamadi's 29-year-old brother, Abbas, was arrested at Frankfurt
airport Jan. 26, 1987 after arriving on a flight from Beirut. He
was charged with kidnapping the two West Germans in an attempt to
win freedom for his brother.
   Abbas Hamadi was found guilty by a Duesseldorf court last month
in connection with kidnapping the two West Germans and sentenced to
13 years in prison.
   Schmidt was released in September in what his captors said was a
``goodwill gesture,'' but Cordes remains a hostage.
   Justice officials have decided to open the case against Mohammed
Hamadi in juvenile court in July, Hesse state court spokesman Falk
Thomas said at a news conference. No exact starting date was given
for the trial, which is expected to last several months.
   The final decision to try Mohammed Hamadi before a juvenile
court was made because his age at the time of the crime could not
be determined, he said.
   Mohammed Hamadi first told West German authorities he was born
on June 13, 1964, but later he said he was two years younger.
   Under West German law, an adolescent is described as between
ages 18 and 21, an adult 21 and older, and a juvenile as less than
18. Juvenile courts also handle adolescent cases.
   ``If he is found guilty and the court determines that he was 21
at the time the crimes he is charged with actually began, the
maximum sentence is life imprisonment,'' Thomas said.
   A juvenile court may give a life sentence to an adolescent based
on a determination of personal maturity at the time a crime began,
despite age, said Thomas.
   He added, however, that the usual maximum sentence is between 10
and 15 years in prison for an adolescent not judged as mature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Staples     05-17 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Staples,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hoarding Continues In Nominal Price Freeze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgrade residents have gone on a
shopping spree, snapping up important consumer items because of a
government decision to postpone the lifting of a price freeze.
   Flour, sugar, coffee, detergents and cooking oil were all
reported to be in short supply, newspapers said Tuesday.
   Even furniture has become a hot item.
   Prices are expected to rise by fifty percent and more when the
six-month price freeze is lifted later this month.
   The largest circulation daily, Vecernje Novosti, described the
buying spree as ``A Fever on the Eve of the De-Freeze'' in a
front-page headline Tuesday.
   The newspaper and Belgrade authorities said sales of detergents
went up by 100 percent last week, while sales of flour rose by 50
percent, of cooking oil by 70 percent and of sugar by 45 percent.
   The daily published an appeal by Belgrade authorities not to
hoard staple items already in short supply.
   ``There is no need to hoard and create unnecessary queues,'' the
daily quoted the appeal as saying.
   According to the newspaper, shelves storing staple items in
highest demand ``are virtually empty.''
   Officials promised to restock the supply of coffee, the first
item to disappear from Belgrade shops, from emergency reserves.
Vecernje Novosti said 250 tons of coffee would be made available,
but the federal government, meanwhile, announced a 3 percent price
increase on coffee going into effect immediately.
   Yugoslavians pay about $13 for 2.2 pounds of coffee.
   The Politika Ekspres daily quoted the owner of one store as
saying his furniture sales had doubled over the past two months.
   Local media have reported that about 80 percent of the country's
manufacturers will announce new prices for their goods when the
government lifts the freeze.
   The end of the six-month price freeze was originally scheduled
for May 15, but was postponed for at least 10 days, until the
government secures about $300 million in emergency credits from the
West.
   The government has not set a specific date for the price freeze
to be lifted, but it is expected to be before the end of May.
   The government said the emergency funds were needed to implement
an economic package made in conjunction with the International
Monetary Fund.
   The package of economic measures, which includes the lifting of
the price freeze, is intended to reduce Europe's highest inflation
of 170 percent and help Yugoslavia repay its $20 billion foreign
debt.
   Yugoslavia is expected to secure $1.4 billion in new loans from
the IMF, Western governments and banks this year.
   Vecernje Novosti said sales taxes were increased Monday on
carpets, ready to wear clothes, soaps, tires, tractors and coal
stoves.
   The government's austerity program is likely to contribute to a
further decline of Yugoslavs' living standards which have already
fallen by one-third since 1980. Labor unrest is also expected to
grow.
</TEXT>
