<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     05-17 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Will Go On, Jackson Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KLAMATH FALLS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As primary voters went to the polls,
Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson reminded Oregon
supporters on Tuesday that he is the only candidate who made a
major effort here.
   ``I campaign amongst you because I do not take you for
granted,'' said Jackson. ``Oregon can make a big decision today to
change the course of America.''
   Jackson campaigned five days in Oregon in an attempt to build
momentum heading into the crucial California primary on June 7.
   Jackson noted the 34th anniversary of the Supreme Court's Brown
vs. Board of Education ruling that desegregated the nation's public
schools but said schools remain segregated economically.
   ``In public schools, 34 years later, some children get $5,000
invested in them and some get $1,600,'' he said. ``There must be
equal access for education. It's legally sound. It's morally right
and it's cost efficient.''
   Jackson repeated his familiar comparison between the cost of
school and the cost of incarceration. He said one year of high
school for a student costs $2,500 in Klamath County, compared with
a $15,000 price tag to house an inmate for a year in the Klamath
County Jail.
   ``Unless we have equal access to education, we have unequal
access to jail,'' he said.
   Jackson was scheduled to meet Wednesday with California leaders
of Jewish groups, with whom his relations remain strained. But the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith said Tuesday it would
boycott the closed meeting.
   ``To have it behind closed doors ... just creates more potential
for disharmony between the Jewish community and Jackson than ought
to exist,'' said ADL regional director David A. Lehrer.
   Jackson has been urged to mend fences with the Jewish community,
still rankled by Jackson's 1979 embrace of Palestine Liberation
Organization leader Yassar Arafat and his 1984 reference to New
York as ``Hymietown.''
   Jews comprise about 10 percent of the California electorate.
</TEXT>
