<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCrash-Pearman     05-17 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Pearman,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Had Premonition Before His Death, Uncle Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bus Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two days before his church bus
collided head-on with a pickup truck, driver John Pearman told
relatives ``something felt wrong.''
   Pearman, the Hardin County circuit clerk and assistant pastor at
Radcliff First Assembly of God church, had driven youngsters from
the church to Kings Island amusement park as many as 10 times
before but ``didn't feel right about this one,'' said his uncle,
state Sen. Virgil Pearman.
   ``He didn't want to go,'' the older Pearman said. ``In fact, he
wasn't going to go because he felt funny about it, but then the
person who was going to take his place didn't, and John didn't want
to disappoint anyone, so he went.''
   The fiery collision on Interstate 71 Saturday night killed
Pearman and 26 others, mostly young people from the church who were
returning from the park north of Cincinnati. Authorities charged a
Worthville man with 27 counts of capital murder after tests showed
his blood-alcohol level was more than twice the legal limit.
   Ronald Hockman, minister of the North Hardin Christian Church
and president of the Dove Academy, a school operated by First
Assembly of God, knew Pearman had been trying to find someone else
to drive the bus.
   ``I hadn't heard about any premonitions,'' he said. ``But I do
know he tried real hard to find others to drive the bus. But I
don't know why.''
   Friends remembered Pearman as a likeable role model in church
and at the courthouse.
   ``He was a guy who doesn't come down the road every day,'' said
Bill Faulkner, who served with Pearman for two years as Hardin
County magistrate. ``He was always a real gentleman and a real
class guy.''
   ``I knew him all his life,'' said Allen T. Bell, who served on
the city council for more than 20 years. ``He was a very dedicated,
very enthusiastic, and very good Christian boy growing up. And he
stayed that way.''
   Pearman's family moved to Radcliff shortly after he was born 37
years ago.
   Shortly after high school Pearman joined the Army and served in
Vietnam from 1971 to 1973.
   ``When he came back, he was more seasoned and more mature,''
Bell said. ``He never talked to me about it in detail, but the war
changed his perspective on things. He seemed to know more what he
wanted. And that was to serve others in church and government.''
</TEXT>
