<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Greyhound-Trailways     05-17 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greyhound-Trailways,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Federal Approval for Greyhound-Trailways Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interstate Commerce Commission gave final
approval Tuesday to the $80 million merger of Greyhound and
Trailways, the nation's two largest bus companies.
   The two bus lines have been operating as a single carrier since
last July when the ICC gave temporary approval to the merger
because Trailways was on the verge of going bankrupt while
operating independently.
   Greyhound Lines Inc. bought its biggest competitor, Trailways
Lines Inc., for $80 million. The deal did not affect 34 small,
regional bus companies around the country that also use the
Trailways name.
   Fred Currey, Greyhound's chairman, called the ICC decision ``a
positive development in Greyhound's efforts to rebuild the
intercity passenger bus business ... and thereby increase
competiton in the travel market.''
   The ICC approved the deal by a 3-2 vote.
   The final merger was likely to be little noticed by bus
travelers.
   George Gravley, a Greyhound spokesman, said the company would
continue to use the Trailways trademark on buses and terminals in
parts of the country where the name is well known.
   ``Obviously, we're delighted (by the decision),'' Gravley said
in an interview from the company's Dallas headquarters. He said
Greyhound had expected final ICC approval since the commission gave
its tentative clearance to the deal last July.
   Together, Greyhound and Trailways carried more than 33 million
passengers last year. The combined company, which has its
headquarters in Dallas, has 3,750 buses and terminals or ticket
agents in 2,500 communities.
   Greyhound had announced in June 1987 that it planned to purchase
Trailways. The ICC granted its temporary approval to the merger two
weeks later after the Justice Department concluded that as an
independent company Trailways had ``virtually no chance of being
restructured as a viable entity.''
</TEXT>
