<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FeedGrains     05-17 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Feed Grains,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Says Total Feed Grain Production May Increase This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers have indicated they intend to plant
fewer total acres of feed grains this spring, but an Agriculture
Department report said Tuesday that total 1988 production may
increase because of greater corn acreage in high-yielding states.
   ``Production of feed grains is forecast at 219 million metric
tons, 2 percent above 1987's 215 million,'' the department's
Economic Research Service said.
   Besides corn, other feed grains include sorghum, oats and
barley. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4
bushels of corn.
   In a related report, the government's Joint Agricultural Weather
Facility said that by mid-May, corn planting had advanced rapidly
to about 88 percent completed in the major producing states,
matching the fast pace of a year ago. Normally, only 66 percent of
the acreage is planted by May 15.
</TEXT>
