<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDS-Justice     05-17 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Justice,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fired AIDS Victim Complains About Justice Department Actions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS victim fired from his clerk-typist job
at the Justice Department said Tuesday he will turn down a one-year
temporary position offered to him in the wake of publicity about
the incident.
   ``I'm not going to accept. They owe me my job back. They fired
me because I had AIDS,'' Mark Gregory told Rep. Patricia Schroeder,
D-Colo., chairman of the House civil service subcommittee.
   Gregory said he has taken 30 days off since learning last
October that he has AIDS-related complex, a precurser to full-blown
AIDS _ nearly half of the time to participate in a treatment study
at another federal agency, the National Institutes of Health.
   Despite what he called an excellent six-month evaluation early
this year, Gregory was fired April 25 on the grounds that his
absences made him incapable of performing his job.
   The firing came several weeks after the Office of Personnel
Management had instituted a policy saying federal workers with AIDS
had to be treated like those with other serious medical problems
and could not be discriminated against.
   Mrs. Schroeder said ``a newly stated, enlightened policy ...
appears to have been thrown overboard within the first month.'' She
said she was dismayed by the Justice Department action and also by
the department's refusal to testify Tuesday on the grounds of short
notice and the press of other business.
   ``We will not let this go,'' she said. ``We want to make sure
that federal policy is leading the way and not catching up.''
   Mrs. Schroeder said she will hold another hearing June 2 and
expects the Justice Department to testify unless the controversy is
resolved to Gregory's satisfaction before then.
   The Justice Department offered Gregory the temporary post on
Monday, five days after The Washington Post published an article
describing the incident.
   But Gregory said he would have no protection in a temporary job.
``They could a week later say ... we don't need you anymore,'' he
said.
   He also said the temporary job was in the same office as his old
job, where he said a supervisor had violated his confidentiality
and word of his disease had spread among co-workers.
   ``That would be an impossible situation,'' Gregory said. ``They
are insensitive to AIDS. I doubt very seriously they've made any
educational effort since the day I was fired. I don't know how
people could change their attitudes that fast.''
   Gregory said he took two weeks off immediately following his
diagnosis at the suggestion of a supervisor who told him to ``get
my act together.'' He said another six days were devoted to
doctor's appointments and dealing with his roommate's illness and
death from AIDS shortly before Gregory was fired.
   Gregory said he took the rest of the time, 14 days, to
participate in an NIH study recommended by his doctor. He did it
even though his advance request for leave, accompanied by a copy of
the NIH study plan and his own consent form, was never granted. The
reason given, he said, was insufficient documentation.
   ``I decided it was more important to save my life than to deal
with them,'' Gregory said. ``It was like they were trying to
interfere with something that was going to save a lot of people's
lives.''
   Gregory said he knew of one other federal worker with AIDS _ a
man who eventually went blind from it. His supervisors at the Labor
Department ``went so far as to hire a reader for him,'' Gregory
said. ``He worked for a long time.''
   Gregory is losing his health insurance as a result of the
firing. However, he said much of his experimental treatment at NIH
is free and as an Air Force veteran, he is eligible for VA benefits.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The virus
most often is spread through close contact with blood, blood
products or semen from infected persons.
   As of May 2, AIDS had been diagnosed in about 60,852 Americans,
of whom more than half, or 34,088 have died since June 1981,
according to the Centers for Disease Control. No one is known to
have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
