<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0727 05-17 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0727,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Retains Confidence in Meese, Ducks Questions on Noriega
Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines a0727-a0736</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, discussing two of his most
persistent problems, said Tuesday that he retains ``complete
confidence'' in Attorney General Edwin Meese III and declined
comment on reports he was offering to drop drug charges against
Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Asked whether he believed in astrology, Reagan said, ``I don't
guide my life by it.`` But he said he could not say whether it was
valid. ``I don't know enough about it,'' he added.
   Reagan opened his news conference with a statement hailing the
agreement to start Senate debate on the U.S.-Soviet arms treaty and
the March trade figures, which showed a dramatic drop in the
monthly deficit in the balance of exports and imports.
   Most of the questions during the brief session concerned Noriega.
   ``We are in the midst of real negotiations,'' said Reagan,
referring to discussions the administration hopes will lead to
Noriega's relinquishing power. ``I can't comment further on this.''
   There have been persistent reports that the administration has
offered to drop drug charges against Noriega in exchange for his
leaving the country at least until after elections are held.
   Reagan said much of what has been written about the negotiations
has been ``based on some kind of leaks or misinformation, because
there are no facts to sustain it.''
   On Meese, the president said, ``I have complete confidence in
him.''
   As for the firing of Terry Eastland, the Justice Department
spokesman who has been defended by conservatives, the president
said there may be ``more than meets the eye.''
   He did not elaborate on that statement except to tell reporters
they should ``talk to the atttorney genenral about that.''
   Reagan also dismissed reports that he and his wife, Nancy, have
considered astrological signs in determining his schedule.
   ``Nothing of that kind was ever going on,'' he said.
   ``It didn't happen that way at all,'' Reagan said of allegations
by his former chief of staff Donald Regan that an astrologer
influences decisions on presidential scheduling.
   Reagan, who leaves next week for a summit in Moscow with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, said he was confident that the Senate
would ratify the INF treaty, which he described as a ``diplomatic
milestone.''
   The agreement would eliminate U.S. and Soviet intermediate-range
nuclear missiles from Europe.
   On trade, the president called the $4.1 billion drop in the
nation's trade deficit ``good news, the best news on this front
since March of 1985.''
   He cited the improved trade figures as evidence that restrictive
trade legislation recently passed by the Democratic-controlled
Congress was not needed.
   He said he expected to act on that legislation ``within a couple
of days.'' Reagan is expected to veto the bill.
</TEXT>
