<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Khomeini     05-17 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Khomeini,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Urges End to Divisions after Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini told Iran's
leaders Tuesday to patch up their differences now that
parliamentary elections are over.
   The elections strengthened the hand of economic radicals with
whom the 87-year-old revolutionary patriarch has appeared to side
recently.
   They seek land reform, price controls and a minimum wage.
Opposing them are conservatives backed by the ``bazaaris,'' or
merchant class.
   A report Monday in the French newspaper Le Monde said nine
people were killed in the central province of Isfahan during
election violence between conservatives and Revolutionary Guards, a
radical organization with personal loyalty to Khomeini.
   Speaking at the end of the Moslem holy month of Ramadan,
Khomeini also wished death upon President Reagan and Saddam
Hussein, the president of Iraq, with which Iran has been at war
since September 1980.
   His remarks to a gathering at his home in north Tehran were
broadcast by state radio and television. Khomeini said in reference
to elections for the Majlis, the Iranian parliament:
   ``A Majlis without diversity of views is an imperfect Majlis ..
. but the outcome should not result in dividing us into two hostile
groups.''
   He said there were attempts to ``create discord,'' which he did
not describe, but ``thanks to God, they did not succeed.''
   In what appeared to be his first public reference to a division
between radical and conservative thinking, Khomeini said:
   ``There are not two fronts. Of course, there are two ways of
thinking and it should be so. There are two opinions, and there
should be different tastes and views. But different tastes do not
mean the people should not be on good terms with each other.''
   The first round of elections for the 270-seat parliament was
held April 8 and the second last Friday. Although little detailed
information was available from the latest round, results favored
the radicals.
   President Ali Khamenei told the gathering:
   ``During the elections there were some harsh words said between
certain candidates, or their followers. Now that, thank God, the
elections have been successfully completed, these arguments should
end too.''
   Le Monde said a conservative religious leader in Isfahan
province, Hojatoleslam Ahmadi, resigned during the election
campaign as prayer leader of the mosque in the town of
Khomeinishahr to protest ``certain electoral methods'' used by the
Interior Ministry.
   His resignation prompted violent protests by his supporters in
the town, which were suppressed by Revolutionary Guards, the paper
reported. Le Monde said three people were killed and several
arrested, including Ahmadi.
   He was imprisoned in the city of Isfahan, 12 miles away.
Supporters demonstrated there for his release and some reports said
six more people were killed, according to Le Monde.
   It said radicals won the elections in the Isfahan area and that
made the conflict worse.
   Khomeini said Tuesday the best prayer for President Reagan and
Hussein, the president of Iraq, ``is to wish them to die.''
   ``This is for their benefit,'' he said, ``whereas if you want to
curse them you'd better wish them a long life. The more they stay
alive, the worse their situation will become and their hell will
become hotter. Therefore if you wish them death, they will die
quicker and avoid the hotter hell.''
</TEXT>
