<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StarkMemorial     05-17 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stark Memorial,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memorial Service for Slain USS Stark Seaman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stark Anniversary Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives and friends of the Navy seamen
killed during last year's attack on the USS Stark gathered at
Arlington National Cemetery on Tuesday to commemorate what one
mother called ``unnecessary'' deaths.
   ``I don't feel he should have been there or any of them should
have been there and I don't feel they should be there now.'' a
tearful Kathleen Ciletta of Philadelphia said of the deaths of her
son, John A. Ciletta Jr., and his 36 shipmates last May 17. ``It
was very unnecessary.''
   Although Mrs. Ciletta said it was important that the memory of
her son be kept alive in memorial services, she still had ``a lot
of anger'' in her heart.
   ``Anger toward the whole situation because I feel like he was
killed for all the wrong reasons,'' she said while clutching a
miniature replica of the ``Lone Soldier'' statue, presented to her
by Rear Adm. William Thompson, president of the Naval Memorial
Foundation.
   During the service Vice Adm. John W. Nyquist, assistant chief of
naval operations for surface warfare, praised the slain seamen as
examples of the ``selfless dedication and indomitable spirit of
courage and patriotism of the men and women of the armed services.''
   ``We share a special and timeless bond _ a bond that only
sailors and their families know,'' Nyquist said. ``It is a bond so
great that nothing can undo it, not even death.''
   The Stark, one of several U.S. ships stationed in the Persian
Gulf to escort tankers and other vessels with American registry,
was attacked by an Iraqi jet presumed to be ``friendly.''
   No effort was made to warn the plane away until it was too late
and the fighter had fired two Exocet missiles. The second missile
nearly sank the ship.
   A Navy board of inquiry concluded the Stark's officers should
have prevented the tragedy by warning away the Iraqi aircraft.
   Since the Stark tragedy, the Navy's rules of engagement in the
gulf have been changed to allow ship commanders to open fire on any
plane or vessel that comes close enough to fire upon their ship.
   ``If the policy one year ago today was what it is today, I
wouldn't be here today. Neither would my son,'' Mrs. Ciletta said.
``Like I said, it was a little too late for my boy.''
   The Ciletta family was chosen to represent the families of the
Stark crewmen in the memorial service, said Carmella LaSpada, head
of No Great Love, the sponsor of the program.
   No Greater Love is a non-profit support group for families of
POWs, MIAs, hostage and terrorist victims.
   Following the wreath-laying ceremony, Mrs. Ciletta planted a
kiss on her son's tombstone.
   ``He had just turned 21 when he was killed,'' she said of her
only son. ``He turned 22 last week.''
</TEXT>
