<DOCNO> AP880517-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZeroTolerance-Cars     05-17 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance-Cars,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vehicles Seized in Drug Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs officials seized 136 vehicles and
arrested 82 people, mostly Americans returning from Canada, in the
first 40 days of the ``zero tolerance'' drug crackdown, a spokesman
said.
   ``Some of them can't believe that you're actually going to seize
their vehicle and place them under arrest,'' Mike Jordan, customs
inspector in Detroit said Monday. ``To them, it's always just been
just another trip over a bridge.''
   Previously, when inspectors found small amounts of a drug, the
suspect was fined up to $600 and allowed to drive away. Under the
Zero Tolerance program, inspectors automatically seize vehicles if
any quantity of a drug is found.
   The vehicles were seized in the Detroit district, including the
Sault Ste. Marie and Port Huron areas, he said.
   Nationally, 27 boats and 700 vehicles have been seized since
April 11, officials said.
   The program received national attention with recent seizures of
the yachts Monkey Business and Ark Royal after small amounts of
marijuana were found on them. Monkey Business is the charter yacht
that once ferried presidential contender Gary Hart and model Donna
Rice.
   Jordan said about 75 percent of the suspects arrested at
Michigan border crossings have been U.S. citizens returning from
Canada, and marijuana and hashish have been the drugs most often
found.
   Terence Heverin, U.S. Customs Director of Inspection and Control
for the Detroit District, said Tuesday he doesn't know how many of
the vehicles have been returned because that is up to the federal
court, where people cited at the border are ordered to appear.
   But he said few of the people are jailed.
   The amount of drugs seized April 1 to May 10 range from a trace
amount of hashish and a pipe, to four grams of marijuana found in
an 18-wheeler, Jordan said.
   ``We have internal guidelines on the amounts of substances we're
looking for, but basically it is in the personal use quantities,''
Heverin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
