<DOCNO> AP880517-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSEffort     05-17 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Effort,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publishing Industry Unites in AIDS Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the nation's leading publishers have
joined the fight against AIDS with a community action book
featuring advice from celebrities, politicians and a Vermont high
school class, organizers said Tuesday.
   The 126-page paperback, ``You Can Do Something About AIDS,'' was
created with the time, money and know-how of more than two dozen
publishing concerns.
   It will be given away at bookstores around the country beginning
June 1 _ about a week after the U.S. government is to start mailing
explicit brochures about acquired immune deficiency syndrome to 107
million households.
   ``This is the `Live Aid' or the `Farm Aid' of the publishing
industry,'' said Sasha Alyson, founder of Alyson Publications in
Boston and the project coordinator. ``It's a massive effort to
raise the public's consciousness about this terrible disease by
showing people exactly what they can do to fight it.''
   The authors include Elizabeth Taylor; U.S. Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop; U.S. Sen. Lowell Weicker Jr., R-Conn.; Abigail Van
Buren; Whoopi Goldberg; actor and writer Harvey Fierstein; Greg
Louganis, Olympic gold medalist diver; and former White House Press
Secretary Jody Powell.
   ``This book will help provide concrete examples of what anyone
can do to make a contribution in the fight against AIDS,'' Taylor
writes in the introduction.
   The authors tell how to educate children, parents and friends
about AIDS and protect oneself from it; volunteer for AIDS-related
activities; write letters to elected officials; and change bigoted
attitudes about the fatal disease.
   ``If you're housebound, you could offer baby-sitting help for a
volunteer who's providing other services,'' suggests Goldberg.
   ``An AIDS benefit show need be no more than a local talent
showcase,'' writes Fierstein. ``What's important is the concern,
not the content.''
   ``Explaining does not mean condoning,'' advises Dear Abby.
``Children become sexually active earlier today than they did even
20 years ago. Parents will never reverse that trend by keeping
children ignorant.''
   ``Working on the AIDS issue at our school meant breaking a
barrier,'' writes a social studies class taught by Jeff Lavin at
Springfield High School in Vermont. ``AIDS _ and more particularly,
homosexuality _ had always been a subject no one was willing to
talk about in the classroom.''
   The students suggest other classes enlist guest speakers _
including an AIDS patient, preferably from the audience's own age
group.
   ``Some students, teachers or parents may spread fears that
letting a person with AIDS come into the school is dangerous.
Address and rebut that kind of hysteria directly,'' they write.
   The Book-of-the Month Club and Ingram Book Co. published an
initial run of 300,000 copies. An additional 150,000 copies are due
around June 6, with a third printing later in June, said project
spokeswoman Annik La Farge.
   More than 20 members of Congress have endorsed the project, she
said.
   Alyson estimated donations for the first printing at about
$200,000 in cash, materials and services such as writing, printing,
distribution, marketing and publicity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
