<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusAccident     05-17 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Accident,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Said Something Was Wrong Just Before Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON CORNERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver of a converted school
bus reportedly told passengers there was something wrong with the
vehicle just before it crashed at the bottom of a hill, killing
three people and injuring 20, authorities said Tuesday.
   State police Sgt. Dennis Cody said investigators are trying to
determine whether mechanical failure or high speed contributed to
Monday afternoon's accident.
   Eight people, including driver Lewis Taylor, were still
hospitalized Tuesday, hospital officials said. Taylor was in
serious condition, suffering from head injuries, cuts and broken
bones.
   The bus, carrying a group of mentally handicapped people, was
traveling down a steep hill and failed to make a sharp right turn
at an intersection, Cody said. It hit a utility pole, tipped over
on its right side and came to rest 30 feet from the road and a few
feet from Little Wappingers Creek.
   When asked about reports that Taylor had spoken of a mechanical
problem, Cody said, ``We are aware of statements made by people at
the (accident) scene and on the bus that the driver made a
statement like that prior to the accident.''
   Taylor reportedly repeated his assertions to witnesses at the
crash site, but Cody refused to say what the problem was. Police
said no charges have been filed.
   Except for Taylor and a bus attendant, all the passengers were
mentally handicapped people working for Rehabilitation Programs
Inc. of the Town of Poughkeepsie. They were being driven home when
the accident happened, Cody said.
   Chris Scott, who lives nearby, said he had seen many accidents
at the turn in the past five years and described it as
``outrageously sharp.''
   A state police accident reconstruction expert is expected to
take at least five days before releasing a report on the accident,
Cody said.
   Three passengers were in critical condition Tuesday, while one
listed in serious condition and three in stable condition,
according to officials at St. Francis Hospital in Poughkeepsie and
the Westchester Medical Center in Valhalla.
   The bus was owned by Laidlaw Transit, headquartered in Van Nuys,
Calif. Tayler, 44, has worked for Laidlaw for 2{ years. Clinton
Corners is about 60 miles north of New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
