<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SaksFire     05-17 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Saks Fire,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspicious Fire Causes Light Damage to Saks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspicious storeroom fire forced the
evacuation of Saks Fifth Avenue's flagship department store
Tuesday, officials said.
   The fire occurred one day short of the one-year anniversary of a
fire that forced the evacuation of the store. Saks spokeswoman
Susan Stern said investigators and store officials ``haven't made a
connection yet. It could be a coincidence.''
   The fire in a fifth-floor stockroom was put out quickly by two
ceiling sprinklers and a nearby hose, fire spokesman John Mulligan
said. There were no injuries, and Ms. Stern said damage was limited
to some sportswear.
   Another department spokesman, Efrain Parilla, said the fire was
labeled suspicious because the storeroom was not considered prone
to fire.
   Dozens of people were evacuated.
   On May 18, 1987, a smoky fire in an empty brownstone building
next to Saks forced the evacuation of the department store and
caused four minor injuries. Mulligan said he did not know the
outcome of an investigation into the cause of that blaze.
</TEXT>
