<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Press     05-17 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Press,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Criticized For Press Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government opponents on Tuesday
denounced warnings given to broadcasters to exercise restraint and
the opposition newspaper La Prensa declared: ``The Muzzle Law
Returns.''
   But the broadcasters appeared undaunted by the threats of
sanctions and continued Tuesday to criticize the leftist government.
   The Interior Ministry summoned directors of eight private radio
news programs Saturday and cautioned them to be careful in reports
about military recruitment, the economy and government. A vaguely
worded communications law provides for sanctions as severe as
closing the stations.
   Critics said the action was a backward step in the process of
democratic reform.
   The government began to lift press restrictions last fall as
part of its compliance with a peace plan signed by the presidents
of Nicaragua, El Salvador, Costa Rica, Guatemala and Honduras on
Aug. 7.
   La Prensa, which had been closed for 15 months, was permitted to
reopen in October. Several news programs that had been barred were
allowed back on the air.
   News media were censored under the state of emergency law
enacted in 1982. That law was revoked last January in compliance
with the peace plan.
   In an editorial Monday, La Prensa said, ``The Sandinista regime
imposes censorship restrictions on the broadcasters because it
doesn't want freedom of expression.''
   The newspaper has said some of its reporters have been harassed
by the Sandinistas, but the government has not clamped down on its
editorial policy.
   Radio Corporacion on Tuesday quoted the head of the
non-governmental human rights commission, Lino Hernandez, as saying
the communications law was ``absolutely a violation of human
rights.''
   In a report Tuesday on the economy, Radio Noticias said the
black market rate for dollars was rising, government measures were
causing unemployment and the state-run oil company is an ``organism
without authority.''
   Radio Catolica said Tuesday the Social Christian Party condemned
the media restrictions and sent a letter of protest to President
Daniel Ortega.
   Radio Mundial, in a commentary Tuesday, said: ``The liberals,
having suspended the state of emergency, substituted it with
another system based on the application of the law of security and
maintenance of public order.''
</TEXT>
