<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MinorityEmployment     05-17 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minority Employment,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Question Administration Progress in Broadcast Minority
Hiring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic members of Congress on Tuesday
questioned the effectiveness of the Reagan administration's efforts
to increase hiring and promotion of minorities at broadcast
stations and cable television systems.
   But Dennis R. Patrick, chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, and Clarence Thomas, chairman of the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, said Democrats in Congress could contribute
to minority gains by confirming President Reagan's nomination of
Bradley Holmes to the FCC.
   ``This appears to have been derailed at the highest levels,''
Thomas told members of the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee,
referring to the nomination of Holmes, a black who heads the FCC's
policy and rules division of the Mass Media Bureau.
   Reagan nominated Holmes, a 34-year-old attorney and former aide
to Patrick, last November. But friction between the FCC and
congressional Democrats have led Senate leaders to put off
confirmation hearings for Holmes and attorney Susan Wing, also
nominated by Reagan to become a commissioner.
   Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, has said he opposes the Holmes nomination. Hollings'
displeasure with the FCC stems from the agency's decision last
August to abolish the fairness doctrine, a policy that required
broadcasters to air conflicting views of controversial issues.
   Patrick joined Thomas in urging action on Holmes' nomination.
Patrick also defended his agency's efforts to hire and promote
women and minorities inside the agency and to encourage equal
employment opportunities at radio and TV stations and cable systems.
   In the broadcast and cable industries, progress has been gradual
but steady, he said.
   In radio and TV, minority employment has risen from 9.9 percent
overall and 8.4 percent in the top four job categories in 1972 to
16.2 percent overall and 14 percent in the top jobs in 1987, he
said.
   Women have increased their numbers during the period from 23
percent overall and 9.7 percent in the top four job categories to
37.8 percent overall and 29.9 percent in top jobs.
   For cable, FCC figures show minorities going from 11.7 percent
overall and 10.2 percent in the top four job categories in 1978 to
19.5 percent overall and 15.7 percent in the top jobs in 1987.
Women went from 30.6 percent of cable's overall workforce and 11.4
percent in the top jobs in 1978 to 40.4 percent overall and 27.8
percent in the top jobs last year.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., subcommittee chairman, disputed
Patrick's claim that minority employment in the top broadcasting
and cable jobs continues to improve and suggested the FCC's
enforcement of equal employment opportunity efforts is weak.
   Patrick conceded that in some specific job categories, the
percentage of minorities has been declining. National Cable
Television Association figures show that while minorities in the
top job category, officials and managers, grew from 8.8 percent in
1984 to 9.6 percent in 1987, minorities in the second job category,
professionals, declined from 15.5 percent to 12.3 percent during
the period.
   Markey said his concern was that the people who decide ``what
Americans will view'' are in the top four job categories. ``It is
their view of America, our culture, our society'' that is
presented, he said. ``To the extent that blacks are not fully
represented ... gives us some concern.''
</TEXT>
