<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Budget     05-17 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Budget,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Critics Say He Ignored Budget Woes in Midst of Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critical home-state lawmakers said Tuesday that
Gov. Michael Dukakis ignored repeated warnings of a state budget
crisis because the signals came at key junctures of his
presidential campaign.
   However, Dukakis' top budget officer said the governor had
warned the Legislature a year ago that the budget was based on
revenue projections that might prove overly optimistic.
   New state figures released Monday showed the state was $243
million short for the fiscal year that ends June 30. That would be
$166 million more than the shortfall projected by the governor's
Revenue Advisory Board on April 12, a week before the New York
primary and two weeks before the Pennsylvania primary. Wins in
those contests made it clear that Dukakis was all but certain to be
the Democratic presidential nominee.
   The $243 million shortfall is in addition to $233 million that
the administration told state agencies not to spend after the money
had been allocated.
   House Taxation Committee Chairman John Flood, a Democrat, said
Tuesday, ``They will be rolling on across the Potomac River while
the ship of Massachusetts goes down with the rest of us on it.''
   House Republican Leader Steven Pierce said ``Potomac fever'' led
the administration to ignore the warning signs.
   ``I think when the governor signed this budget at the beginning
of last July, anyone who knew anything knew that it was out of
balance,'' said state Republican Party spokesman Charlie Manning.
``Yet this guy is running as a fiscal manager.''
   Secretary of Administration and Finance Frank Keefe scoffed at
the criticism, pointing to budget-paring Dukakis vetoes and to the
Legislature's rejection of a $255 million Dukakis-filed tax
enforcement and fee package.
   ``I'm a little bit amused by folks who want to rewrite
history,'' Keefe said. ``It was the Legislature that fully believed
the future was going to be just like the immediate past, which was
a period of enormous good fortune.''
   Keefe said Dukakis had instructed him in September 1987 to put
together contingency plans to cut $185 million in spending, and he
said the governor at several intervals since had told him to look
for further cuts.
   The administration privately considered the Revenue Advisory
Board's projected shortfall conservative, but ``we weren't about to
say absolutely that things were horrible when we had no concrete
evidence that that was the case,'' Keefe said.
</TEXT>
