<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Garbage     05-17 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Garbage,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy Bars Ship Carrying Toxic Waste That Has Been Afloat For a
Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto ROM-4</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARINA DI CARRARA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Port authorities on Tuesday
refused for a second time to let a Syrian ship enter the harbor
with a cargo of toxic chemical waste that left Marina di Carrara
more than a year ago.
   The cargo of 2,000 tons of waste has been transferred from ship
to ship since it was first loaded aboard a freighter in this
northern port in February 1987.
   At one point, after a trans-Atlantic voyage, the hazardous waste
was unloaded in Venezuela but officials there said a boy died after
playing near some of the open drums and the government asked Italy
to take the cargo back.
   Francesco Rizzuto, an attorney for the Syrian ship's owner,
Tobalo Shipping, said Tuesday there are 12,000 drums of
unidentified chemicals aboard the Zanoobia and leakage has made two
of the 18 crew members seriously ill.
   The Zanoobia has been anchored off Marina di Carrara, 60 miles
southeast of Genoa, for three weeks.
   Since the waste was first loaded aboard the Cypriot-flagged
freighter Ljnx, there have been efforts to dispose of the cargo in
Djibouti, Venezuela, Syria and Greece.
   Rizzuto said the waste is jeopardizing the crew of the Zanoobia
and posing a threat to the Italian coastline.
   Port officials refuse to allow the ship to enter the harbor,
saying it does not have the proper permits from regional
authorities.
   Rizzuto gave this account of the cargo's journey:
   The Milan-based company Jelly Wax paid the equivalent of 36
cents per pound to have the chemicals disposed of and the waste was
loaded aboard the Ljnx.
   When authorities in Djibouti rejected the cargo, the ship sailed
to Venezuela where it was unloaded.
   After Venezuela insisted that Italy take the waste back, the
drums were put on the Cypriot-flagged ship Makiri. But when the
Makiri arrived in Sardinia, Italian authorities said the vessel did
not have the proper documents and it sailed to Syria.
   In Syria, the cargo was transferred to the Zanoobia. That ship
sought unsuccessfully to unload the cargo in Greece before it
returned the drums to Marina di Carrara.
   Rizzuto said there is a criminal investigation in Italy into the
handling of the waste. He said the ship's captain, Atmed Tobalo,
also had filed a request for an investigation into the contents of
the drums.
</TEXT>
