<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCrash-Mahoney     05-17 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Mahoney,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Bus Crash Called Quiet, Distant Person</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bus Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man charged with 27 counts of murder
for allegedly driving drunk and slamming his truck into a bus is
shy, would not intentionally hurt anyone and was well-liked at
work, friends and his boss said.
   ``He's a good person,'' said Billy Joe Cull, manager of
Drifter's Tavern, where Larry W. Mahoney of Worthville often shot
pool. ``I never saw him get out of hand here. He never caused a
problem.''
   Mahoney, 34, was convicted of drunken driving in 1984 and paid a
fine. He also had pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct in 1980 and
1983. His former wife charged he allegedly threatened her with a
knife in 1980, but the charge of terroristic threatening was
dropped.
   Mahoney was living with the former wife, Janice King Mahoney,
and their son at the time of the accident. He had been divorced
from his second wife, Betty Mahoney, by whom he had a daughter.
   ``He was just an easy-going, good ole country boy,'' said Linda
Mefford, a friend. ``He was a little backward _ shy and
quiet-spoken. But people should know that he wasn't some kind of
wild maniac.''
   Mahoney was charged with murder Monday and Carroll County
Commonwealth's Attorney John Ackman said he would seek the death
penalty.
   Authorities said tests showed Mahoney's blood alcohol level was
2{ times the legal limit when his pickup, traveling the wrong way
on Interstate 71, struck the bus Saturday night, killing 27 people
on a church outing.
   ``He might have had a drink now and then on a Saturday night,
but he didn't have a drinking problem,'' Mrs. Mefford said.
   Mahoney was transferred to the prison unit of Humana
Hospital-University in Louisville, where he was listed in fair
condition and will remain under 24-hour guard during his recovery,
said Taylor Rice, the hospital's public relations manager.
   State police said they talked Monday with Mahoney, but would not
discuss details.
   Mahoney dropped out of high school in the 10th grade and grew
tobacco with his father and a brother-in-law until he got a job at
M&T Chemical Co. in Carrollton.
   Plant manager Richard Vonnahme called Mahoney an excellent,
well-mannered employee. He was a a production worker, helping mix
chemicals, said John Way, personnel manager at the company.
   ``He's respected by everyone and well-liked within the plant,''
Vonnahme said.
   ``I feel sorry for the people who lost their children, but I
feel sorry for Larry, too,'' said Mrs. Mefford. ``He wouldn't hurt
anybody for the world.''
</TEXT>
