<DOCNO> AP880517-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonRiot     05-17 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Riot,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cleanup, Investigations Begin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRINGTOWN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees worked ``fast and furious''
Tuesday to clean up a medium-security prison while state agencies
began investigating a 59-hour weekend uprising.
   Prison officials offered counseling to eight guards taken
hostage at the Mack Alford Correctional Center, and prison
spokeswoman Anita Trammell said the disturbance tightened bonds
among the prison's 148 employees.
   Gov. Henry Bellmon said he was assigning the investigation to
the Department of Public Safety even though the Oklahoma State
Bureau of Investigation had already begun its probe.
   ``Our problem with the OSBI's prison investigation is that it
takes them so long,'' said Bellmon.
   OSBI spokesman Paul Renfrow said agents expect to interview
about 100 people involved in the incident, which began Friday
evening and ended Monday morning when the last hostages were
released unharmed.
   State corrections director Gary Maynard said 40 inmates
identified as being ringleaders or involved in the riot were being
held in a disciplinary unit called ``The Rock'' at a state prison
in McAlester.
   ``All of those will receive misconduct reports. If found guilty
(of misconduct), they will most likely receive 30 days in the
disciplinary unit,'' he said.
   Maynard said during the 30 days the inmates would receive no
privileges with only one visit a month from family members and one
hour a day of exercise during which they will wear handcuffs and
leg irons.
   ``Their cases also will be submitted to the district attorney
for review,'' he said.
   Prison officials met Tuesday with seven of the eight hostages
and their families at the prison visitor's center, and Marcus
Pogue, health services administrator at the prison, offered
counseling to the families.
   Most of the prison's 653 prisoners have been transferred to
other institutions, and the staff is working ``fast and furious''
on a cleanup, Ms. Trammell said.
   Ms. Trammell said an early $5 million estimate on damage may be
low, but added it may be several days before authorities come up
with another estimate.
   State corrections officials said about 130 inmates remain at
Stringtown. They said they did not know when the damaged portions
of the prison would be ready for reoccupation.
</TEXT>
