<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-17 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Curtis is glad to hear that Sioux
City Gateway Airport no longer will be known as SUX.
   ``It was somewhat of a joke in the industry,'' said Curtis, the
airport manager.
   The Federal Aviation Administration announced Monday it would
change the airport's three-letter identification, which all
airports have for airline directories, identification on baggage
tags and some radio frequencies.
   Curtis said he favors SUI, for Sioux City, Iowa.
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, had asked the FAA to change the code
after complaints from residents and the airport's advisory board.
   ``The community of Sioux City has been interested in having the
designation changed to something more appropriate and less
suggestive,'' a spokeswoman for Harkin said.
   The request was submitted more than two years ago, so the
decision to nix SUX ``came as sort of a surprise,'' Curtis said.
   Curtis said the airport has had the three-letter code for years.
``It probably goes back quite a few years ago when the connotations
were not like that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher is giving his fifth-grade
students a hands-on lesson in interest-group politics.
   Students at Carrollton Elementary School had complained about
the state of the playground, which had too few swings in good
repair near the school and lacked a ball field. So John Bushroe got
his 27 students to obtain estimates for repairs and petition the
Board of Education as part of their social studies class.
   After two months of checking with local suppliers, they found it
would cost $1,400 to repair and move swings, build a baseball
diamond and make other small changes, said 11-year-old Craig Stuart.
   Then, they got the Parent Teacher Organization to pledge $700 in
matching funds and submitted a petition with 234 signatures to the
Board of Education for the balance.
   The board will decide on the request June 1, and President May
Lou Miller already seems impressed by the students' homework.
   ``It'll be a matter of deciding if we can put it in this year's
budget or build into next year's,'' she said.
   ``The worst they can say is `no,''' Craig said. ``Maybe if they
don't give us everything, we can get part of what we want.''
</TEXT>
