<DOCNO> AP880517-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KidneyFunds     05-17 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidney Funds,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Kidney Funds Bypassing Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   W.R. Grace & Co. used $21 million in federal
funds earmarked for kidney patients to finance acquisition of the
nation's largest kidney dialysis company, The Philadelphia Inquirer
reported Tuesday.
   A federal audit concluded that the use of the money was
improper, the newspaper said.
   In the same year, 1984, in which Grace's chairman, J. Peter
Grace, headed a president's commission to investigate waste, fraud
and fiscal abuse, his company took control of the dialysis company,
National Medical Care.
   W.R. Grace, in a statement read by spokesman Frederick Bona in
New York, said the Inquirer article contained ``many inaccuracies''
and showed a lack of understanding of ``the mechanisms that
determine the dialysis remimbursement rate.''
   The newspaper said that in 1985 a dialysis clinc in Puerto Rico
owned by the Grace subsidiary made a $1 million profit. It said a
federal program paid the clinic $2.5 million to treat about 140
patients, while a government audit showed the treatments cost $1.5
million.
   More than $500,000 was profit for the clinic, the newspaper
said, and the remaining $500,000 paid non-patient expenses and
physicians' salaries that federal auditors deemed excessive.
   Dialysis, which keeps kidney-disease patients alive, costs about
$20,000 a year.
   Congress moved 16 years ago to ensure that dialysis was
available to everyone. It launched a program that this year will
pay $2.5 billion to 1,665 clinics.
   Federal records show that many clinics are making profits
approaching 30 percent from the average $125 per treatment paid by
the government, the Inquirer said.
   Federal officials acknowledge that they have little idea of how
the clinics spend the money they receive through Medicare.
   ``We don't ask questions about how they parcel out that amount
of money,'' said Bernadette Shoemaker, director of the Division of
Dialysis and Transplant Policy for the government's Health Care
Financing Administration.
   ``We pay the rate. It's up to the facilities to divvy up the
amount.''
   The Inquirer said that the spending of the money is largely
uncontrolled and feeds a tremendously profitable industry.
   W.R. Grace & Co., a giant conglomerate that owns chemical
companies and restaurants, obtained NMC, according to the Inquirer,
through a $350 million buyout of shareholders. But the new company
borrowed about $290.4 million to complete the deal, the newspaper
said.
   According to the audit, NMC paid about $35 million in interest
in 1985 on the money borrowed from the stock buyout and labeled a
portion of that interest as a cost of patient care.
   Edmund G. Lowrie, senior vice president of NMC, estimated in an
interview last week that about 60 percent or about $21 million of
that $35 million payment was charged to the federally funded clinic.
   ``The root cause of this is the denial of government to
acknowledge that a return on invested capital is an allowable
cost,'' Lowrie said.
   Larry Simmons, deputy assistant inspector general for health
audits in the Department of Health and Human Services, said there
was no finding of illegality in the audit.
   ``How they spend their money is not really a concern of the
government,'' Simmons said. ``When that money hits NMC, it's their
money.''
   In its statement, Grace said that since federal dialysis
payments began in 1973, the reimbursement rate dropped 10 percent
from about $138 per treatment to about $125 per treatment today,
while health-care costs rose by more than 200 percent.
   ``NMC received no more money as a result of the sale of the
business than if they didn't sell it,'' Bona said. ``Whatever the
costs are, that's up to the provider.''
   Grace's statement also said that in 1983, NMC's last full year
as a publicly traded company, net income was $23 million, compared
with $8.4 million in 1985, NMC's first full year after the
acquisition.
   ``This drop is accounted 100 percent by the increased interest
expense associated with the acquisition and, therefore, was borne
by the current NMC shareholders,'' Grace's statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
