<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bosch     05-17 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bosch,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INS Wants Anti-Castro Militant Deported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials ruled Tuesday that
anti-Castro militant Orlando Bosch is a danger to the community and
ordered him deported, bringing bitter protests from his family.
   Bosch, a hero to many in Miami's Cuban exile community, served a
sentence for a 1968 rocket attack on a Polish freighter here, and
was held 11 years in Venezuelan prisons on an unproven accusation
he bombed a Cuban jetliner in 1976, killing 73 people.
   Bosch's attorneys are seeking a stay of the deportation. A
hearing is scheduled Friday before U.S. District Judge William
Hoeveler. The expulsion also must be reviewed by regional
Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Steve Martin in
Dallas.
   INS officials in Washington decided to deport Bosch after
receiving custody of him Monday from federal parole officials, who
had held him since his arrival from Venezuela in February.
   ``They feel he is a threat and a danger,'' Perry Rivkind,
Florida INS district director, said Tuesday. ``Today I received
instructions from Washington to send him a temporary exclusion
notice. It will be presented to him shortly.''
   Bosch's angry daughter, Myriam Bosch, accused the INS of
persecuting her father.
   ``You know why they don't want to release him?,'' she said.
``Because they don't want to give him the chance to show he's not a
menace to society.''
   Bosch came to the United States in the 1960s and lived in the
Miami area, joining thousands of other Cubans in flight from Fidel
Castro's takeover. He is not a U.S. citizen.
   The pediatrician-turned-activist was convicted of a 1968 Miami
rocket attack on a Polish ship that had done business in Cuba. He
fled the United States while on probation for that crime.
   Venezuelan authorities then arrested him on an accusation of
masterminding the bombing of the Cuban jetliner. He was detained
for 11 years despite being acquitted by Venezuelan military and
civilian courts, but earlier this year was finally freed to the
United States. On his arrival here in February, Bosch was taken
into custody for violating parole.
   Bosch was turned over to the INS Monday, said Tom Kowalski,
Atlanta spokesman for the U.S. Parole Commission.
   Bosch is being held at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in
south Dade County.
</TEXT>
