<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Guatemala     05-17 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Presidential Candidates Involved in Coup Attempt, President
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Vinicio Cerezo said Tuesday that
two former presidential candidates were among the civilians
involved in last week's failed coup attempt against his government.
   He identified them as Gustavo Anzueto Vielman, the candidate in
1982 for the ultraconservative Authentic Nationalist Center party,
and Mario David Garcia, the party's candidate in 1985 and director
of a television news program.
   The army has said eight civilians were involved in last
Wednesday's attempt. Six army officers, including deputy commanders
of two bases, are under arrest and three others were retired
temporarily or permanently.
   The president identified another purported plotter as Mario
Castejon, who was a member of the National Renovation Party and was
trying to form his own party. For a time Castejon was with the
U.S.-backed Contra rebels fighting to overthrow Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government.
   Cerezo, who took office on Jan. 14, 1986 as Guatemala's first
civilian president since 1970, said military authorities will file
complaints in civilian courts against the civilians involved. None
was under arrest Tuesday.
   He spoke with reporters after inaugurating a preventive
detention center at the Pavon prison in Fraijanes, 15 miles east of
the capital.
   Cerezo said the former military officers involved in the coup
attempt included retired Gen. Mario Lopez Fuentes, military chief
of staff during the government of Gen. Efrain Rios Montt and until
recently Guatemalan ambassador to Italy, and retired Col. Fernando
Luis Gordillo Martinez, who was a member of the junta formed after
the March 23, 1982 coup that brought Rios Montt to power.
   The junta later was dissolved and Rios Montt named president.
   Gordillo Martinez is secretary-general of the Emergent Concord
Movement, a small political party. His brother, Maj. Manuel Maria
Gordillo Martinez, who was in charge of training at the base in
Retalhuleu, is among the active officers under arrest in the
attempt.
   Columns of officers and soldiers from the bases at Retalhuleu,
115 miles southwest of Guatemala City, and Jutiapa, 75 miles
southeast, were stopped by troops loyal to the government as the
rebel soldiers moved toward the capital early Wednesday.
   Officials said the forces were stopped peacefully.
   Rios Montt was overthrown in an Aug. 8, 1983, coup and replaced
by Gen. Humberto Mejia Victores, who in 1986 turned over the
government to Cerezo, the winner in two rounds of elections.
</TEXT>
