<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Senegal-Amnesty     05-17 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senegal-Amnesty,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Promises Amnesty, End to Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Abdou Diouf said Tuesday night
he will end the emergency imposed during riots after the Feb. 28
general elections and grant an amnesty.
   At a feast ending the Moslem holy month of Ramadan, Diouf also
said he would meet with opposition leader Abdoualaye Wade to
``examine ways and means to consolidate Senegal's democracy and to
find solutions to problems facing the young, including education
and employment.''
   These actions showed his ``confidence in the Senegalese
people,'' Diouf said, and he was ``betting on the maturity and
wisdom of my countrymen.''
   Wade claimed his Senegalese Democratic Party won the elections.
He was convicted of instigating post-election riots and last
Wednesday was given a one-year suspended prison sentence. He also
was barred from his seat in the National Assembly.
   Boubacar Sall, the No. 2 man in Wade's party, was sentenced to
two years in prison and two other party officials were given six
months each.
   Diouf said he would submit an amnesty proposal to the National
Assembly, but gave no details. The state of emergency will be
lifted this weekend, he said.
   The president, who leads the Senegalese Socialist Party, won 73
percent of the presidential vote and Wade 25 percent, according to
official returns. Wade claimed the elections were rigged.
</TEXT>
