<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FugitiveCaptured     05-17 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive Captured,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Most-Wanted' Escape Artist Agrees to Return to Oklahoma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who tried to escape from jail after fellow
inmates recognized him from the ``America's Most Wanted''
television program agreed Tuesday to return to Oklahoma, where he
is wanted for bank robbery and another escape.
   Mark Austin Goodman, 27, was on the U.S. Marshals Service's
wanted list when his case was described on the Sunday television
program, which each week highlights suspects being sought for
serious crimes.
   Using the alias James Ron Eide, Goodman had been serving a
75-day sentence for burglary at the Palm Beach County stockade when
other inmates watching the program recognized him, said sheriff's
spokesman Bob Ferrell.
   Goodman was due to be released Saturday, and guards decided to
transfer him to more secure quarters while they determined his
identity, Ferrell said.
   But Goodman, who has a deformed right arm, slipped out of his
handcuffs Sunday night and scaled an eight-foot fence topped with
barbed wire.
   An off-duty deputy spotted him Monday at a shopping mall. He was
arrested without incident and is being held at the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in Dade County until he is taken to Oklahoma.
   Shackled and surrounded by marshals, Goodman was brought Tuesday
before Chief U.S. Magistrate Peter Palermo. Goodman acknowledged
his true identity and signed a waiver agreeing to go back
immediately to Oklahoma.
   His departure time was not revealed for security reasons, said
marshal's Inspector James Simmons, but he added ``he'll be back
there within five days.''
   The marshals stamped ``Captured'' in red letters across
Goodman's picture on their bulletin board at the Miami federal
courthouse.
   Goodman escaped Oct. 30 from the Federal Correctional
Institution in El Reno, Okla., where he was awaiting trial on
charges of robbing 10 Oklahoma City-area banks last year.
</TEXT>
