<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-Justice 1stLd-Writethru a0784 05-17 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Justice, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0784,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Says Eastland Firing Didn't Involve Inadequate Support</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to change day of Meese comments on Eastland
letter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III said Tuesday
he fired chief spokesman Terry Eastland because ``it was time for a
change in leadership'' and that the dismissal did not revolve
around a question of aggressively defending Meese.
   Meese made the comment to reporters after President Reagan
reiterated his confidence in Meese and said in reference to
Eastland's firing that ``there is more than meets the eye with
regard to this latest departure.''
   Meese said ``I suspect'' what Reagan ``had in mind'' concerning
Eastland's departure was ``that I determined it was time for a
change in leadership'' rather than ``all this big blowup in the
paper ... about this reason or that reason.''
   Eastland, Meese's public affairs chief since April 1985, said in
a letter Monday that the attorney general had told him Friday he
wanted someone ``willing to aggressively defend you against ... any
and all criticism.'' He said Meese had concluded ``my efforts have
not sufficed.''
   Meese flatly contradicted that portion of Eastland's letter late
Monday afternoon, telling reporters that Eastland's departure ``had
nothing to do with a defense of me. ... Actually, ... defending me
... was not one of Terry's tasks.''
   Meese said the task of defending him was being handled by his
personal lawyers, Nathan Lewin and James Rocap. They are
representing the attorney general in a year-old criminal
investigation being conducted by independent counsel James McKay.
   Meanwhile, Eastland's special assistant, Ronald Tomalis,
resigned. Tomalis was asked to remain at the Justice Department but
handed in his resignation and plans to leave the department in two
weeks, said Patrick Korten, who is Eastland's replacement.
   Tomalis declined to comment on his reasons for leaving, but it
is customary for aides to departing political appointees to leave
as well.
   In addition, Meese announced that Deborah Burstion-Wade is the
new deputy director in the public affairs office, succeeding Korten.
   Burstion-Wade joined the Justice Department's public affairs
office in October 1986 after working as a spokeswoman for the U.S.
Civil Rights Commission.
   On another matter, the manager of a public relations firm said
Tuesday he has spoken to Meese about a possible contract to examine
the Justice Department's public portrayal of its war on drugs.
   Charles Crawford, who manages the Washington office of Hill &
Knowlton, said ``I discussed with the attorney general the whole
veracity of the process'' in publicizing the department's drug
enforcement efforts.
   Crawford said there was concern that drug enforcement programs
were being ``lost in the background'' of other issues and said ``I
suppose'' the other issues include Meese's current legal troubles.
He said no contract had been drawn up. Meese and Hill & Knowlton
Chairman Robert T. Gray are friends.
   The Justice Department's public affairs office has a $1.7
million annual budget. The FBI, Drug Enforcement Administration and
other department agencies have their own public relations
operations.
</TEXT>
