<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms Bring Heavy Rain, Hail to Much of East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled over much of the Eastern Seaboard Tuesday,
pelting some South Atlantic states with hail as big as golf balls
and dumping over four inches of rain on parts of Pennsylvania.
   Thunderstorms stretched from Florida to western Virginia and
dropping hail on many areas, particularly in the Carolinas.
   Golf ball-sized hail hit several parts of South Carolina,
including St. Matthews in the center of the state and Spartanburg
and Cherokee Counties on the state's northern border. The hail
inflicted heavy damage on peach crops in the border counties.
   ``It just literally beat them (the peaches) off the trees ... 80
percent of them. The rest are just torn up,'' Spartanburg County
agricultural extension agent George W. Bowen said Tuesday.
   Iredell County in west-central North Carolina was peppered with
1\-inch hail. Smaller hail fell on several other areas in the
Carolinas, northern Georgia and western Virginia.
   The storms produced locally heavy rain, with West Palm Beach,
Fla., receiving nearly three-quarters of an inch during a one-hour
period late in the morning.
   Rain was heavy in the mid-Atlantic states. In south-central
Pennsylvania, Cashtown received up to 4{ inches of rain during the
early afternoon.
   In the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT, about three-quarters of an
inch of rain as recorded at New York's John F. Kennedy Airport, and
at Allentown, Pa.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms also extended from western
Montana through Utah and into southeast California. The storms
generated winds up to 45 mph at Big Piney, Wyo.
   Skies were mostly sunny over the Plains and the Missisippi
Valley, with temperatures in the 60s and 70s in the northern Plains
and the middle Mississippi Valley. Temperatures stayed in the 50s
across the northwest Great Lakes, while readings rose into the 80s
from the central Plains to the Gulf Coast, with parts of southwest
Oklahoma in the low 90s.
   Cloudy skies and temperatures in the 50s and 60s prevailed over
most of the Pacific Coast and temperatures were in the 80s and 90s
across the Southwest deserts.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 43 degrees at Grand
Marais, Minn., to 95 degrees at Biloxi, Miss.
   Wednesday's forecast called for scattered rain from eastern New
England to the central Appalachians, with numerous thunderstorms
across the mid-Atlantic states. Central and southern Florida also
was expected to get scattered showers and thunderstorms.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast for the
northern Plains and central Rockies, and parts of the Pacific
Northwest. The rest of the nation was expected to have mostly sunny
skies.
   Highs were predicted in the 70s or 80s across much of the
nation. Highs were expected to be in the 60s from the Pacific
Northwest to the northern Rockies, and from the upper Ohio Valley
through New England; and in the 90s from the Southwest deserts to
northern and central Texas and the Oklahoma Panhandle. Highs were
forecast to approach 100 degrees in southwest Texas.
</TEXT>
