<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0771,0805</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Stop Infiltration Attempt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with troops stopping guerrilla
infiltration; picks up 6th graf pvs, ``Associated Press ...; edits
to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops stopped a guerrilla squad trying
to infiltrate into Israel from Jordan Tuesday and wounded one
guerrilla in the firefight, the army said.
   In other developments Tuesday, the Israeli army disciplined two
soldiers for firing against orders in a village where an Arab
teen-ager was killed, and officials promised to start reopening
West Bank schools.
   The military administration closed 1,199 West Bank schools
nearly four months ago in an effort to to quell unrest. The vow to
begin reopening the schools next Monday was taken as a sign of
Israel's growing view that the 5-month-old Arab uprising is waning.
   Violence persisted, however. Troops wounded a Palestinian who
tried to grab one of their weapons Tuesday in a refugee camp north
of Jerusalem.
   And in central Israel, activists of the anti-Arab Kach Party
hurled eggs at American folk singer Joan Baez and about 30 Israeli
leftists who staged a performance Tuesday outside the Zerifin
military base.
   The military command reported no Israeli casualties in the
attempted infiltration. It said the guerrillas planned to stage an
attack in Israel.
   It was the second reported attempt by guerrillas to sneak into
Israel from Jordan since the Palestinian revolt began in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip on Dec. 8.
   The army said the guerrillas tried to cross into Israel at about
9 p.m. (2 p.m. EDT) near the border kibbutz of Kefar Ruppin on the
banks of the Jordan river 48 miles northeast of Jerusalem.
   The wounded guerrilla was captured, the army said.
   The brief military announcement did not say which guerrilla
organization the squad belonged to, and gave no further details.
The army delayed the announcement for more than five hours.
   It was the first reported infiltration attempt from Jordan since
last Dec. 24 and the second in 10 years.
   Ms. Baez, who is in Israel on a concert tour, came to the
Zerifin base to show support for Israeli conscientious objectors
who are being held at the base prison.
   Associated Press photographer Anat Givon said about 15 members
of Kach, which is led by Brooklyn-born Rabbi Meir Kahane,
interrupted the performance, and that scuffles broke out between
the groups.
   Witnesses said three people were detained. Ms. Baez herself was
not hurt. However, she was ordered to leave by police, who revoked
a permit issued to the group earlier.
   Merchants in the occupied lands observed a near-total commercial
strike as Moslems marked the second day of Id el Fitr, a three-day
feast at the end of the Ramadan holy month. Curfews remained in
force on four towns and refugee camps.
   The army said an officer was ``severely reprimanded'' and
another soldier was given a 35-day suspended jail sentence for
firing live ammunition, against military regulations, in the West
Bank village of Azmut on Monday.
   A 15-year-old Arab was shot to death in the village during a
confrontation with Israeli troops. The army says it is
investigating whether the boy was killed by soldiers.
   An army spokesman said the soldier was punished for firing and
the officer was reprimanded for not stopping him.
   ``There are orders of when to shoot, and when not to shoot, and
the commanders decided he fired against regulations,'' the
spokesman said.
   The army lifted a four-day curfew on Nablus, the West Bank's
largest city. It also lifted a curfew on the Shati refugee camp in
Gaza, but later declared it a closed military zone, barring
residents from leaving and reporters from entering.
   Since protests began Dec. 8, 190 Palestinians and two Israelis
have been killed.
   Officials said the West Bank schools would be reopened in three
phases starting Monday.
   Olivier Rafovitch, spokesman for the West Bank military
administration, said primary schools would reopen first, allowing
203,000 children to return to classes.
   Rafovitch said plans were to allow 70,000 elementary school
pupils back to school in the last week of May and 37,000 high
school students during the first week of June, ``depending on how
the students behave.''
   The most violent incident Tuesday took place in Kalandia refugee
camp when troops tried to stop an Arab man who was violating a
curfew, an army spokesman said.
   The man got out of his car and tried to seize a soldier's gun,
the spokesman said. The troops opened fire, wounding him in the
abdomen, he said.
   A doctor at nearby Ramallah hospital said Ali Asnan Youssef, 31,
had bruises on his stomach, indicating he had been beaten.
</TEXT>
