<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vanuatu-Riot     05-17 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vanuatu-Riot,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australia and New Zealand Fly in Riot Gear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia and New Zealand flew riot
gear to this remote island group Tuesday, the day after a march for
land rights turned into a street battle in which one person was
killed and several were injured.
   Shops were looted and office windows smashed Monday after the
march by 2,000 villagers became violent, and police arrested 30
people, official Vanuatu radio reported.
   All shops and offices in Port Vila, the capital, were closed
Tuesday.
   The radio said many residents spent the night outside Port Vila.
It said security forces fired at a boat in the harbor Tuesday and
arrested a man who failed to stop, but gave no details.
   Prime Minister Walter Lini's government met in emergency session
Tuesday.
   Vanuatu, formerly the Anglo-French New Hebrides, is 930 miles
northeast of Australia. It achieved independence in 1980 and has a
population of 130,000, including about 15,000 in Port Vila.
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke of Australia said he sent a military
C-130 Hercules loaded with gas masks, tear gas canisters and
launchers to help the government with riot control.
   He said Lini requested the equipment. ``In a city with a
population of less than 20,000 it is clear that these disturbances
have been on a very serious scale,'' Hawke told Parliament in
Canberra.
   New Zealand sent similar supplies, but Foreign Minister Russell
Marshall told reporters in Wellington there had been no thought of
sending soldiers.
   ``There has been no request ... for military units,'' he said.
``If the situation deteriorated, we'd have to look at it very
seriously.''
   About 2,000 people from tribes in three villages marched through
Port Vila on Monday to protest the closure last week of the Vila
Urban Land Corp., a government agency that administered leased
tribal land in the capital, the radio said.
   It said protesters began rioting, police fired tear gas and a
police vehicle ran over a man, killing him. The radio said Lini, an
Anglican priest, was not in Port Vila at the time.
   The government said Tuesday it had received a petition from
tribal chiefs saying they would form a new body to collect revenue
from tribal land in the capital. According to the radio, Lini's
government promised land leases would be honored.
</TEXT>
