<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru a0676 05-17 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope, Nearing End of Visit, Denounces Exploitation of Peasant
Farmers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 5 grafs SUB for 3d graf pvs, Heavy rains ... UPDATING with
pope meeting with Indians. Picks up 4th graf pvs, The meeting .. ..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Tuesday denounced
the exploitation of Latin America's peasant farmers, telling
hundreds of thousands of ``campesinos'' not to be resigned to
poverty.
   ``Although it is true this fertile land that God has given
rewards your efforts abundantly, how many times do those who do the
work fail to reap the benefits?'' the pope declared at a Mass in
Villarrica, a farm center 100 miles southeast of Asuncion.
   Heavy rains disrupted the pope's itinerary on the next to last
day of his four-nation South American visit.
   After the Mass John Paul flew to Mariscal Estigarribia, 335
miles northwest of Asuncion, and spoke to about 5,000 Indians
representing 16 tribes from Paraguay and areas of neighboring
Argentina, Brazil and Bolivia.
   ``Above all, you want to be respected as persons and want your
rights, both human and civil, to be recognized and protected,'' he
told the crowd gathered at the Santa Teresita Mission.
   He urged the Indians ``not to abandon yourselves to despair''
and said ``the church has defended the freedom and dignity of
native people'' in South America since the 16th century.
   The pontiff's last event of the day was a controversial meeting
with civic leaders, including opposition politicians, in Asuncion.
   The meeting with the church-sponsored ``Builders of Society''
was abruptly canceled by the government of Gen. Alfredo Stroessner
last week. The government dropped its ban after the Vatican
protested publicly.
   About 300,000 to 400,000 people stood in ankle-deep water on a
field in Villarrica and burst into applause and song when John Paul
arrived by car from Asuncion instead of by plane as planned.
Officials said the rains made it impossible to land on the dirt
airstrip.
   Paraguay's authoritarian government has harshly repressed
attempts by peasant farmers to organize. The Roman Catholic Church
has given some support to those efforts, and 19 foreign
missionaries have been expelled in the last 20 years.
   Police Monday briefly detained two leaders of the Peasants
Rights Movement, who were arrested along with an American priest
and an union activist. All were freed without explanation.
   Addressing the crowd, John Paul said living a Christian life
``does not mean simply accepting with resignation the difficulties
that you encounter.''
   John Paul cited lack of adequate social benefit for farmers,
``intransigence regarding salaries and unfair contracts and
difficulty in obtaining property'' as ``some of the modern thorns
and thistles that increase the already difficult conditions of your
work.''
   Questions of trade and pricing on the national and international
levels have added to their difficulties, he said.
   The pontiff, speaking from under a thatched canopy, switched
several times from Spanish to Guarani, the Indian language spoken
widely by farmers in this landlocked country of 3.8 million people.
   The pope began the day with an hour-long meeting with more than
1,000 priests, nuns and seminarians in the National Cathedral in
Asuncion.
   He told them they must give preference in their ministry to the
poor ``who in Paraguay, as in so many parts of Latin America,
suffer every kind of privation.''
   ``So many peasants, laborers, workers without employment or
being exploited lack their badly needed bread,'' he said.
   Peasants who were occupying a church in Paraguay's capital ended
a hunger strike and prayer service Tuesday. A spokesman said they
accomplished their goal of bringing their plight to the attention
of the public as well as the local church and Vatican.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
