<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Curran-Catholic 1stLd-Writethru a0742 05-17 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Curran-Catholic, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curran Says Catholic University Reneged on Teaching Reassignment</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 14th graf pvs bgng, `Catholic spokeswoman,' with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with response from university</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Charles Curran, whose views on sex
caused the Vatican to bar him from teaching moral theology at
Catholic University, charged Tuesday that the school broke its
contract by refusing to offer him another ``acceptable'' teaching
assignment.
   ``The board of trustees at Catholic University is not willing to
offer me a position in my area of competence with no strings
attached,'' Curran told reporters. ``I was willing to make a
tremendous amount of concessions. Unfortunately, they were not
willing to accept them.''
   Catholic's board of trustees stripped Curran of his canonical
mission on April 12, prohibiting him from teaching in the
department of theology because his lectures on homosexuality,
abortion and other issues of sexual morality differed from the
Vatican's position.
   But the trustees retained his right as a tenured professor to
teach in another area.
   A faculty committee had gone along with the trustees as long as
Curran, a member of the theology department for more than 20 years,
be offered a position acceptable to him before his canonical
mission was revoked.
   Curran said negotiations with the oard this spring led him to
believe he would be allowed to teach Christian social ethics in the
sociology department, as long as he avoided issues of sexuality and
human reproduction.
   Curran said he was willing to accept such an arrangement,
provided ``the position was truly in the area of my competence,
that I had access to students interested in this area, and that I
was in no other way worse off that I had been in the department of
theology.''
   But he said the trustees have now stipulated that students in
the departments of theology and canon law and the school of
philosophy cannot take Curran's courses for credit, and his courses
cannot be required to satisfy core requirements of the department
of religion and religious education.
   ``They were going to put me over there and isolate me from every
student,'' Curran said. He demanded his classes be open to all
students.
   The university also required that Curran promise in writing he
would not teach Catholic theology.
   ``A breach by Professor Curran of this provision shall
constitute adequate cause for his dismissal from the university,''
the proposed agreement said.
   ``I just cannot sign a statement that says I won't teach
Catholic theology at Catholic University,'' Curran said. ``That's
who I am. It would be untrue.
   ``Basically, this is constructive termination,'' he said.
   Catholic University President William J. Byron said in a
statement: ``The university has been attempting to arrive at a
solution that is faithful to the Holy See's judgment that Father
Curran is unsuitable to teach Catholic theology and that is
respectful of the faculty committee's recommendation that Father
Curran continue to teach moral theology and-or ethics somewhere at
the university.
   ``The university has chosen to offer Father Curran a position in
the field of social ethics in the School of Arts and Sciences,''
Byron said in the statement read by university spokeswoman Anne
Smith. Ms. Smith said this is the same offer that was presented
previously to Curran.
   Curran already has accused the school in a lawsuit with breach
of contract and said he will add to his complaint the assertion
that he was terminated illegally.
   ``This is not a church-state issue,'' said Curran's attorney,
Paul Saunders. ``It's fundamentally a question of breach of
contract.''
   The trial is scheduled for September.
   Curran is finishing a one-year visiting professorship teaching
Catholic studies at Cornell University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
