<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0664 05-17 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,0755</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Face Most Dangerous Passage Early In Journey Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 7th graf pvs, But others ... UPDATING
with Soviet TV reports. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Gunshots could ...
with minor editing to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet soldiers heading home Tuesday
in a 300-vehicle convoy faced the most dangerous stretch of their
three-day journey: a guerrilla-infested gorge north of Kabul.
   The Soviet news agency Tass reported that residents of the
Soviet border city of Termez had decorated the streets with
streamers and flags and were preparing a meal for the soldiers.
   Correspondents traveling with the Soviet column leaving
Afghanistan were unable to report on developments after leaving
Kabul, but they were told before departure Monday that the most
perilous portion of the journey north would be through the gorge
and the Salang tunnel in the Hindu Kush mountains.
   Most of the 1,300 Soviet troops in the convoy pulled out of a
base in Jalalabad, near the border with Pakistan, early Sunday and
spent the day wending their way along the 88-mile rutted route to
the capital.
   They set off for the Soviet border after a ceremony conducted by
Afghan President Najib. Officers said the journey would take about
three days.
   ``We feel more sure that everything will be OK now,'' one
soldier said above the din of revving tank engines, referring to
the 250-mile trip north.
   But others indicated the convoy would be lucky to escape the
journey without casualties.
   The Soviet television news program ``Vremya'' showed a series of
reports Tuesday night from Afghanistan.
   In the first, a Soviet correspondent reported from an armored
vehicle while rifle fire rang out in the background. He said he was
on the road with the Soviet forces withdrawing from Afghanistan,
but did not say exactly where or comment on the shooting.
   A second report said rebels had hit Jalalabad with six rockets
since the Soviets began pulling out. It showed pictures of dead and
wounded Afghans, but did not say if the casualties were in
Jalalabad.
   Gunshots could be heard in the mountains towering over the
Jalalabad-Kabul route on Sunday, and a pool reporter riding with
the convoy said the travelers felt especially vulnerable on low
ground between mountains from which the anti-communist guerrillas
can take aim.
   Information about the Soviet withdrawal has been relayed from
Kabul by a Reuters news agency pool report. The Associated Press
was denied permission to travel to Afghanistan for the pullout, and
a Soviet Foreign Ministry official said the exclusion was the
result of ``inappropriate questions'' asked during a previous visit
by AP.
   Tass said in a dispatch from Termez, located in the Soviet
republic of Uzbekistan, that ``city streets and squares are decked
out with streamers with words of welcome for the
soldiers-internationalists who have courageously fulfilled their
duty.''
   A meal of mutton, vegetables and pilaf would be waiting for the
soldiers, it said.
   ``We have the great honor to be the first to welcome to the
Soviet land the soldiers who have fulfilled their internationalist
duty in Afghanistan,'' city Communist Party leader Tamara
Dzhurayeva told Tass.
   Tass reported from Kabul that Afghan officials on Monday
presented a note to U.N. observers monitoring the pullout, alleging
that Pakistan was violating conditions of the April 14 agreement
that set out conditions for the Soviet withdrawal. Tass said no
details of the note were made public.
   Under the Geneva accord, Pakistan is to stop aiding the
insurgents.
   Pakistani Foreign Minister Zain Noorani, in Moscow on an
official visit, met with Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov on
Tuesday, and the conversation focused on Afghanistan, Tass said.
   Tass said Noorani was told by Soviet officials that ``in
present-day conditions'' there are better prospects for improving
Soviet-Pakistani relations, apparently referring to the Afghan
peace accord.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said at a
news briefing Tuesday that the start of the pullout was ``a strong
impulse'' toward success of Najib's policy of national
reconciliation _ a plan laid out two years ago that proposes to
share power with other political groups.
   Gerasimov said the withdrawal refutes accusations that the
Soviets were seeking to conquer the neighboring country with the
hope of obtaining a warm sea port. He also dismissed speculation
that the Soviets were planning to divide Afghanistan with Najib's
government holding the resource-rich northern areas adjacent to the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
