<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacistTown     05-17 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racist Town,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Demotes Lieutenant Who Complains Of Racism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKY HILL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Town Council demoted a police
lieutenant and cut his pay by $1,683 because he complained about
the town's racist attitudes, the town police chief said Tuesday.
   But Town Manager Dana Whitman Jr. said the demotion was needed
to eliminate an unnecessary position and was not in retaliation for
complaints by Lt. John C. Herbst.
   ``I don't care what way it's masked, and what way it's put
forth. It's retaliatory,'' countered Police Chief Philip H.
Schnabel.
   Herbst's complaint of ``pervasive racism'' more than a year ago
led to an investigation by the state Commission on Human Rights and
Opportunities. The commission issued a report in January that
substantiated Herbst's claims and recommended changes in town
policy to eliminate racism.
   In addition to the demotion and pay cut, Herbst will be forced
to work a rotating shift on nights and weekends. He currently works
daytime hours and no weekends.
   ``It's really upsetting,'' Herbst said Tuesday. He declined
further comment on the Town Council's action, but his attorney said
a lawsuit would be filed as soon as possible in federal court.
   ``There's simply no question this is punishment for blowing the
whistle on racism in the Police Department,'' said John Williams,
representing Herbst. ``The people who did this are going to have to
pay for it. They've aligned themselves with the racism cancer in
that town.''
   William Olds, executive director of the Connecticut Civil
Liberties Union, said the organization would discuss the case later
this week at a meeting.
   Rocky Hill, a well-to-do Hartford suburb of about 16,000
residents, including about 330 blacks, has 28 police officers.
   Herbst complained that racial jokes and slurs were common at
Town Hall and tolerated by town officials. He also said some police
officers were in the habit of making stops based on a suspect's
race.
   Whitman termed Herbst's demotion as a ``reduction in force,''
which is allowed under the town's contract with the local police
union. He said when council members decided to eliminate one of the
department's three lieutenant positions, they had no idea Herbst
would be the officer affected.
   Herbst and the other lieutenants all achieved their rank the
same day in 1982. Herbst, the department's administrative
assistant, was considered the senior lieutnenant since that time
because he had the highest score on the lieutenant's test.
   But the Town Council decided seniority should be based on the
length of employment, leaving Herbst with the least seniority.
Herbst was hired in 1976.
   Whitman also said the idea for cutting a lieutenant's position
``came up at a budget meeting'' last month. He said the chief told
town leaders that the duties performed by Herbst duplicated those
handled by Deputy Chief Robert Riley.
   Schnabel agreed that the job description for Riley and Herbst
are similar, but complained that the council was forcing him to
choose between the two men. Riley said that his job and Herbst's
are not in fact similar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
