<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Baez,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-Wingers Hurl Eggs At Joan Baez At Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto TLV9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZERIFIN, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant rightists hurled eggs at
American folk singer Joan Baez when she took part Tuesday in a
rally backing Israeli soldiers who refuse to serve in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Ms. Baez was not hit, said Associated Press photographer Anat
Givon.
   The attack came as the singer and about 30 Israelis demonstrated
outside this military base, 8 miles south of Tel Aviv, where some
of the conscientious objectors are being held.
   Ms. Baez, 47, who is on a concert tour, was giving an impromptu
performance when about 15 members of the anti-Arab Kach movement
heckled her.
   A scuffle ensued and saome Kach members threw eggs.
   Three Kach members were detained, Israel radio said. Kach is an
extreme right-wing movement led by Brooklyn-born Rabbi Meir Kahane.
   Police did not question Ms. Baez but ordered her to leave the
area after revoking a demonstration permit issued earlier.
   The rally was organized by Yesh Gvul, Hebrew for ``There is a
Limit,'' a group organized by reserve soldiers and officers who
refuse to serve in or carry out Israel's policies in the occupied
lands. The organization was founded after Israel's 1982 invasion of
Lebanon.
   Ms. Baez arrived in Israel on May 11 at the invitation of Peace
Now, an organization that supports territorial concessions in
return for peace with Israel's Arab neighbors.
   The folk singer has said she would donate the proceeds from her
two concerts in Israel to Peace Now and other anti-war groups.
   During her tour, Ms. Baez has performed at a Palestinian refugee
camp and met with Jewish activist Natan Sharansky, who spent nine
years in a Soviet prison before being allowed to emigrate to Israel.
   On Monday, Ms. Baez had a dispute with editors at Israel's army
radio. She accused radio officials of censorship after they
canceled a live broadcast of her performance because she sang an
Israeli protest song banned by the station.
   Army radio later broadcast an edited version of the performance,
leaving out the song, ``Shooting and Crying,'' which criticizes
army methods in the occupied lands.
</TEXT>
