<DOCNO> AP880517-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Cannes     05-17 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Cannes,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Film Included in Cannes Official Selection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The screening Tuesday of Chen Kaige's
``The King of the Children'' at the 41st Cannes Film Festival
marked the first time a film from China has been in the official
selection, the most important category.
   Kaige, 36, is a leading figure in the new Chinese cinema. His
formative years were dominated by China's Cultural Revolution, the
radical upheaval from 1966-76.
   ``The King of the Children'' is set in the late 1970s, and Kaige
indicated his approval of aspects of the Cultural Revolution.
   ``Man invented culture and became its slave,'' Kaige told a news
conference. ``The fire in the last scene symbolizes my attitude
toward the traditional culture.''
   ``The King of the Children'' _ as teachers were once known in
China _ is Lao Gar. He is sent to a village school in a remote area
in Yunnan province where he is confronted by children who learn to
read and write by copying, without understanding the information
from the teacher.
   The teacher abandons the established teaching program with its
official manual and encourages the students to use their
imagination and write essays about their lives.
   The unorthodox methods provoke officials and district
authorities expel him from the school.
   The story reflects elements of Kaige's experiences.
   Kaige was sent to work in the country under the re-education
plan adopted in 1968 as part of the Cultural Revolution. The plan
sent students from the cities to rural areas to work in the fields
and learn about peasant life.
   In the film, Lao Gar spends seven years as a farm laborer before
receiving the teaching post.
   ``I had the same age as the teacher and received the same
education, full of big words and devoid of sense,'' Kaige said.
``We didn't know how to construct our own personality.''
   China's new leadership introduced reforms following the end of
the Cultural Revolution and Communist Party leader Mao Tse-tung's
death in September 1976.
   Kaige, commenting on the current situation in China, said, ``The
fact that I was able to make `The King of the Children' is a sign
of good health.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
