<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ContaminatedIsland     05-17 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contaminated Island,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contaminated Scottish Island Declared Safe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A remote Scottish island contaminated with
dangerous bacteria during World War II experiments was declared
safe after a government cleanup, the Defense Ministry said Tuesday.
   The 520-acre island of Gruinard will be offered to the original
owner, a family trust, for $930, the price paid by the government
when it took it over in 1941, the ministry said in its annual paper
on the defense budget.
   The ministry spent two years using the island off the western
Scottish Highlands to test bombs containing anthrax bacteria in the
belief that Nazi Germany was doing something similar. The bacteria
can be fatal to humans.
   Briton subsequently passed the test results to the United
States, which began making anthrax bombs.
   In 1979, government tests showed only 10 acres were still
contaminated.
   Last year, a company with experience in soil-decontamination
began treating the soil with a mixture of sea water and
formaldehyde. When that appeared to work, sheep were taken to the
island for study.
</TEXT>
