<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0681 05-17 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0681,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanker Explodes, Killing Crewmen on Salvage Tug</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stark Anniversary Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: 3 grafs SUB for 9th graf pvs, On Tuesday ... UPDATING with
report from UN. Picks up 10th graf pvs, President Ali ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burning Spanish supertanker exploded at
Iran's Larak Island oil terminal Tuesday, killing crew members on
tugs that were fighting fires started by an Iraqi air raid last
weekend.
   The unofficial toll of dead and missing already stood at 22 from
the raid Saturday that damaged five ships.
   Several explosions ran through the 235,000-ton Barcelona, which
had been beached in shallow water, just after noon. Lloyd's
Shipping Intelligence Unit in London said four tugs were attending
it at the time.
   It reported ``all crew lost'' on the tugboat Scan Force and
three dead on the Beaufort, and said the tugs Safir and Ferdinand
Verbiest were damaged. A salvage tug normally has nine or 10 crew
members.
   Lloyd's said it ``understood'' the Scan Force sank and said the
other three had left for the Arabian side of the Persian Gulf,
where Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
   An earlier report from Lloyd's had said five crewmen were
reported missing from the Scan Force, a Panamanian-flag tug, and
two from the Belgian vessel Ferdinand Verbiest. There was no
immediate explanation for the differences.
   Shipping sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they
had reports of bodies washing onto the rocks of Larak Island, in
the narrow Strait of Hormuz that leads into the gulf, and the
bodies might be those of dead tug crewmen.
   Iran uses shuttle tankers to ferry oil from its main Kharg
Island export terminal in the northern gulf to makeshift terminals
at Larak and Sirri islands in safer waters about 450 miles down the
gulf. Iraqi warplanes make occasional raids on the southern
terminals, refueling in flight.
   At the United Nations in New York, diplomatic sources said
Tuesday that Iraq had accepted Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar's call for negotiations outside New York to help set dates
for a cease-fire. It attached the usual condition that Iran also
must accept.
   Perez de Cuellar has not received a response from Iran, which
insists Iraq must be declared the aggressor before there can be a
cease-fire. Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after several
border incidents.
   Iranian leaders threatened on Tuesday to block all petroleum
exports from the gulf and exhorted followers of the fundamentalist
Shiite Moslem regime to pray for the deaths of President Reagan and
Saddam Hussein, president of Iraq.
   President Ali Khamenei said at prayers ending the Moslem holy
month of Ramadan that, if Iran's oil exports were cut off, ``there
would be no way for any other country to do the same through the
waterway.''
   Iraq raids Iran's terminals and the shuttle tankers it owns and
charters in an attempt to halt the oil exports with which it
finances the war. Iraq sends most of its oil abroad by pipeine.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's revolutionary patriarch, was
quoted by Tehran radio as saying the best prayer for Reagan and
Hussein would be ``to wish them to die'' because ``the more they
stay alive, the worse their situation will become.''
   A U.S. Navy ship dropped a ceremonial wreath in waters of the
central gulf on the first anniversary Tuesday of another Iraqi air
strike, a mistaken missile attack on the missile frigate U.S. Stark
that killed 37 sailors.
   Lt. Cmdr. Jerry McNabb, a Navy chaplain, conducted memorial
ceremony on the destroyer Stump at about 4 p.m. in the area where
the frigate was hit. A 24-man honor guard and seven-member rifle
team took part, and the oldest and youngest members of the Stump's
crew dropped the wreath over the side.
   The Stump is in the gulf to replace the Samuel B. Roberts, a
sister ship of the Stark that was damaged by a mine last month.
   Shipping executives identified the tanker attacked by Iraqi
warplanes Monday as the 112,445-ton Bisoton, formerly Norwegian and
now owned by Iran.
   It was the 12th attack on a ship Iraq had reported in 18 days.
Six have been confirmed.
   In London, Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence said the Bisoton was
hit off Iran. Gulf shipping executives said 10 crew members were
killed.
</TEXT>
