<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Legionnaires     05-17 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Legionnaires,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Death in Legionnaires' Disease Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second employee of the British Broadcasting
Corp. died Tuesday in an outbreak of Legionnaires' disease at BBC
headquarters, a public health office said.
   Five people were seriously ill among the 39 known cases of the
disease in and around the BBC, and 44 more cases are suspected, the
Westminster Public Health Office said.
   A 53-year-old man working as an assistant manager in charge of
studios was hospitalized May 10 and died Tuesday, the office said.
   A 63-year-old cleaning supervisor, Jim Morgan, one of the first
cases diagnosed in the outbreak between mid-April and early May,
died last Thursday.
   Legionnaires' disease produces symptoms similar to pneumonia and
often is caused by bacteria from water-cooled air conditioning
units. The BBC said its air systems in Broadcasting House and a
nearby building had been disinfected.
   The disease was diagnosed first in 1976 when 221 people
contracted it at the Pennsylvania American Legion convention in
Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
