<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalMurder     05-17 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Murder,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Keeps Suits Alive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled Tuesday that
a psychiatric hospital's officials could be sued in connection with
the 1985 rape and murder of one hospital patient by another.
   In two 3-0 decisions, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
rejected attempts by Napa State Hospital officials to dismiss suits
filed by the victim's estate and her psychiatrist.
   The court said the victim, Marilyn Conners, was lured from her
ward to a remote part of the hospital grounds by John Duncan, who
raped and strangled her.
   Duncan had been admitted to the hospital after entering an
insanity plea to a separate charge of rape and murder. He also had
tried to rape another female patient about two weeks before his
attack on Ms. Conners, but still was allowed to roam the hospital
grounds, the court said.
   Duncan later pleaded no contest to second-degree murder and
assault with intent to commit rape of Ms. Conners.
   Ms. Conners' heirs sued five hospital administrators claiming
gross negligence and reckless indifference to patient safety in
allowing patients hospitalized on criminal charges to walk around
the grounds.
   Dr. William Schwartzman, a staff psychiatrist who treated Ms.
Conners, sued two administrators after he was fired in 1985
following disputes with management over the previous three years.
He claimed his dismissal was motivated partly by his public
criticism of the hospital for allegedly administering too many
drugs, providing unsafe working conditions and inadequately
supervising Duncan.
   Tuesday's rulings upheld earlier decisions by two federal judges
who refused to dismiss the suits.
   Although government officials have some protection from
lawsuits, the immunity does not apply to violations of clearly
established rights, said the opinions written by Judge Alfred
Goodwin. He said the suits would meet that test if plaintiffs can
prove that hospital officials were indifferent to patient safety
and that Schwartzman was fired because of his criticism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
