<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ArianeLaunch     05-17 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ariane Launch,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Space Agency Launches 22nd Ariane Rocket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Space Agency on
Tuesday launched its 22nd Ariane rocket, putting into orbit a
communications satellite.
   Officials at the space center on the northeastern shoulder of
South America called the launch ``a complete success.''
   The countdown had been stopped for 15 minutes at 8:37 p.m.
because of bad weather conditions.
   ``A storm cloud passed over the launching pad,'' a space agency
official said. The countdown was resumed at 8:52 p.m. and the
rocket lifted off at 8:58 p.m.
   Sixteen minutes and 40 seconds later, the International
Telecommunications Organization satellite separated from the
rocket, according to the official.
   The agency said the flight was ``nominal,'' or perfect, except
for the brief weather problem.
   New French Premier Michel Rocard watched the operation from the
space agency's facility in suburban Paris.
   Four of the previous 21 Ariane shots were unsuccessful. A
failure in 1986 grounded the program for more than a year, but the
last three launches have been a success, including the previous one
on March 12.
   The Intelsat V-F13 satellite put into geostationary orbit 22,500
miles above the Earth is part of a series of 15 satellites built by
an international consortium headed by Ford Aerospace. The satellite
contains 15,000 telephone circuits and two television channels.
   Tuesday's launch involved an Ariane 2 rocket.
   On a nearby pad other crews are preparing for the first launch
of the larger Ariane 4 rocket that can carry 4.2 tons into orbit _
nearly double the Ariane 2 payload. The Ariane 4 launch is
scheduled for June 8.
   The European Space Agency now has 44 launches on its order
books. It plans a total of eight in 1988 and nine in 1989 and 1990.
   Ariane launches cost between $53 million and $105 million,
depending on the version.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
