<DOCNO> AP880517-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PumpkinPapers 2ndLd-Writethru a0729 05-17 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pumpkin Papers, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0729,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hodel Declares Whittaker Chambers Farm A Historic Landmark</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead to delete garbled material</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel rejected
the advice of an advisory committee Tuesday and declared a national
historic landmark the Maryland farm where Whittaker Chambers hid
the ``pumpkin papers'' that convicted Alger Hiss.
   Chambers was ``a figure of transcendent importance in the
nation's history,'' Hodel said in a speech to the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative group.
   Hodel, a staunch conservative who like many in the modern
conservative movement acknowledges an intellectual and
philosophical debt to Chambers, himself nominated Pipe Creek Farm
in Westminster, Md., for landmark status.
   Westminster is about 30 miles northwest of Baltimore. The farm
is operated by Chambers' son, John.
   He was supported by the staff of the National Park Service,
which administers the landmark program.
   William Penn Mott, director of the service, wrote Hodel that the
staff concluded ``that Whittaker Chambers was exceptionally
significant and that the farm represents that significance with the
requisite degree of historical integrity.''
   Both the Maryland state historic preservation office and a
professional review committee, including outside historians,
supported the designation but the advisory board of the National
Park Service on April 26 opposed it.
   The board cited the service guideline that 50 years should
elapse before designation of landmarks to give historians time for
an objective assessment.
   ``I appreciate that the board disagrees but I do not chose to
follow its advice in this instance,'' said Hodel.
   The chairman of the advisory panel, Daniel Jordan, was
philosophical about the secretary's rejection of its advice.
   ``I'm surprised and disappointed. I felt the advisory board had
met its obligation in a serious manner, and had made the correct
decision,'' said Jordan, who is head of the Thomas Jefferson
Memorial Foundation in Charlottesville, Va., in a statement relayed
by an aide.
   ``But I also recognize that the board is responsible only for
making a recommendation, and that the final decision always rests
with the secretary of the interior.''
   Bruce Craig, cultural resources specialist for the National
Parks and Conservation Association, a private group that lobbies
for policies to benefit the parks, said interior secretaries had
disregarded the 50-year rule before, but it was the first time in
memory that one had overruled the advisory board.
   Hodel's disregard of the 50-year rule ``constitutes a threat to
the preservation program insofar as it represents a politicization
of the program,'' Craig said.
   It was 40 years ago that Chambers, then an editor at Time
Magazine, accused Hiss, a former State Department official who had
been secretary of the founding conference of the United Nations, of
being a fellow member of a communist spy ring in the late 1930s.
   At first not many people believed Chambers, a rumpled figure
with bad teeth who looked seedy in comparison with the patrician,
Harvard-educated Hiss, then head of the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace.
   Hiss denied the allegation before the House Un-American
Activities Committee and sued Chambers for libel.
   But a young committee member named Richard Nixon followed up,
and for him Chambers retrieved copies of 1937 State Department
documents from a hollowed-out pumpkin.
   Hiss was indicted for perjury. Prosecutors were able to prove
that the documents had been typed on a machine owned by Hiss.
   Convicted, Hiss served 44 months in prison. His libel suit was
dismissed. He has maintained his innocence ever since, in two
volumes of memoirs and elsewhere, and has declined to comment about
the landmark discussions.
   Chambers died in 1961. President Reagan awarded him a Medal of
Freedom posthumously in 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-BRF--TreeWarden 1stLd-Writethru a0744 05-17 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tree Warden, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0744,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Candidates Running for Tree Warden</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with results and CLARIFIES that only two
candidates were on actual ballot</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hotly contested post of tree warden was
won by John Morandi in a landslide Tuesday. Now all he has to do is
figure out what the job entails.
   The post was vacant for a year and has a total budget of $50,
but to everyone's surprise, including the candidates', four people
sought the job during a March 29 caucus in this little Berkshire
Hills town.
   Only the top two vote-getters at the caucus won a place on
Tuesday's ballot. According to the unofficial tally, Morandi won
with 42 votes to Louise Hardy's 20.
   With only about 250 registered voters, Alford has had trouble
frequently getting enough candidates to fill its ballot. Tree
warden was the only contested office out of 17 on Tuesday's ballot.
   ``You'd think they were running for president,'' said Helene
Morandi, wife of the winner. She said her husband is retired and
decided to run because he thought no one else would.
   In campaigning, Hardy had pledged that, ``If elected, I'll find
out what the job entails.''
   A former tree warden, David Germain, summed up the duties: ``The
important thing in this job is not to cut down any trees before the
owners are told about it.''
  
</TEXT>
