<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Indelicato-Freedman     05-17 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indelicato-Freedman,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Declares Mistrial In Fraud Case Involving Ex-Dukakis Aide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge declared a mistrial Tuesday in the
fraud and conspiracy trial of a businessman accused of
participating in a kickback scheme with Gerard Indelicato, former
top education adviser to Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Indelicato, who pleaded guilty last month to participating in
the scheme, testified against Michael Freedman two weeks ago.
Indelicato won a recommendation from federal prosecutors for a
reduced sentence in exchange for his cooperation with what
Assistant U.S. Attorney Ralph Gants called an ``ongoing
investigation.''
   U.S. District Court Judge Douglas Woodlock declared the mistrial
Tuesday afternoon after a 12-member jury was unable to reach a
unanimous verdict on one count of mail fraud and one count of
conspiracy.
   The key issue on which the jury appeared to be stumped was
whether the prosecution had proved willfulness on Freedman's part
in accepting kickback money. After the jury raised that question
Tuesday morning, Judge Woodlock reiterated instructions.
   Later in the day, as the deadlock continued, Gants asked that
the jury be queried specifically on whether they could find
Freedman guilty on either of the two counts. The answer was no.
Freedman's defense attorney, John Burns, moved for a mistrial and
Woodlock granted the motion.
   Woodlock set a new trial date for July 11.
   ``It's analagous to a baseball team playing to a 2-2 tie in the
ninth and it rains,'' Gants said.
   Burns did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
   Indelicato testified that the kickback scheme involved skimming
some $80,000 from two adult education programs between 1979 and
1983. Indelicato headed the state's adult education program at the
time the scheme got under way.
   According to Indelicato's testimony, the conspiracy involved
using federal funds administered by the state to pay more rent than
necessary for classroom space and then splitting the difference
among Freedman, Indelicato, his brother Joseph and a fourth
conspirator, Antonio Perrotta.
   All but Freedman have already pleaded guilty. Gants said it
would be ``a mischaracterization'' to say Indelicato agreed to
plead guilty and win a recommendation for a lesser sentence solely
in exchange for his testimony in the Freedman trial. But the
federal prosecutor declined to specify in what other matters
Indelicato is cooperating with authorities.
   Indelicato is scheduled to be sentenced July 8, three days
before the new Freedman trial is set to begin. Gants declined to
say whether Indelicato would testify in the new trial.
   Prosecutors agreed to recommend to Judge Woodlock that
Indelicato receive a five-year prison term and pay an $80,000 fine.
Woodlock could exceed that recommendation if he chose.
   Gants called the recommended punishment ``a very fair sentence.''
   Indelicato became Dukakis' education adviser in March 1983, two
months after the conspiracy alleged by the government ended. While
he worked for Dukakis' election bid in 1982, Indelicato testified,
he was receiving cash kickbacks of hundreds of dollars per month
from the adult education program.
   ``It was a regular income, if you will, for all of us,''
Indelicato testified during Freedman's trial.
   Indelicato said Freedman accepted his share and was aware of
where the money was coming from. But his testimony did not depict
Freedman as one of the architects of the scheme.
</TEXT>
