<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MotleyCrue     05-17 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motley Crue,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadlocked Jury Forces Mistrial On Suit Against Motley Crue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deadlocked jury forced a judge to declare
a mistrial Tuesday in a $1.3 million suit filed by two teen-agers
against the heavy metal band Motley Crue for injuries allegedly
suffered at a 1985 concert.
   The jury told Limestone County Circuit Judge Henry Blizzard that
they were at an impasse on their second day of deliberations, court
reporter Regeana Gentry said.
   ``We will put it on the next civil docket,'' she said of the
case.
   Foreman Marshall Mitchell of Athens said later that 10 jurors
believed the California-based rock band was not at fault and two
wanted to award damages because ``somebody should pay.''
   Attorneys for the injured teen-agers claimed the special effects
display at the Huntsville concert propelled dry ice into the
audience where Robbie Miller, 17, of Piney Chapel, and David Hunt
Wright, 19, of Grant, were standing in front of the stage.
   Miller lost his right eye and Wright contends he suffered facial
cuts.
   Before sending the case to the jury, Blizzard dismissed the City
of Huntsville as a defendant based on insufficient evidence, and
the plaintiffs' attorneys dropped the band's promoters from the
suit.
   Jimmy Alexander, one of the plaintiffs' attorneys, said they
will file for reinstatement of the city as a co-defendant within
the next few days. He said he and the teen-agers' other attorneys
believe the dismissal of the city as a defendant was a major factor
in the jury deadlock.
   Mitchell said most jurors were sympathetic to the plaintiffs,
but insufficient proof of ``something coming off the stage''
produced the deadlock.
   ``Someone could have thrown a bottle; there are a lot of things
that could have happened, and if you go to one of those rock
concerts you are likely to see anything going on,'' he said.
   The trial, which began May 9, drew crowds of young fans trying
to catch a glimpse of band member Nikki Sixx, who was in the
courtroom daily.
</TEXT>
