<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Nuclear     05-17 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Nuclear,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain to Replace Old Free-Fall Bombs With New Weapon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain will replace its aging free-fall nuclear
bombs with a new nuclear weapon, Defense Secretary George Younger
said in a BBC interview broadcast Monday.
   The Independent newspaper, whose correspondent interviewed
Younger on the TV program, said nuclear-tipped missiles would
replace the bombs.
   The program called ``Replacing the Hidden Bomb'' also quoted
Ronald Lehman, a U.S. assistant secretary for defense, as saying
the United States has been discussing a joint project to build the
weapon with France and Britain.
   Younger said on the British Broadcasting Corp.'s current events
program ``Panorama'' that details of the new weapon would be
decided in a year to 18 months.
   He rejected the notion that the project might undermine the
U.S.-Soviet Intermediate Nuclear Forces treaty to eliminate an
entire class of land-based missiles in Europe, saying the weapon is
a ``replacement, a modernization of a system which is going out of
date.''
   The Independent reported that the government wants to build a
missile with a 300-mile range, with stealth-radar absorbing
materials. The missiles covered by the INF treaty have a minimum
range of about 310 miles.
   The new missiles would replace the British air force's
20-year-old bombs codenamed WE177, and would be carried by
Britain's Tornado bombers, the same planes that carry most of the
old bombs, it said.
   The old bomb has to be dropped over or very close to its target.
A missile could be launched from a distance and enable the bomber
to avoid enemy air defenses.
   The newspaper estimated that about 200 of the old bombs were
produced.
   It quoted unidentified defense sources as saying the final cost
of the new missile project was likely to be 3 billion pounds ($5.67
billion).
   Last December, Younger and French Defense Minister Andre Giraud
announced after a meeting that they would study further the
possibility of an Anglo-French missile.
   Published reports, which were not denied by officials, said the
missile would be a longer-range version of France's ASMP nuclear
air-to-surface missiles carried by Mirage warplanes.
   These missiles have a 50-125-mile range, depending on the firing
angle.
   The BBC program quoted Lehman as saying the United States
supported the idea of a three-way project and had discussed it with
both countries.
   Lehman said the United States believed that a cooperative
program would be a ``very good way'' for it to modernize its own
nuclear weapons economically.
   ``When Younger raised this in December, we thought it was a good
idea,'' said Lehman. ``We've had good discussions in a number of
bilateral meetings and our first trilateral meeting in March.''
   Giraud also appeared on the program Monday. He said that
although he has no objections to a three-nation deal, he was ``very
suspicious of cooperation involving too numerous partners.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
