<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CarrieCloses     05-17 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carrie Closes,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Carrie' Closes on Broadway at a Loss of $8 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Carrie,'' the musical version of Stephen
King's horror novel, closed over the weekend after a
five-performance run and a loss estimated at a record $8 million, a
spokesman for the show said Monday.
   The musical about a teen-age girl with the power to move and
destroy objects folded Sunday after five performances and 16
previews, spokesman Jim Baldassare said.
   The show, which starring Betty Buckley and newcomer Linzi
Hateley in the title role, was panned by most critics, receiving
some of the severest reviews of the season.
   ``Carrie'' was budgeted at $7 million, according to Baldassare,
but needed extra financing after the opening was postponed several
weeks to allow more rehearsal time. Other shows, such as ``The
Phantom of the Opera'' and ``Starlight Express,'' have cost as much
but are still running.
   Broadway has had some quick and expensive flops in recent years,
but nothing as costly as ``Carrie.'' ``Big Deal,'' a Bob Fosse
musical from 1986, lost an estimated $5 million, as did ``Grind,''
a burlesque musical that had a short run in 1985.
   ``Carrie'' was plagued by trouble ever since it began its
pre-Broadway tryout in Stratford, England, last February. Barbara
Cook, its original star, dropped out after the British engagement
and was replaced by Miss Buckley.
   ``Carrie'' was produced by Friedrich Kurz, a West German
financier, and the Royal Shakespeare Company and directed by Terry
Hands, the artistic head of the the RSC.
   The show had music and lyrics by Michael Gore and Dean
Pitchford, the team responsible for the music for the movie version
of ``Fame.''
   Its cast was a mixture of American and British performers who
were allowed to appear both in England and New York under a special
agreement from actors unions in both countries.
   ``Carrie'' was more successful as a film. The movie, directed by
Brian Depalma, starred Sissy Spacek as the troubled teen-ager who
is taunted and tormented by other high school students and her
mother before she gets revenge on prom night.
</TEXT>
