<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Mexico-Candidate Adv24   05-17 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Candidate, Adv 24,0643</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues AMs, May 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Opposition Candidate Says His Party Is Mexico's `Only Option'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ENSENADA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``What is lacking is democracy, where
the people no longer are tricked, where there are no monopolies of
any kind, particularly when the monopoly opens the door to
electoral fraud,'' presidential candidate Manuel J. Clouthier was
saying.
   ``We are fighting all of this and we are going to win.''
   ``We'' is the National Action Party, which has put up the
staunchest opposition to Mexico's long-dominant Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has won every election since its
inception in 1929.
   But National Action, known as PAN, has been making deeper
inroads against PRI in northern Mexico in recent years and now
believes it has a better chance than ever to come away with an
upset in the presidential election July 6.
   The 53-year-old Clouthier, a prosperous agricultural
businessman, made his point about winning in an interview with The
Associated Press while on a campaign swing through the northwestern
border state of Northern Baja California.
   He has visited more than 70 cities and towns across Mexico in
his campaign and has sought to portray himself and PAN as a
free-market alternative to PRI's political and economic
centralization.
   ``We are the only real option for change because we are rabidly
democratic, because we want democracy politically, economically,
culturally,'' Clouthier said. ``We are not in favor of government
control of the economy; we represent a social market economy.''
   National Action is strong in northern Mexico, but it has never
been able to build a national base to challenge the PRI, whose
presidential candidate is Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   ``I see that the people of Mexico are more disposed to change
things,'' Clouthier said of conditions now. ``They have been
repressed but are ready to fight once more for the change that they
yearn for.
   ``Our way is distinct; the state monopoly is not concerned with
initiative because it sacrifices everything for the sake of
control.''
   ``Maquio,'' as Clouthier is popularly known, places
responsibility for Mexico's economic troubles on Salinas de
Gortari, who had served as budget and planning secretary under the
incumbent president, Miguel de la Madrid.
   Clouthier supports private enterprise, more government
austerity, greater foreign investment and allowing peasants to own
the land they now are allowed to use and pass on to their children
but not sell.
   For years National Action was the only significant opposition to
the PRI, but the economic difficulties that have lasted throughout
de la Madrid's administration have allowed Clouthier and four other
minority candidates to take a more vocal and visible role this year.
   PAN, cast as a conservative opposition group, has strong support
from business and the Roman Catholic church hierarchy.
   Clouthier, running on a Program for Economic Construction,
contends that corruption has played an important part in Mexico's
economic crisis.
   ``Regarding the foreign debt, the majority of which the
government contracted on the shoulders of the people, I would first
seize the goods of the public officials who have enriched
themselves,'' he said in the interview.
   Mexico's foreign debt of $105 billion is the second largest in
the developing world after Brazil's.
   Clouthier favors the return of the Mexican banking system to the
private sector.
   ``Since the banks have been `ours,' there has been no credit for
the campesino (peasant),'' he said.
   The government of President Jose Lopez Portillo nationalized the
banks in September 1982, at the outset of the economic crisis
brought on by falling oil prices.
   PAN was the runnerup in the 1982 presidential race, with 15.8
percent of votes against 70.9 percent for de la Madrid.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues AMs, May 24</NOTE>
