<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, May 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rules or Not, Juice Prevails for Many Christians, Wine for Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Issue or non-issue, it still was the question.
   United Methodists debated whether to retain a rule requiring use
of grape juice in communion. They dropped the rule, but most will
still retain the practice.
   That was the curious consequence of a bubbling interlude at the
church's governing conference in St. Louis earlier this month,
throwing a spotlight upon the diverse customs of denominations.
   Some use wine, some juice, some both. For some, it's an option
to be decided congregation by congregation.
   Whatever the choice, it is a feature of Christianity's central
act of worship, commemorating the Last Supper of Jesus with his
apostles before his crucifixion, at which he bade them perpetuate
that sacred meal.
   ``Take, eat, this is my body, which is given for you,'' he said
as he broke bread with them. Of the wine, he said, ``Drink ... this
is my blood of the new covenant, poured out for you and for many
for the forgiveness of sin.''
   Distinct communion customs among Christian denominations
sometimes produce unusual arrangements. In some ecumenical
settings, such as the Consultation on Church Union, involving nine
denominations, celebrating communion sometimes has involved two
tables, one dispensing wine, the other grape juice.
   In general, wine is used in churches with classic liturgies,
including the Episcopal, Lutheran, Roman Catholic and Eastern
Orthodox churches. It's also standard in the Christian Reformed
Church.
   Among Presbyterian, United Church of Christ and Reformed Church
in America congregations, the usage varies, some congregations
using wine, others grape juice, some offering both.
   Grape juice is used in most Baptist churches and in the majority
of Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) congregations, although a
few use wine.
   That is also the case for United Methodists, whose choice of
grape juice has a commercially tinged story behind it that
knowledgeable old-timers insist is real history.
   The story is that the founder of the Welch grape juice
enterprise, a devoted Methodist, persuaded the church's governing
conference in the early 1900s to adopt a rule requiring use of
grape juice.
   That rule has been on the books ever since, a part of the
rubrics for worship in the church hymnbook, reading in its 1966
edition:
   ``The Lord's table should have upon it a fair linen cloth. Let
the pure unfermented juice of the grape be used.''
   But that hymnbook, its rituals and rubrics were replaced at the
recent conference, and the revised version leaves out the grape
juice rule.
   This omission caused considerable splashes of debate, twice
impelling the Rev. Richard L. Wright of Buckhannon, W.Va., to
intervene with proposals to restore the rule for grape juice.
   ``We have a long tradition of opposition to the use of alcoholic
beverages in our church,'' he said.
   However, the Rev. Tex S. Sample, a Kansas City, Mo., theologian,
argued that keeping a rule that looks ``highly moralistic'' would
drive off young people who would go elsewhere.
   He said research indicates the reason United Methodists are not
increasing is because ``we are not attracticing those young people
under 42 or 43 years of age on the cultural left of our country. ...
   ``If we continue to moralize about these personal issues, we
will drive them away from our denomination and not have a
compelling evangelical power to draw them into it.''
   However, June Goldman, a Spirit Lake, Iowa, delegate, said, ``We
have been adrift,'' and young people ``want us to say there are
parameters.'' Keeping the rule, she said, would give ``definite
directions'' to the young.
   ``When we are wishy-wishy, our young people lose faith in us,''
she said.
   The delegates voted strongly, 525 to 343, against retaining the
rule, and also, en bloc, voted down a batch of similar measures,
thus eliminating the old juice-only law.
   In the new hymnal-worship book, the communion service uses the
words, ``the cup'' and ``the wine'' interchangeably, while old book
uses only ``the cup,'' not mentioning wine _ as now is done.
   Even so, veteran Methodists said the long-time custom of using
juice would doubtless continue, although a few, scattered
congregations use wine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, May 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
