<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-AmericanAbroad Adv22   05-17 1088</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-American Abroad, Adv 22,1125</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>American Pizza King Turns English Estate Into Hotel-Like-No-Other</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAPLEFORD PARK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strapping, exuberant Bob Payton,
Britain's most famous American entrepreneur, has one very prominent
British characteristic: eccentricity.
   It's evident all over Stapleford Park, the 500-year-old country
house the man who became London's pizza king is turning into a
hotel-like-no-other in his latest venture.
   For example, he'll have a fire in the fireplace every day of the
year, not for the heat but for the smell.
   Then there's the trompe l'oeil in the grand tea room. Peering
over the painted banister is a likeness of Gunther, Mrs. Payton's
giant schnauzer, wearing a red-white-and-blue bandanna. The dog was
added to the decor to celebrate his release from the six-month
quarantine required of every immigrating pet.
   ``I wanted things to be 5 degrees off,'' Payton said, explaining
his desire to have things a bit off-kilter.
   Gunther now trots happily around the 55-acre estate in
Leicestershire hunt country, where Payton and his wife, Wendy, are
striving to create the American dream of an English country house.
More specifically, it's a Victorian gentleman's hunting lodge,
which opened its doors to guests in April.
   ``It's sort of Disney World for real,'' said Payton, who is 6
feet 4 inches tall and weighs 250 pounds and on this misty day was
wearing a bold argyle sweater with matching socks.
   Payton bought the home, 110 miles north of London, from Lord
John Gretton of the Bass brewing family more than two years ago. He
used $1.4 million of his own money and since has spent millions
more of investors' money renovating it.
   Payton, who became famous and wealthy by bringing Chicago-style,
deep-dish pizza to London, is deliberate in his details and panders
to American notions of what is English.
   The 23 rooms and suites, which cost $160 to $611 a night, have
been decorated not only by the usual interior designers but also by
well-known English companies, chosen for their recognizeable brand
names.
   For the Wedgwood Room, the chinaware makers chose hand-printed
wallpaper in its blue-with-white-cameos Jasper design.
   Shirtmakers Turnbull and Asser hung framed bow ties and curtains
made of forest green velvet, of the smoking-jacket variety, lined
with silk paisley.
   The Liberty Room is cheered with the fabric designer's renowned
small-flower prints.
   The 125-room house, with a grand, sweeping staircase, is long on
marble, mahogany paneling, 16-foot ceilings, leather sofas and
framed pictures of British royalty.
   Peek into the ``loo,'' the men's room, and heads of wildebeests
stare down at you from high on the walls.
   Not wanting the hotel to look too new, he ordered reproductions
of Victorian spigots.
   From the stone mullion windows are stunning views of gently
undulating, green countryside featuring sheep, frolicking horses in
a grazing paddock and a still lake.
   Payton has worked under the close scrutiny of British
preservation officials who have allowed him some distinctly
American flourishes, too, like the miniature golf course and a
basketball net and backboard. Homemade chocolate-chip cookies are
left on bedside tables in the rooms.
   Payton, who went to the University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill and still gulps diet soda from an oversized school mug, is
treating the hotel like an informal house party.
   The Land Rover that picks up guests at the train station, half
an hour away in Grantham, arrives with a cooler stocked with
Chicago beer.
   ``It's not going to be a health farm,'' said Payton.
   He has lived in Britain for 15 years and first saw the house in
1980 while he was ``riding to hounds,'' or fox hunting.
   ``I walked through the front door of the place and I knew it had
to be preserved for what it was,'' Payton said. ``This is quite a
staggering edifice.''
   At the time, he added, ``I was looking for something new to
invent. I thought, `What am I going to do with my life once I've
created my business?'''
   Payton launched that business with a pizza restaurant in 1977,
when he quit the J. Walter Thompson advertising agency, which had
hired him in Chicago and transferred him to London.
   Payton had worked his way through college playing drums in a
rock band, and went on to Northwestern University in Evanston,
Ill., to earn a master's degree in advertising.
   The son of a traveling salesman, Payton was born in Troy, N.Y.,
and reared in Miami.
   Although he had trouble raising the initial $66,000 for his
first pizza restaurant, his company became hugely successful and
will be operating 14 restaurants with names like Chicago Pizza Pie
Factory and Chicago Rib Shack in London and on the European
continent by the end of the year.
   The company is called My Kinda Town Ltd. _ Payton says that
refers both to Chicago and London _ and had an after-tax profit of
$1.88 million on revenue of $21 million in 1987.
   Payton managed to raise $8.5 million for Stapleford Park by
privately selling stock in My Kinda Town, in which he retains a
majority interest.
   What makes this hotel a bold experiment is that it's in a part
of the country that has traditionally attracted few tourists.
   It is a two-hour drive from Heathrow Airport in London, or a
90-minute train ride from London's King's Cross station, before you
get into the Rover and take a beer from the cooler.
   Payton, who lives in a private wing of Stapleford Park, is
relying on word of mouth instead of advertising and says not only
Americans will come to his hotel.
   ``Americans don't want to come here and meet other Americans,''
he said. ``The worst thing is people coming here and it's all
Americans.''
   Bookings are ``pretty good,'' said Payton, who expects the
operation will break even in the first year and make a profit in
the second.
   And if he fails, he can always sell the house, which he now
values at about $12 million.
   However, he says profit is not his principal motive in
Stapleford Park.
   ``I`ve done my bit for society by preserving this,'' Payton
said. ``I've given this house the opportunity to live again like it
did in its heyday.''
   Carved on the outside of the limestone building is ``William
Lord Sherard Baron of Letrym Repayred this Building Anno Domini
1633.''
   Payton had a mason carve in an addition: ``And Bob Payton Esq.
Did His Bit Anno Domini 1988.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
