<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-AmericanIsraeli Adv22-2Takes   05-17 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-American Israeli, Adv 22-2 Takes,0789</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>American Killed Fighting for Israel Leaves Diary, Poems</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandy-haired Alex Singer, an American Ivy
League honors graduate and jazz lover, dreamed of being an artist
or writer, but religious fervor brought him to Israel and to his
death as a soldier on his 25th birthday.
   Lt. Alex Singer was killed in a raid inside Lebanon on Sept. 15.
   But his talents as an artist and writer live on in 200 pages of
diaries.
   He has left behind a rare portrait of an Israeli soldier.
   The diaries are filled with pencil drawings of military
maneuvers, army camps and the barren landscape of war.
   The words, in verse and prose, are of his thoughts as a
commander of other men in war and tell of listening for the sound
of enemy footsteps in southern Lebanon and confronting Palestinian
anger in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   Some of the notebooks were found in Singer's kitbag the day he
was shot on a mission to flush out Palestinian guerrillas trying to
infiltrate Israel's northern border settlements. His family gave
copies to The Associated Press.
   In verse done while still in officers' training, Singer
confronts his feelings about the day when he will face combat:
   ``If the war comes
   ``When the war comes
   ``I will have to lead men to die.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``But those men were not men a short time ago.
   ``Some don't even shave yet.
   ``And I will have to have the calm power
   ``To yell to them or to whisper
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Kadima (Hebrew for ``forward'')
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``And
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I will have to have the calm power
   ``To step forward myself.''
   Alex Singer came to Israel in December 1984, seven months after
graduating summa cum laude from Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y.
Three days later he joined the army.
   His brother Daniel, 22, said Alex's deepening attachment to
Judaism moved him to emigrate and join the military.
   ``As a Jew, Israel played an important part in his life, and it
wasn't enough to talk about it, but to act,'' Daniel said in an
interview. ``He considered it a duty and an honor to help defend
the country. He wasn't trying to prove anything. Here it isn't like
in the States, where the Army seems distant. Here it's part of
life.''
   Little in Singer's early days points to a future as a combat
soldier. Daniel said family life in Washington, D.C., was not
religious. The boys' father, Max, is a writer for the Jewish
magazine Commentary, and mother Suzanne is a magazine editor.
   Alex was not athletic. He suffered from asthma and was a
bookworm, a loner. On travels he went off by himself to sketch
landscapes. He took solace in the jazz of Ella Fitgerald and Louis
Armstrong and the folk rock of Simon and Garfunkel.
   A boyhood trip to Israel inspired Alex to think seriously about
Judaism, said Daniel. In college, his Jewish identity became so
intense that he devoted his thesis to the subject.
   For the thesis, ``Letters from the Diaspora,'' Alex traveled to
London, Moscow and Cordoba, Spain, in search of Jewish life.
   Later he visited Jordan, and Daniel said it was the trip to the
Arab world that solidified Alex's feeling for serving Israel.
   ``There he really learned what the Arabs think of us. It really
brought it all down to earth for him,'' said Daniel, who also
served three years in Israel's army.
   In the military, Alex combined his talents for writing and
drawing with his duties. His journals are filled with meticulous
drawings of weapons, such as Israeli-made Galil rifles, grenades
and TOW missiles.
   On a page dated July 9, 1987, Singer sketched an officer
briefing soldiers before a battalion exercise in the Golan Heights,
near the Syrian border.
   The troops sweated up a hill attacking a mock Syrian base, but
Singer's record was mostly about losing his prayer shawl and
phylacteries, or prayer straps, in a bag that disappeared in the
charge.
   ``We ran and retraced our exact steps,'' he wrote. ``I was just
about to give up looking when two-thirds up the hill, I saw the bag
on the ground, right where we started charging.''
   In training, Singer dedicated one diary page to a drawing of his
feet with arrows pointing to callouses and bunions. He bemoaned the
life of a foot soldier and talked of transferring from the infantry
to the tank corps.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880517-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-AmericanIsraeli Adv22-1stAdd   05-17 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-American Israeli, Adv 22-1st Add,0603</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>JERUSALEM: tank corps.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nevertheless, he volunteered for the Givati Brigade, an elite
combat unit famed for its fight on the Egyptian border in the
Independence War of 1948.
   The Givati troops get the toughest jobs, and Singer frequently
wrote that he was glad to be guarding the northern frontier.
   ``I like this type of front-line duty,'' he wrote in January
1986. ``Being in Lebanon makes all that goes on closer. I feel
pride when I know that we are the ones sent in the end to do the
work.''
   In later entries Singer described in painstaking detail missions
he commanded along the border. In one instance, he wrote about
being on watch in a wooded border post.
   ``I heard footsteps on the other side of the fence, 20 yards
from our gang. I put a bullet in the chamber of my gun and looked
to find the source of the steps.
   ``My heart was beating fast and we were ready to open fire. I
passed an order left and right not to shoot until they hear me
shouting `fire'! The tension was unbelievable. After 15 minutes or
so the sounds stopped _ it must have been a wild boar or
something.''
   In an entry last summer, Singer wrote of awakening to find the
platoon's sentries asleep near the border fence, near what Israelis
call Mount Dov, the site of battles between the Israelis and
Palestinian guerrillas attempting to infiltrate.
   ``There is no doubt that my waking up on my own saved one or
more of us ... from paying the corresponding price.''
   The diaries also include descriptions of a month in 1987 in the
occupied Gaza Strip, a coastal zone crowded with 600,000
Palestinian refugees.
   Most of these accounts reflect the hostility and fear of
soldiers in street patrols and house-to-house searches for
guerrilla suspects.
   ``I saw `Palestine' written on a door,'' Singer wrote. ``We
stop, I call a man from the house, take his ID, tell him he gets
his ID when the graffiti is gone. He calls his wife who brings
H-2-O and washes it.''
   But Singer also wrote that he tried to teach men in his platoon
to be tolerant of Arabs. In an entry titled ``Idea for Teaching
About the Difference of a Jewish Army,'' Singer wrote:
   ``We can go either way: 1) Arabs as ... `jukim' (cockroaches) or
2) Arabs as people.
   ``Israel must take the second path because Israel is a Jewish
state, a democratic state and a light unto nations.''
   Four months later, Singer was sent on his final mission into
Lebanon and got the first taste of combat he'd written about in
verse two years before.
   According to other accounts of the day, guerrillas hiding behind
boulders surprised Singer's patrol with bursts of gunfire just
after the Israelis landed near Mount Dov by helicopter. Singer was
shot as he ran up a hill taking a medic to a wounded comrade.
   President Reagan praised Singer's heroism in a message of
condolence to his parents.
   Daniel said the family is proud of Alex's devotion to Israel and
plans a public exhibit of his drawings and diaries.
   But, he added, it does not make up for a lost brother.
   ``This is something that takes the glamour out of being in the
army,'' he said. ``It's like having a hole where something was. You
can't fill it. You have to walk around it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
