<DOCNO> AP880517-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   05-17 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0558</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At The Movies: ``Da''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago, ``Da'' captivated Broadway audiences with its
Irish charm and insights into father-son relationships. Now, ``Da''
has been translated to film and, as the Irish might say, a lovely
movie it is.
   Time, which sometimes dims the best of stories, seems to have
burnished the glow of ``Da,'' which transports viewers from
present-day New York to a rural Irish village with cobblestone
streets and fragrant gardens.
   It is here that we meet Da, the shorthand name for father.
Barnard Hughes, whose portrayal won awards on the New York stage,
recreates the role of the old man whose death stirs up an emotional
whirlwind for his adopted son, Charlie.
   Martin Sheen is Charlie, a successful playwright who returns to
his Irish homeland for the funeral of his adoptive father and is
haunted by memories of the man whose complex personality colored
his son's life.
   ``I love you, Da,'' Sheen tells the father whose ghost
self-confidently replies, ``Why wouldn't you?''
   That question leads Sheen on a tortuous journey back to his own
childhood, reliving the worst moments through now critical eyes.
Da's interference in Charlie's youthful pursuit of a neighbor girl
becomes humorous in retrospect. A sequence in which Charlie's
mother decrees that the rambunctious family dog must be drowned and
Da sets out to do the deed is agonizing. Da's outrageous defense of
Hitler while Charlie's prospective employer visits the family makes
the old man out as something of a fool.
   But there are better times remembered as well, and Charlie is
inevitably lured back by his father's Irish magnetism. As Da
declares: ``Love turned upside down is love for all that.''
   Hughes' portrayal of Da is about as pefect as acting gets. The
white haired, blue-eyed Hughes creates the magic that makes Da the
inhabitant of his son's dreams. Sheen is just right as Charlie,
resentful but loving, determined to shed his father's ghost but
unwilling to let their relationship die.
   There are other fine performances here. Karl Hayden makes an
impressive film debut as the self-conscious young Charlie. William
Hickey is memorable as Drumm, Charlie's first, demanding employer.
And Doreen Hepburn, as Charlie's mother, projects the combined
sweetness and strength of a realist who sees her gardener-husband
for what he is.
   Matt Clark directed the film, which is often seen in the brown
and gold tones of memory. A co-star certainly is Ireland, in
particular the village of Dalkey which was playwright Hugh
Leonard's home. The seaside vistas, the green hills and the
extraordinary rose garden which Leonard's father (the real life Da)
planted 60 years ago are part of charm of this thoroughly
satisfying film.
   Da is rated PG. Running time is 102 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
