<DOCNO> AP880517-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   05-17 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How do retailers know what will sell and what
won't among the 500 or more home videos available each month?
   Box-office hits, such as ``Fatal Attraction,'' ``Beverly Hills
Cop II'' and ``Dirty Dancing'' are sure shots, regardless of their
artistic demerits. Then there are sleeper films, such as ``Prick Up
Your Ears,'' that attracted small audiences and might not make
whopping good rentals.
   Some video store owners are turning to ``Video Forecaster,'' a
report published by bi-monthly by Warren Adler, who uses consumer
polls and other marketing tools to give retailers the odds on a
particular movie.
   In the May 1-15 edition, for example, ``Barfly,'' starring Faye
Dunaway and Mickey Rourke, received a ``high'' consumer awareness
level and a ``good'' from critics, but the much acclaimed ``Hope
and Glory'' only got a ``poor'' awareness level and a ``rave'' from
critics.
   ``Fatal Beauty,'' the Whoopi Goldberg bomb, had a ``very high''
consumer awareness level but a ``poor'' rating from critics
   The publication also lists stars, a synopsis of the film,
consumers' intent to rent or buy _ medium for ``Barfly'' and ``Hope
and Glory,'' but very high for ``Fatal Beauty'' _ box office
grosses, number of weeks it ran and comments from Video Forecaster
on how it will do.
   ``We've reduced our purchasing now to a few hours a month,''
said J. Fred Sproule of Super Video, Inc., in Seattle. ``We buy for
60 stores and spend over $100,000 a month on video, so this has
become very valuable to us.''
   Bruce George of Sundance Audio and Video in Yuba City, Calif.,
said the report ``protects us from buying everything out there.''
   Adler, whose ``The War of the Roses'' will be produced by
Academy Award winning director James L. Brooks (``Terms of
Endearment,'' ``Broadcast News''), started ``Video Forecaster'' in
Los Angeles in 1987.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Barfly'' and ``Real Men.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Barfly'' (Warner Home Video, VHS-Beta and available with</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Spanish subtitles and closed captioned for the hearing impaired,
$89.95, Rated R for language)
   
   Despite great reviews, this offbeat 1987 Barbet Schroeder film
didn't get a wide release, so if you missed it, the video is a
second chance to catch first-rate performances by Mickey Rourke and
Faye Dunaway, not to mention beat- generation writer Charles
Bukowski's wonderfully lucid observations which fall like diamonds
from the mouth of muttering skid-row writer Henry Chinaski.
   Henry falls in love with fellow barfly Wanda Wilcox, an
irascible sort who observes when she meets him, ``I hate people. Do
you hate people?''
   ``No,'' says Henry, ``but I feel better when they're not
around.''
   When not stimulating his senses by taunting a tough-guy
bartender (Frank Stallone) into knocking the stuffing out of him,
Chinaski dashes off brilliant scribblings to a literary magazine
which hires a private eye to track him down. What a gem. Not a
Naugahyde barstool out of place.
   _ By Kathryn Baker, AP Television Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Real Men'' (CBS@Fox, VHS@Beta, $79.98, Rated PG-13)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Real Men'' is a far-out farce about male bonding and role
reversals that sinks under the weight of its own absurdity.
   The funny parts appeal to those who laugh at assassinations, car
bombings, kidnappings, gun fights and double crosses, all of which
happen in the first 10 minutes.
   A macho CIA agent played by James Belushi coerces the help of a
wimpy suburbanite insurance agent played by John Ritter in order to
save the world. Ritter happens to look just like a dead CIA agent.
   The mission is to get to Washington within five days to get a
secret formula from space aliens who have an antidote to a poison
that is destroying the food chain and will make the Earth lifeless
in five years.
   Wait, there's more.
   The unlikely pair must contend with Soviet agents and a faction
in the CIA that wears clown suits. The CIA clowns have a different
deal for the spacemen. They want a gun capable of destroying the
planet instead of the antidote.
   On their wacky journey, Ritter meets Belushi's father _ who had
a sex change operation and comes on to Ritter.
   Later, in a Pittsburgh bar, tough guy Belushi falls in love with
a whip-cracking seductress. Ritter, meanwhile, sheds his
milquetoast mannerisms by foiling a robbery and completing the
mission.
   The price asked by the spacemen to save the world is a glass of
water. The payoff somehow matches the drippy comedy.
   _ By Robert Dvorchak, AP National Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
