<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   05-17 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0648</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Chalk Mark in a Rain Storm'' (Geffen) Joni Mitchell
   
   Joni Mitchell doesn't need any help, but she is nevertheless
joined by an all-star cast on this eclectic, profoundly political
effort. The cast is just as varied _ Willie Nelson, Billy Idol,
Peter Gabriel, Don Henley, Tom Petty, Wendy and Lisa and even Iron
Eyes Cody makes a guest appearance.
   The cuts include some remakes: a jazzy version of ``Corrina,
Corrina'' (titled ``A Bird That Whistles'') featuring Wayne Shorter
on sax, and ``Cool Water'' _ yeah, that song by the Sons of the
Pioneers _ a duet with Willie Nelson.
   Mitchell seems to be having more fun musically on this album
than she has in the past, but in some ways she seems almost
visually oriented, casting parts in the songs and referring in an
interview to one of them as ``cinematic.''
   Her own material, evincing at various times her folk, jazz and
rock influences, is emotional and highly political.
   ``The Tea Leaf Prophecy,'' is a poignant reminiscence of wars
past set against a melodic chant, ``Study war no more.'' Gabriel
sings on the lovely ``My Secret Place.'' Henley trades vocal leads
with Mitchell on the wry ``Snakes and Ladders.'' Iron Eyes Cody
intones the opening lines of ``Lakota,'' a pulsing Hopi lament.
   Recorded, appropriately enough, at Peter Gabriel's studio in
Bath, England, ``The Beat of Black Wings'' was written after the
U.S. bombing of Libya. The lyrics are the words of a soldier,
``Killer Kyle,'' who notes ``the old pick the wars, we die in
'em.'' He gives the album its poignant title: ``Keep the drinks
comin', girl. 'Til I can't feel anything. I'm just a chalk mark in
a rain storm. ...''
   _ By Kathryn Baker, AP Television Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Green Thoughts'' (Capitol) _ Smithereens
   
   Ever since John, Paul and George strapped on guitars and sat
Ringo behind the drum kit, thousands of kids have devoted their
lives to a search for the perfect melody. It's a wonder the classic
1960s song structure can still sound fresh today.
   The Smithereens, a New Jersey-based quartet, do better than
most. Their crisp melodies and tight performances made 1986's
``Especially for You'' an unusually strong debut, and the new
``Green Thoughts'' is a worthy follow-up.
   Actually, those '60s comparisons probably rankle the
Smithereens. As much as bands want to emulate their heroes from
those days, a reputation as a band more interested in the past than
the present could be a death sentence.
   That fear seems to be a motivating force encouraging the
Smithereens to stretch a bit. They know the rock graveyard is
littered with nondescript jangly guitar bands.
   On songs such as ``Drown in My Own Tears'' and ``The World We
Know,'' guitarist Jim Babjak employs a bass-like fuzztone that
rattles the backbone. Fortunately, the Smithereens are equally
adept when things quiet down, with the ballad ``Especially for
You'' noteworthy for its sax solo by Los Lobos' Steve Berlin.
   ``Green Thoughts'' may be more appropriately titled after a
darker shade. Lead singer Pat DiNizio, whose odd goatee gives him
the look of a beatnik, is one lonely guy. Consequently, the record
is top-heavy with songs of shattered romance and late-night
yearning.
   That can be done well, of course; ``Elaine'' is a particularly
pretty take on that theme. But DiNizio's already come close to
exhausting it. Maybe a girlfriend would help.
   Given the well-documented pitfalls of new bands trying to prove
they have more than one good album in them, the Smithereens can be
proud of ``Green Thoughts.''
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
