<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Hanks Adv27-29   05-17 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Hanks, Adv 27-29,0879</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27-29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 27-29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: A Grinning Optimist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Tom Hanks seems like a grinning optimist
on the screen, it's not just acting.
   ``When I wake up in the morning, I'm a pretty happy guy,'' he
says. ``I'm not one of these guys who rolls out of bed and is
groggy for an hour and a half until he has blueberry pancakes and
six cups of coffee. I wake up and the sun is shining or the clouds
are raining and I think it's great either way.
   ``Where that comes from, I don't know. I'll leave that off to
the DNA (genetic materials) that my parents planted in me.''
   Hanks has more than the usual reasons to be happy nowadays. He
stars in two promising comedies this summer: ``Big,'' in which he
plays a 12-year-old whose wish to be an adult is granted;
``Punchline,'' in which he co-stars with Sally Field as a pair of
aspiring stand-up comics.
   And on March 30 he married actress Rita Wilson, whom he met
while both were appearing in ``Volunteers.''
   Until now, Hanks has mostly been seen with co-stars: Darryl
Hannah (``Splash''); John Candy (``Volunteers''); Shelley Long
(``The Money Pit''); Jackie Gleason (``Nothing in Common''); Dan
Aykroyd (``Dragnet''). With ``Big,'' Hanks flies solo, though he
draws strong support from Elizabnt and debonair.''
   The highlight of ``Big'' provided the biggest physical
challenge. Hanks and his boss, Loggia, perform a dance in New
York's F.A.O. Schwarz toy store on king-size piano keys, tapping
out ``Chopsticks'' and ``Heart and Soul.''
   ``It was a huge dance number that required hours and hours and
hours of rehearsal stretched out over a six-week period,'' Hanks
said. ``When we finally finished shooting it, I said, `Our long
national nightmare is over.'''
   Like Tom Cruise, Demi Moore, Rebecca De Mornay and other stars
of his generation, Hanks had an unsettled childhood. His parents
divorced when he was young, and he moved back and forth between
them. Growing up in Northern California, he figures he and a
brother and sister changed homes every six months. Instead of
growing withdrawn, he became a joker.
   ``Part of it is a self-defense mechanism,'' he reflected. ``I
moved around a lot when I was a kid and found myself in new cities
and with new friends and new family members. It also comes from a
brand of communication that was developed between my siblings and
my mom and my dad.''
   Hanks discovered theater at Sacramento State University and was
invited by director Vincent Dowling to join the Great Lakes
Shakespeare Festival in Cleveland. He moved to New York, then came
to Hollywood in 1980 to star in the well-remembered ``Bosom Buddy''
series for ABC. The series' untimely end freed Hanks for films, and
he has been working steadily ever since.
   He has played a variety of roles, but producers view him as a
comedian. He remains philosophical about being so pigeonholed.
   ``I have made my peace long ago with the fact that I'm a funny
guy,'' he said. ``I treated it like a curse for a long time, but
it's just as much of a fact that I have two feet.
   ``The fear of being labeled as a comedian? I don't care. I'd
rather just let the sum total of all the work just speak for itself
over the long haul.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 27-29</NOTE>
</DOC>
