<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Menotti Adv27-29   05-17 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Menotti, Adv 27-29,0898</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27-29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 27-29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: The Secret of Spoleto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secret of the Spoleto Festival's success is
that there is no real program, says composer Gian Carlo Menotti,
who has led the arts celebration for three decades.
   ``We do whatever we feel like doing. We surprise our audience
and the press,'' he said.
   ``We are against all commemorations. During the anniversary of
Bach's birth, we do Beethoven. During the anniversary of Beethoven,
we do Stravinsky. We keep away from everything that is somewhat
dictated. We use instinct and imagination. We don't announce a
program two or three years in advance because we never know what
we're going to do.''
   This year, at the 112-event Spoleto Festival U.S.A. in
Charleston, S.C., Menotti felt like presenting Dvorak's 1901 opera,
``Rusalka.'' Since the first act is supposed to take place under
water, ``Rusalka'' has only been done in this country a handful of
times since its American premiere in 1935.
   John Paull III, technical production manager for Broadway's
``The Phantom of the Opera,'' is in charge of ``Rusalka.'' He is
swathing the stage in China-blue silk for the water and bringing
soprano Maria Spacagna as the water nymph Rusalka _ who lives in
the lake _ onto the stage through a trap door.
   Her father, the Water Sprite, at one point becomes angry and
creates a whirlpool. The silk spins round and round.
   Menotti founded the Festival of the Two Worlds in Spoleto,
Italy, in 1958, and later founded the Spoleto Festival U.S.A. in
Charleston _ this year it runs from May 20 to June 5 _ and the
Spoleto Festival of the Three Worlds in Melbourne, Australia. He
still heads all of them.
   ``We create a festive atmosphere,'' Menotti said in a recent
interview. ``I always think of it involving the whole town. I
wanted to see if an artist can be as important a member of a
community as a doctor. The people of Charleston have the dignity of
knowing arts are needed.''
   Menotti recently directed his 1950 opera, ``The Consul,'' in
Bulgaria. The opera, which opened the first Spoleto Festival U.S.A.
in 1977, is set in an unidentified police state in which a woman
tries to get a visa for another country where her husband has found
refuge.
   ``I never thought I would ever see `The Consul' in Bulgaria,''
he said. ``I think they feel it is about some other country. I had
no trouble. I asked somebody if the translation was faithful and
the answer was yes. The audience stood and cheered.
   ``Now the government has asked me to do a film of it in Bulgaria
in English. They offered to pay for everything, the whole
production. They only thing is, they cannot pay foreign singers _
they have no dollars. Soprano Mirella Freni wants to sing the
woman. Her husband, bass Nicolai Ghiaurov, is Bulgarian. There's no
reason his character, the chief of police, shouldn't have an accent.
   ``I accepted. If I'm still alive, I'm going to do it next
year.'' Menotti will be 77 in July.
   The composer also recently has been in Korea where two of his
operas, ``Amelia Goes to the Ball'' and ``The Medium,'' were done
in Korean last year.
   ``Unfortunately, they were a big success. The day before I left,
the head of the Olympic Games talked me into doing an opera. The
only sport I do is tennis and I only win when my son lets me win,''
he said.
   ``I asked what sort of opera I should write. The Olympic Arts
Festival gave me the choice of three possible subjects. I chose the
one I like best for `The Marriage.' It was supposed to be ready in
January and wasn't.'' The premiere is to be in September in Seoul
and Menotti will direct.
   Menotti will compose a piece for chorus and orchestra for the
Atlanta Symphony and will direct ``Tosca'' for the Washington Opera
next spring. ``It is a promise I made to Placido Domingo. It's my
swan song as a director of operas other than my own.''
   He'll also direct when Domingo sings the title role of ``Goya,''
which Menotti composed for him, in Spain next February in its
European premiere.
   Menotti's first grandchild will be a year old in July. ``He is
called Claudio in honor of (composer) Claudio Monteverdi. He
already bangs on the piano. He is very angry because I play
something for him and he can't make it himself. I know he is
musical.
   ``I play for him. He listens and looks at my hands. Then he
bangs. Then he looks at me. Then he gets very frustrated,'' he said.
   The composer of ``Amahl and the Night Visitors'' would like to
do another children's opera.
   ```Help, Help, the Globolinks!' is doing very well and so is
`The Boy Who Grew Too Fast,''' he said. ``I think it is marvelous
to write for children. But I don't know. I don't want to become the
Brother Grimm of opera.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 27-29</NOTE>
</DOC>
