<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0625EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Strait Adv27-29   05-17 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Strait, Adv 27-29,0859</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27-29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 27-29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Strait Revitalizes Country Music</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer George Strait has a
crisp tenor, a lean frame and a career that is rolling like the
tumbleweed in his native Texas.
   The 36-year-old performer has recorded nine gold albums
incorporating a blend of ballads about broken hearts and happier
times.
   In seven years of entertaining, he has helped revitalize
hard-core country music while maintaining a family tradition as a
fourth generation cattle rancher in the Lone Star state.
   Strait has twice been voted male vocalist of the year by the
Country Music Association, but says of his singing: ``I feel that
I'm just getting started.''
   With more than 20 No. 1 records to his credit, the gentleman
cowboy has established himself as a top concert draw treated much
like pop star Tom Jones. The handsome Strait finds boots, flowers,
room keys, cowboy hats, women's underwear and various other items
thrown on stage.
   ``It surprises me,'' he said in an interview. ``People are so
generous. I get nice gifts like quilts, afghans, artwork. I know it
took them a lot of time to make them.''
   He has performed for almost 50,000 at the Houston Astrodome and
says singing for that many people can be intimidating.
   ``It's very scary and exciting,'' he said. ``You can't see them,
but you can feel them.''
   He believes his audiences appreciate his concert mixture of old
country songs plus his own material such as ``All My Ex's Live in
Texas,'' ``Ocean Front Property'' and his most recent No. 1 hit,
``Famous Last Words of a Fool.''
   ``I just go out and do my songs and don't tell jokes or do a lot
of talking,'' Strait said.
   Strait was born in Poteet, Texas, and grew up in Pearsall,
Texas, as the son of a junior high school math teacher who was a
part-time rancher. He went into the Army after high school where he
taught himself to play the guitar by reading some Hank Williams'
song books.
   After the Army, he earned a degree in agriculture from Southwest
Texas State University in San Marcos and sang in small bars and
clubs throughout Texas.
   He enlisted his band, The Ace in the Hole Band, by putting up a
flier on a campus bulletin board. Three of them are still with him.
   He went to work as a rancher and for two years was foreman of a
1,000-head cattle ranch. At night, it was off to sing.
   ``I'd have about half an hour to get cleaned up and get to that
night's gig,'' he said of his crowded schedule.
   Two self-financed records went unnoticed. He visited Nashville
in 1976 and 1978, hoping to sign a recording contract. He was not
successful, and instead took a full-time job designing barns and
other ranch facilities. But at the last minute, he decided to try
music for one more year.
   He was finally signed by MCA Records in Nashville in 1981.
   Strait is noted for his white cowboy hats, pressed jeans and
starched, button-down shirts that all accent his trim, athletic
appearance.
   ``During my career, I've always tried to project a clean look,''
he said. ``I feel this is important to my fans, even though I've
been criticized . . . for being too wrinkle-free.''
   He writes few of the songs he records, but does make most of the
decisions about picking album material.
   ``I think what I look for first is the melody,'' he said. ``I
look for something a little different. Then I listen to the lyrics
and if it will fit me.
   ``I don't look for any specific type of song, but if I have a
lot of ballads picked I start looking for up-tempo material for
balance.
   ``I have always gone into the studio to make it better than the
last one. Each time, I feel I have.''
   Many of his songs have Texas cities in their title, such as
``Amarillo by Morning'' and ``Does Fort Worth Ever Cross Your
Mind.''
   ``It's pure coincidence,'' he said. ``Those were strong songs.
`Amarillo by Morning' was one we'd been doing for a long time
before I recorded it. That's why we released it.''
   His current album, which has been No. 1 on the country charts,
is ``If You Ain't Lovin' (You Ain't Livin').'' He's also completed
a 60-minute concert video, ``George Strait Live.''
   But he's had to cope with tragedy. His 13-year-old daughter,
Jennifer, was killed in an automobile accident in June 1986. That
October, he dedicated his CMA award to her.
   As he prepared to set out recently on a concert tour, he said
about his success: ``I would like to think talent had a lot to do
with it. The material has been good and the timing had a lot to do
with it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 27-29</NOTE>
</DOC>
