<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. says preliminary results
indicate its shareholders backed the company over hostile suitor,
Bank of New York Co., in a heated proxy battle for control of
Irving.
   Bank of New York said it was disappointed by Monday's
announcement and was considering several options, including ending
its seven-month effort to acquire the rival banking company for
about $1.08 billion.
   Irving said that while it had no specific numbers, an early
count of proxies submitted that a slate of 16 incumbent directors
had been re-elected over Bank of New York's nominees.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. and Carl Icahn, its biggest
shareholder and main potential antagonist, are discussing how to
resolve their differences without continuing a proxy fight over
five seats on the oil giant's board.
   The company said late Monday that it and Icahn also had agreed
to support a one-week adjournment of its June 7 annual shareholder
meeting _ if each party requested it _ in order to facilitate the
discussions.
   Icahn, who is chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., has
nominated five candidates including himself for Texaco's 14-member
board. The election is scheduled for the June 7 annual meeting in
Tulsa, Okla.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-stakes brawl continues today when leaders
of the world's two biggest computer companies unite with five
others to challenge American Telephone & Telegraph Co. over
computer operating standards.
   The battle pits AT&T and its hotshot younger partner, Sun
Microsystems Inc., against the might of International Business
Machines Corp. and Digital Equipment Corp. as well as
Hewlett-Packard Co., Apollo Computer Inc. and three European
computer makers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. is cutting production of the
Eagle Premier, the flagship car of its new Jeep-Eagle division,
because of slower-than-expected sales during a difficult
image-building period.
   For two weeks in June and again for a previously scheduled
two-week vacation period in late July, Chrysler will close the
brand-new former American Motors Corp. assembly plant in Bramalea,
Ontario, which builds Premier.
   The plans were announced Monday.
</TEXT>
