<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-17 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Move Higher On Production Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices have risen in response to reports
that the world needs more oil production, not less.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, advanced 17 cents
Monday to settle at $17.66 per barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale prices
for unleaded gasoline increased 0.39 cent to 52.73 cents per
gallon, while heating oil moved up 0.51 cent to 47.98 cents per
gallon.
   Analysts said the market was bolstered by European forecasts
that OPEC would have to boost production in the months ahead to
meet demand later this year.
   Those reports said production by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries would have to increase to 19 million barrels
per day, from the current 18 million.
   ``If we don't have an increase in production, we'll have an
extremely tight and volatile market through the second half,''
observed Bob Baker of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Baker said the strong move in outer-month contracts confirmed
the market's bullish tone. Contracts for September delivery of West
Texas Intermediate, for example, traded 31 cents higher than the
June contract.
   Worries about continuing hostilities in the Persian Gulf also
helped pull prices up, the analysts said. Iraq reported its 12th
attack on an Iranian tanker in 18 days on Monday.
</TEXT>
