<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid Bjt   05-17 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Of NY Considering Dropping Irving Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. says it may drop its
seven-month hostile effort to acquire Irving Bank Corp. now that
Irving management apparently has won a heated proxy battle for
control of the company.
   Irving had no specific results Monday, but said a preliminary
count of proxies submitted at its May 6 annual meeting showed
shareholders re-elected a slate of incumbent directors over Bank of
New York's 16 nominees.
   Bank spokesman D. Emerson Phelps said the results were released
by Corporation Trust Co., an independent elections inspector based
in Wilmington, Del. A final vote count is expected at a reconvened
shareholders' meeting May 24.
   Re-election of Irving's directors would amount to a vote of
confidence in the company's defensive restructuring plan and stock
sale to state-run Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's
second-largest bank. The proposal was made as an alternative to
rival Bank of New York's $1 billion-plus hostile tender offer,
which expires Friday.
   ``This vote of confidence in Irving's board is gratifying,''
Irving said in a statement.
   Bank of New York, which owns a 4.9 percent stake in Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its stock for each of
Irving's common shares. The offer is valued at about $63 a share or
$1.08 billion.
   The company said Monday that it held about 62 percent of
Irving's common shares, including its own shares and those tendered
to it. The company said its offer was contingent upon it receiving
two-thirds of Irving's 18.5 million common shares outstanding.
   Irving was unchanged at $60.62{ a share Monday on the New York
Stock Exchange, while Bank of New York rose $1.25 to $32 a share.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said the company was
disappointed by Irving's announcement Monday and was reviewing all
of its options, including dropping its bid. Brady refused to
elaborate.
   Banca Commerciale is offering $75 a share for 9.5 million Irving
shares, about 51 percent of the outstanding common stock, for a
total of $712.5 million. In addition, it said it would pay
shareholders interest on the purchase price from May 31 until the
deal closes.
   The Banca Commerciale bid is part of a complex restructuring
plan that includes sales of assets such as Irving's 50-story Wall
Street headquarters, cost-cutting measures and a special
$10-a-share cash dividend. Irving said the offer has a blended
value of between $65.20 and $72.55 a share.
   Banking experts said they were surprised by Irving's apparent
victory in the proxy battle.
   Most analysts had given Bank of New York an edge, mainly because
it already had secured the necessary regulatory approvals from the
Federal Reserve and New York State Banking boards. Banca
Commerciale, which is controlled by the government agency Instituto
per la Recostruzione Industriale, has just begun the lengthy
regulatory review process.
   ``I guess all the right analysts were wrong once again,'' said
Stephen Berman of County Securities USA.
   James McDermott, an analyst with Keefe Bruyette & Woods, said,
``barring a change in attitude by Irving management ... it would be
unlikely that the Bank of New York would acquire Irving.
   ``I guess as a practical matter it probably takes the Bank of
New York offer out of play,'' he said.
   Irving has staunchly resisted Bank of New York's advances since
they began in late September.
   Hostile takeover efforts are very rare in the banking industry.
A Bank of New York-Irving merger would have created one of the
nation's 15 largest banks with assets of more than $40 billion.
   Banca Commerciale has assets of about $60 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
