<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AirplaneOrder Bjt   05-17 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airplane Order, Bjt,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ripple Of Boeing's $3.69 Billion Order Will Be Felt In Seattle For
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State, local and company officials weren't
popping champagne corks when Boeing Co. landed a $3.69 billion
commercial jet order, but they nevertheless were delighted about
the years of economic stability expected to stem from the sale.
   ``As the saying goes, `what's good for Boeing is, by and large,
good for Seattle,''' laughed D'Anne Mount, spokeswoman for the city
of Seattle's Department of Community Development.
   The order Boeing announced Monday represented the lion's share
of a record $5.04 billion, 130-plane purchase by International
Lease Finance Corp., which leases planes to many of the world's
airlines. Europe's Airbus Industrie consortium got the rest of the
order.
   R.R. Albrecht, executive vice president in charge of sales and
marketing for Boeing Commercial Airplanes, said the order would not
change production schedules.
   But it will add stability and keep the world's leading airplane
manufacturer working at full capacity through 1991, even if Boeing
receives no other airplane orders, Albrecht said.
   Boeing employs 90,000 people in the Seattle area, and directly
or indirectly provides for one of every four jobs in a metropolitan
area of 1.5 million people, Ms. Mount said.
   But the ripple effect of Monday's 100-plane order will be felt
by the whole state through the early 1990s, said Dick Milne, Gov.
Booth Gardner's press secretary.
   ``Any time Boeing gets an order of that magnitude it's good news
for the whole state,'' said Milne. ``It may not mean a single new
job, but it means that the ones we have are secure through 1995.''
   Monday's order easily put Boeing on a record sales pace, one
that industry analysts said may quicken more as recent safety
incidents prompt airlines to review their aging fleet and consider
orders for new planes.
   George D. Shapiro, of the investment firm Salomon Brothers in
New York, said Boeing sales may be spurred by the Aloha Airlines'
Boeing 737 that lost part of its fuselage, killing a flight
attendant, before landing safely earlier this month.
   ``One of every four airplanes today is over 19 years old. What
that says to me is the potential for future sales for Boeing,''
Shapiro said.
   ``Passengers are concerned and that's going to put pressure on
the airlines to replace older planes,'' he said.
   In the first five months of 1988, Boeing has amassed $11.6
billion in orders. The previous yearly high was last year's $19.9
billion in jet orders. The 1988 total already is the airline's
third highest total, with seven months to go.
   Boeing now has a backlog of 930 airplanes to deliver.
   The company's portion of Monday's order consisted of 72 planes
of models 737-300, 737-400 and 737-500; eight 757-200s; nine
767-300ERs; four 747-400s; and a previously unannounced order of
six planes in the 737 series and one 757-200.
   Boeing valued its share of the contract at $4.6 billion,
including the price of 24 additional planes on which International
Lease Finance has purchase options.
   The largest civilian airplane order to date was in 1986, when
British Airways ordered 16 Boeing 747s for $2.3 billion. That deal
includes options for 12 more of the jumbo jets that would bring the
value to $4.1 billion.
</TEXT>
