<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn     05-17 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco, Icahn Talking About Settling Differences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. and Carl Icahn, its biggest
shareholder and main potential antagonist, are discussing how to
resolve their differences without continuing a proxy fight over
five seats on the oil giant's board.
   The company said late Monday that it and Icahn also had agreed
to support a one-week adjournment of its June 7 annual shareholder
meeting _ if each party requested it _ in order to facilitate the
discussions.
   Icahn, who is chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., has
nominated five candidates including himself for Texaco's 14-member
board. The election is scheduled for the June 7 annual meeting in
Tulsa, Okla.
   Texaco, the nation's third-largest oil company, has filed a
federal court suit to block Icahn from soliciting proxies and
accusing him of securities law violations.
   The company claims Icahn is trying to get Texaco to buy back his
14.8 percent stake at a premium, to force Texaco's acquisition by a
third party or to acquire Texaco and liquidate its assests.
   But in a statement late Monday from White Plains, Texaco said it
and Icahn were ``engaged in discussions seeking to resolve their
differences without continuing a proxy contest.''
   The statement said Texaco and Icahn stressed that any resolution
of their differences ``will not include consideration for any
shareholder that is not equally available to all Texaco
shareholders.''
   ``Any such resolution would also require that Texaco be
satisfied that it would retain an investment grade credit rating,''
the statement said.
   ``To facilitate such discussions, Texaco and Mr. Icahn have
agreed that each of them will vote the shares and proxies under
their control to support an adjournment of the annual meeting from
June 7 to June 14 if a request is made by the other party to do
so,'' it said.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange on Monday, Texaco fell
62{ cents a share to $48.87{.
   Icahn began buying stock in Texaco while Texaco was negotiating
a settlement with rival Pennzoil Co. over a $10.3 billion judgment
awarded Pennzoil after a Texas jury found Texaco had interfered
illegally with Pennzoil's merger with Getty Oil Co.
   Texaco filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
the Bankruptcy Code last year to forestall payment of the massive
judgment. It emerged from Chapter 11 last month under a
court-approved reorganization plan that included a $3 billion
settlement with Pennzoil.
</TEXT>
