<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-InterestRates 1stLd-Writethru f0028 05-17 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Interest Rates, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0326</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   Eds: updates with other banks cutting rate, includes details of
reported rift.
   LONDON (AP) _ Britain's major commercial banks announced on
Tuesday they would cut their base lending rate by half a percentage
point to 7.5 percent, heeding a signal from the central bank which
was an apparent effort to stem the strong pound.
   The recent strength in the pound has caused a reported rift in
the government.
   National Westminster Bank PLC, Barclays Bank PLC, Lloyds Bank
PLC and Midland Bank PLC cut the benchmark borrowing rate,
effective Wednesday, after the central bank cut its money-market
dealing rate to 7.5 percent from 7~ percent.
   The pound plunged on the news, which surprised the markets.
   It was quoted at $1.8740 and 3.1550 West German marks, down from
$1.8810 and below 3.18 marks just before the central bank announced
its move at about midday.
   The latest cut brings the base lending rate to its lowest level
since April 1978, Natwest said. The base rate previously was cut on
April 8, when it was lowered half a point to 8 percent.
   Corporate borrowers can obtain loans at one percentage point
above the base lending rate.
   The Bank of England's move came when sterling actually was
weakening a bit on on unconfirmed reports that Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, an advocate of free-market policies, would back
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's desire for a more
managed exchange rate.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has expressed concern that sustained
intervention could fuel inflation, was to answer questions in the
House of Commons later in the day, and she was likely to be
questioned closely on exchange rate policy. Mrs. Thatcher
repeatedly has cited fighting inflation as her main economic aim.
   Lawson suppports curtailing the pound through interest rate cuts
and central bank intervention in the foreign exchange markets. A
strong pound could hurt British exports and corporate profits.
</TEXT>
