<NOTE>Eds: updates with market rising further on trade report</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices jumped Tuesday, buoyed by a sharp
improvement in the U.S. trade deficit and by a cut in the British
commercial banks' base lending rate.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 23.8
points, or 1.3 percent, by early afternoon.
   At midday, volume was a modest 203.5 million shares compared
with 164.5 million shares at the same time Monday.
   Share prices spurted after the Commerce Department reported that
the U.S. merchandise trade deficit narrowed to $9.7 billion in
March from $13.8 billion in February.
   The markets had been expecting a deficit of between $12 billion
and $13 billion.
   Earlier, Britain's major commercial banks, heeding a signal from
the Bank of England, announced they would cut their base lending
rate by half a percentage point to 7.5 percent.
   The banks announced the cut in the benchmark borrowing rate,
effective Wednesday, after the central bank cut its money-market
dealing rate to 7.5 percent from 7~ percent at about midday.
   The Bank of England's move, which surprised the markets,
apparently was in response to the pound's recent strength on
foreign exchange markets.
   The pound plunged against the dollar on the interest rate cut
and trade report.
</TEXT>
