<HEAD>Stocks Rise, Industrial Output Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT that imports rose in March sted
fell; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, The besieged ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's trade deficit shrank more than $4 billion in March
to $9.7 billion, the lowest monthly shortfall since March 1985, the
government reported today.
   U.S. producers sold a record amount of goods overseas in March,
slicing by 29.5 percent the February deficit of $13.83 billion.
   The Commerce Department said U.S. exports shot up 23 percent to
an all-time high of $28.97 billion while imports rose only 3.6
percent to $38.72 billion. The trade deficit is the difference
between the two.
   The besieged dollar was boosted by news of the dramatically
improved trade performance. The U.S. currency was trading at around
125.90 Japanese yen in New York shortly after the figures were
released, up from 124.95 yen earlier in London.
   The dollar also jumped to around 1.7060 West German marks from
1.6875 marks. The British pound dropped against the dollar, to
around $1.8500 from $1.8855.
   The stock market got a late-afternoon lift Monday from
speculation that the March trade-deficit numbers being released
today would show substantial improvement.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which moved in a
narrow range for much of the day, rose 17.08 points to 2,007.63 on
Monday. Broader market indicators also rose.
   Earlier Monday, the government reported U.S. industrial
production surged 0.7 percent in April, the biggest gain in six
months. The rise was more than three times as rapid as the 0.2
percent March increase and pushed overall industrial output up 6.4
percent from a year ago.
   The April increase reflected widespread production gains at
manufacturing plants, where output rose 0.7 percent. Factories
producing durable goods expected to last three or more years saw
output climb 0.9 percent while plants making non-durable goods
boosted output by 0.4 percent.
   Auto production, which had been lagging as manufacturers tried
to work down a huge backlog of unsold cars, jumped sharply for a
second straight month with passenger cars being assembled at an
annual rate of 7 million units, up from a rate of 6.6 million in
March.
   The overall production increase in April was the strongest since
a 1.1 percent rise last October. Output slowed a bit early in the
year, reflecting in large part a drop in auto production.
   Still, the slowdown was nowhere near as severe as some
economists had forecast immediately following the October stock
market crash, which had raised concerns of sharp production
cutbacks early this year that could push the nation into a
recession.
   In other economic news on Monday, interest rates on short-term
Treasury securities fell in the latest auction to the lowest level
in two weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.28 percent, down from 6.31 percent
last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 6.50 percent, down from 6.51 percent last
week.
   The rates were the lowest since May 2, when three-month bills
sold for 6.13 percent and six-month bills averaged 6.41 percent.
</TEXT>
