<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose broadly this morning after the
government reported an unexpectedly large drop in the trade deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which climbed
back over the 2,000 level late Monday on expectations that the
trade deficit would narrow, advanced 7.62 points to 2,015.25 by 10
a.m. EDT on Wall Street.
   Among broader market barometers, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.51 to 146.72. On the
American Exchange, the market value index rose 0.93 to 298.89.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 4-to-1 on the
NYSE, with 880 up, 200 down and 428 unchanged. Volume on the Big
Board totaled 24.72 million shares after the first 30 minutes.
   The Commerce Department said the trade deficit shrank to $9.7
billion in March, a drop of more than $4 billion over the previous
monthly deficit, reflecting a 23 percent surge in exports to a
record $29.97 billion. Imports rose 3.6 percent to $38.72 billion.
   The improvement was a major surprise, driving the dollar sharply
higher, inciting a rally in the dollar and easing interest rates in
the bond market, a sensitive barometer of the economy.
   On Monday, the Dow Jones industrials rose 17.08 points to
2,007.63. Advancing issues outnumbered declines on by slightly more
than 3-to-2 in nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 901
up, 559 down and 508 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 155.01 million shares, vs. 147.24
million in the previous session.
