<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Trade-Baker     05-17 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Trade-Baker,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Cites Trend Toward Smaller Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III said
Tuesday the sharp drop in the U.S. trade deficit in March confirmed
a clear trend toward closing the gap between the nation's imports
and exports.
   The Commerce Department reported in Washington that the American
trade gap shrank to $9.7 billion in March as U.S. exports surged to
record levels. The February deficit had been $13.83 billion.
   ``The U.S. trade deficit has been declining in volume terms for
quite some time,'' said Baker, who was in Paris to attend a meeting
of Western trade and finance ministers starting Wednesday. ``While
monthly figures will tend to fluctuate, it is nevertheless clear
that the U.S. trade deficit is now also declining in nominal terms
as well.''
   Baker was referring to the fact that the trade gap, measured in
nominal dollar terms, has been fed by the effects of a weakening
U.S. dollar, which has boosted the value of imported goods even as
import volumes have leveled off.
   World trade imbalances are expected to be a central focus at
Baker's two days of meetings this week with his counterparts from
the 23 other member countries of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development. Agriculture and other economic
policies also are to be discussed.
</TEXT>
