<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ForeignTrade-Markets     05-17 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Trade-Markets,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Jumps, But Stocks Mixed and Bond Prices Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged against other major currencies
today, bolstered by news of a better-than-expected U.S. trade
performance in March.
   But stock prices turned mixed following a short-lived rally
sparked by the trade figures, while bond prices dropped after an
initial strong advance.
   The Commerce Department reported today that the trade deficit
shrank more than $4 billion in March to $9.7 billion, the lowest
monthly shortfall since March 1985. U.S. producers sold a record
amount of goods overseas in March, slicing by 29.5 percent the
February deficit of $13.83 billion.
   The report triggered a sharp rise in the dollar on foreign
currency markets.
   The dollar jumped to around 125.90 Japanese yen in New York from
124.95 yen earlier in London, and rose to just under 1.71 West
German marks from 1.69 marks. The British pound dropped to around
$1.85 from $1.89.
   Stock prices rose broadly after the trade report was released
but then gave up most of the gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which climbed
back over the 2,000 level late Monday on expectations that the
trade shortfall would narrow, was down 2.49 points at 2,005.14 at
11 a.m. EDT on Wall Street.
   After an initial surge inspired by the trade news, bond prices
dropped as traders began to look more closely at the statistics.
They were disappointed that U.S. imports rose during the month, by
3.6 percent to $38.72 billion.
   In addition, the bond market viewed the 23 percent jump in
exports _ to an all-time high of $28.97 billion _ as a sign the
U.S. economy could overheat from the surge in production of export
goods and thereby intensify inflationary pressures.
   Inflation erodes the value of fixed-income investments such as
bonds and tends to depress bond prices and drive interest rates
higher.
   Bond traders saw further evidence that the economy risked
overheating when the government reported at midmorning that U.S.
industry operated at 82.7 percent of capacity in April, the highest
level in more than eight years.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond was down about {
point, or $5 for every $1,000 in face value, at around mid-morning.
Its yield rose to 9.16 percent from 9.11 percent late Monday.
</TEXT>
