<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose broadly this morning after the
government reported an unexpectedly large drop in the trade
deficit, but the rally quickly faded in another sign of post-crash
investor apathy and fear of inflation.
   ``The fact that it waned so quickly is disappointing to me,''
said Peter J. DaPuzzo, manager of retail equities at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. ``The psychology is negative and low. One number
isn't going to change that.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which rose about
15 points at the opening on the trade news, retreated by 11 a.m.
EDT to 2,005.14, down 2.49.
   Among broader market barometers, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.23 to 145.98. On the
American Exchange, the market value index was unchanged at 297.96.
   Advancing issues narrowly outnumbered declines on the NYSE, with
628 up, 576 down and 536 unchanged. Volume on the Big Board totaled
50.83 million shares after the first 90 minutes.
   The Commerce Department said the trade deficit shrank to $9.7
billion in March, a drop of more than $4 billion over the previous
monthly deficit, reflecting a 23 percent surge in exports to a
record $29.97 billion. Imports rose 3.6 percent to $38.72 billion.
   The improvement was a major surprise, initially driving the
dollar sharply higher and rallying the bond market, a sensitive
barometer of the economy. But bond prices later retreated.
   Some economists interpreted the trade figure as another sign of
a rapidly growing domestic economy, which translates into higher
inflation and rising interest rates.
   That theory was reinforced by another economic statistic
released this morning from the Federal Reserve, which showed
American industry operated at 82.7 percent of capacity in April,
the highest level in more than eight years.
   Texaco was the most-active NYSE issue, up ] to 49\ on volume
exceeding 1 million shares. The oil giant was holding talks with
its largest shareholder, takeover strategist Carl Icahn.
   Among other actively traded blue-chips, General Electric fell \
to 40\, IBM rose [ to 111} and AT&T fell ] to 26~.
   On Monday, the Dow Jones industrials rose 17.08 points to
2,007.63. Advancing issues outnumbered declines on by slightly more
than 3-to-2 in nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 901
up, 559 down and 508 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 155.01 million shares, vs. 147.24
million in the previous session.
