<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed, Turn Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed but
quickly turned higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Dry-weather fears continued to dominate the market, with some
private forecasters predicting an extended period of dryness in the
Corn Belt, said Richard Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Dry conditions could damage the winter wheat crop, which is in a
critical stage of maturity, and delay germination of corn and
soybeans, Loewy said.
   ``There's no ceiling on the soybean market if this dry weather
continues,'' he said. Soybean futures have gained more than 60
cents a bushel so far this this month.
   The Agriculture Department reported Monday corn planting was
about 88 percent complete as of Sunday. Soybean planting was about
40 percent finished.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
May unchanged at $3.19 a bushel; corn was { cent to 1{ cents higher
with May at $2.07} a bushel; oats were { cent to 1 cent lower with
May at $1.62} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 2{ cents
higher with May at $7.48{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange following Monday's USDA report
showing larger-than-expected cattle marketings during April.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .37 cent higher with June at
73.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .60 cent
higher with May at 80.85 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .55
cent higher with June at 53.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .28 cent to .63 cent higher with May at 54.40 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Monday.
</TEXT>
