<1ST_LINE>s f BC-NBCCable Adv22   05-17 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NBC Cable, Adv 22,0989</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday May 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>NBC's Cable Venture Would Bridge Television Rivalry</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Broadcasting Co.'s plan to buy a cable
television channel promises to forge the strongest link to date
between rival segments of the television business.
   With prime-time network ratings dropping and cable advertising
revenue rising, even the owner of top-rated NBC Television is
looking for ways to broaden its base.
   Analysts say NBC's new cable channel, which it plans to use as
an outlet for sports and business news, could boost the return on
its investment in information gathering and provide a hedge against
further erosion in the audience for network broadcasts.
   ``This could be a model for what happens in the industry over
the next couple of years,'' said media industry analyst Peter
Appert of the investment firm Cyrus J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell
Inc.
   The audience for the three major networks has slipped in recent
years as viewers turned to cable, independent and pay television
and videocassettes. In the just completed television season, for
instance, the prime-time audience for the three major networks fell
9 percent.
   At the same time, advertisers have spent more on cable
television. Ad spending on cable networks alone is expected to rise
20 percent this year to more than $1 billion, industry analysts say.
   Although cable audience ratings and ad spending remain only a
fraction of what the networks get, a trend is evident.
   ``The broadcast networks have reached a relative stage of
maturity ... while cable still has the largest portion of its
growth curve ahead of it,'' said Larry Gerbrandt, a senior analyst
for the media research firm Paul Kagan Associates in Carmel, Calif.
   The companies that own the three major broadcast networks have
already taken their first steps into the cable business:
   _NBC owns a 24 percent stake in the Arts & Entertainment Cable
Network, which has about 32 million subscribers. It is proposing to
buy Tempo Television, a cable network with 12 million subscribers.
   _Capital Cities-ABC Inc., the parent of the ABC Television
Network, owns 80 percent of the ESPN sports cable network, with
about 46 million subscribers; 38 percent of Arts & Entertainment
and 33 percent of Lifetime cable network, with about 38.9 million
subscribers.
   _CBS Inc., which owns the CBS Television Network, operated a
cultural cable channel in the early 1980s, but dropped the project
after a year when it failed to generate sufficient viewers and
advertising revenue.
   In each of these cases, the cable networks operated autonomously
from the broadcast operations. NBC said it plans to operate its
cable network separately from its broadcast network, but wants to
have broadcast network talent contribute to the cable sports and
business news programs that it hopes to launch by early 1989.
   While NBC executives say details of how that will be done are
being developed, Tom Rogers, an NBC vice president, said NBC wants
to stamp ``a visible imprimatur of NBC's resources'' on the cable
programming.
   The clearest indication of that, he said, would be to have
people familiar from the NBC network appearing on the cable
programs as well.
   Another feature of this cable proposal that makes it different
from the others is that NBC plans to offer cable operators a chance
to buy a piece of the sports programming service. Terms have not
been disclosed, but Rogers said NBC would retain majority interest
of the sports service.
   NBC President Robert C. Wright had spoken often of his desire to
get into cable, a segment in which he worked before taking over at
NBC in 1986.
   NBC would buy Tempo Television from TeleCommunications Inc., a
Denver-based concern that is the nation's largest cable operator.
The price was not disclosed but it has been reported to be about
$20 million.
   Tele-Communications' president, John Malone, said in announcing
the deal that the cable industry benefits from high-quality
programming and he wanted to encourage NBC's efforts to provide it.
   Some NBC affiliates have expressed concerns that NBC may pay
less attention to its network operations, but others said NBC
executives have repeatedly assured them that the broadcast network
remains the company's main interest.
   Eric Bremner, president of broadcasting for King Broadcasting
Co. in Seattle, which owns three NBC affiliates, expects NBC's move
into cable will ultimately benefit the affiliates.
   NBC could bid for the rights to sports events confident it can
sell the rights to secondary events to its cable partner. The
networks have struck such arrangements with ESPN, for instance, for
events such as tennis or golf.
   It could also test programs on the cable service and bring them
to the network if they prove popular.
   ``The truth is other business entities are moving into these
same areas. We won't be well-served if NBC sits on the sidelines
and lets these developments pass by,'' Bremner said.
   But CBS has no plans to get back into cable anytime soon. The
CBS Television Network finished third for the first time this past
season in the prime-time ratings and Laurence A. Tisch, CBS chief
executive, said he doesn't want to do anything to distract his
management's attention from regaining first place for the network.
   NBC's cable plans of airing business news in the daytime and
sports at night bears a strong resemblance to the format at
Financial News Network Inc. The FNN cable network has provided
financial news since 1981, and currently offers business news by
day, sports at night and home shopping overnight.
   David Meister, president of FNN, said he is confident his
service is lean and driven enough to compete effectively against
NBC.
   ``We take them seriously, but think we can prevail,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday May 22</NOTE>
