<1ST_LINE>u f PM-MarketReport 1stLd-Writethru   05-17 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Market Report, 1st Ld-Writethru,0769</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with administration defending report; picks
up 2nd graf pvs, I'm very disappointed.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House today defended an
administration report on the stock market crash after it drew a
cool reaction on Capitol Hill.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater called the document an
``excellent report'' and said President Reagan feels its
recommendations are sound. ``We feel the report represents the
actions that should be taken,'' Fitzwater said.
   However, the reaction in Congress ensured that lawmakers will
continue work on bills aimed at altering the exchange's operations.
   ``I'm very disappointed with the report. I think it's flatly
wrong,'' Senate Banking Committee Chairman William Proxmire,
D-Wis., said Monday, shortly after the Reagan administration's
working group issued its recommendations for preventing future
market plunges.
   The group, headed by Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, said
that a ``circuit-breaker'' should be put in place that would halt
trading on all stock, futures and options markets for an hour
should the Dow Jones Industrial Average fall by 250 points. A
second, two-hour close should occur if the Dow drops by 400 points,
the group said.
   The market has only dropped more than 250 points once in its
history: the 508-point plunge of last Oct. 19. It has swung wildly
ever since.
   The group, created in March, also recommended improvements in
the ways traders' transactions are completed and in coordination
among federal agencies that oversee the markets. In addition, they
said the group should continue functioning to help deal with
problems as they arise.
   But the group _ which also consisted of Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan, Securities and Exchange Commission
Chairman David S. Ruder, and Commodity and Futures Trading
Commission Chairwoman Wendy Gramm _ failed to suggest other moves
that have found support on Capitol Hill and elsewhere.
   They concluded that the margins _ or downpayments _ for stock,
stock index futures and options are adequate. They failed to agree
on whether steeper margins should be required in an effort to
dampen speculation, a move Ruder supported but the other three
opposed. Margins for futures trading are much lower than for stock
transactions.
   They also ignored a recommendation issued in January by a
presidential task force headed by investment banker Nicholas F.
Brady that a single agency _ preferably the Fed _ should oversee
intermarket issues. Currently, the CFTC oversees the futures
markets while the SEC and the Fed regulate the options and stock
exchanges.
   The group also urged no actions that would limit the use of
program trading, the computer-driven transactions that critics have
blamed for volatility on the stock and futures markets.
   ``It is unrealistic and perhaps counterproductive to try to undo
the changes in financial markets or market strategies brought about
by improvements in telecommunications and computer technology,''
the report said.
   ``Legislation may or may not take place,'' Treasury
Undersecretary George D. Gould, who sat in for Baker at most of the
group's meetings, said at a news conference. ``But the fact is
there were some things we could agree on and put in place which we
felt are important to the integrity of the markets and important to
investor confidence.''
   But Proxmire, who has introduced legislation that would set up a
panel consisting of officials of the Fed, SEC and CFTC to
coordinate market regulation, criticized the report.
   ``It shows a lack of sensitivity to what's keeping the
individual investor out of the market, the volatility,'' he said.
``All the evidence is that the small investor has gotten out of the
market.''
   Asked if he would continue to seek passage of his bill, he said,
``Absolutely.''
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the House
telecommunications and finance subcommittee, faulted the group for
its failure to recommend that one agency oversee the markets and
for not urging a change in margin requirements.
   ``Now it's Congress' turn to take the ball and put forward
meaningful market reforms,'' said Markey, who is drafting his own
bill.
   Rep. John Dingell, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee, of which Markey's panel is a part, said the group had
made some ``useful recommendations.'' He called for the
administration and its working group to work with Congress to deal
with the overall problem.
   Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.,
whose panel oversees the CFTC and the futures exchanges, called the
recommendations ``a start.'' He said a federal role in setting
margins needs to be studied.
</TEXT>
