<HEAD>Bond Prices Filp-flop Following Trade Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices turned lower today following a
short-lived rally sparked by better-than-expected U.S. trade
performance in March.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond was off about ] point, or
$3.75 per $1,000 face amount, by midday. Its yield, which moves
inversely to its priceology for a long time,''
said Peter A. Karos, manager of equity and over-the-counter trading
for the Minneapolis investment firm Piper, Jaffray & Hopwood Inc.
``Investors are depressed. They're frustrated. They don't know
which way to react.''
   Some economists interpreted the trade figure as another sign of
a rapidly growing domestic economy, which translates into higher
inflation and rising interest rates.
   That theory was reinforced by another economic statistic
released this morning from the Federal Reserve, which showed
American industry operated at 82.7 percent of capacity in April,
the highest level in more than eight years.
   Texaco was among the most-active NYSE issues, up | to 49{ on
volume exceeding 1.7 million shares. The oil giant was holding
talks with its largest shareholder, takeover strategist Carl Icahn.
   Among other actively traded blue-chips, General Electric fell \
to 40\, IBM rose ] to 112 and AT&T fell ] to 26~.
   Cray Research dropped 4[ to 77}. Some Wall Street analysts
reportedly cut their earnings estimates for the company.
