<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Warner-Lorimar     05-17 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Warner-Lorimar,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Companies Sign Definitive Merger Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. and
Lorimar Telepictures Corp. announced Tuesday they had signed a
definitive agreement for Warner to acquire Lorimar, producer of
``Dallas'' and other hit TV shows, in a stock swap.
   The deal, announced May 10, would have a value of about $630
million, based on Warner's midday stock price of $33.50 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   The agreement calls for holders of Lorimar's 45.3 million shares
outstanding to receive .415 shares of the New York-based
entertainment conglomerate for each share of Lorimar.
   The transaction, scheduled to close in September, requires
regulatory approval and the approval of a majority of Lorimar
shareholders.
   In addition to the stock trade, Warner agreed to assume
Lorimar's debt of about $550 million.
   After announcement of the tentative merger agreement, Lorimar
disclosed that investor Marvin Davis, who previously had expressed
an interest in the company, was considering a $15-per-share bid for
Lorimar. His earlier bid, dismissed by many analysts as not being
serious, was $17 a share.
   Lorimar chairman Merv Adelson has made it clear he prefers the
stock swap.
   The merger would add a leading producer of network and
syndicated television shows to Warner's already strong movie and
music businesses.
   In addition to ``Dallas,'' Lorimar produces such network series
as ``Knots Landing'' and ``Alf,'' and has a strong lineup of shows
that are syndicated, or sold directly to individual television
stations.
   The merger agreement allows Lorimar to back out if Warner's
stock price doesn't average an amount that would bring Lorimar
shareholders at least $15 a share. If Lorimar cancels, it must pay
Warner $10 million, and if Lorimar is acquired by a third party,
Warner has the right to but 18.5 percent of the company at $15 a
share.
</TEXT>
