<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Thatcher     05-17 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Thatcher,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Thatcher Says She and Lawson Agree on Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, apparently
healing a rift with her top Treasury official, said Tuesday she
advocated the use of interest rate cuts and central bank
intervention under the right cicrumstances to manage the pound.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who reportedly has disagreed strongly with
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson over how to respond to the
strong rise in the pound since March, made the comment in
Parliament just hours after Britain's central bank sent a signal to
the commercial banks to cut interest rates.
   The prime minister, who has championed free market policies,
maintained during a session of Parliament that she and Lawon, who
believes in managing exchange rates, were in agreement.
   When asked whether there was ``complete and total unanimity''
between her and Lawson, she replied, ``Yes.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, who repeatedly has cited fighting inflation as
her economic aim, had expressed concern that sustained intervention
could fuel inflation.
   Lawson favors curtailing the pound through rate cuts and
intervention in the foreign exchange markets. A strong pound could
hurt British exports and corporate profits.
   ``We will use the available levers, both interest rates and
intervention, as seems right in the circumstances,'' Mrs. Thatcher
said.
   She said it would be a ``great mistake for any speculator to
think that sterling is one-way bet.''
   Britain's major commercial banks announced earlier Tuesday they
would cut their base lending rate by half a percentage point to 7.5
percent, heeding a signal from the central bank, which cut its own
money-market dealing rate.
   The pound fell sharply after the cuts were announced.
   In London, it cost $1.8540 to buy one pound after the rate cut
and the release of better-than-expected U.S. trade figures, cheaper
than $1.8855 in the morning and cheaper than $1.8915 late Monday.
   The prime minister said in Parliament the rate cut would not
have an inflationary impact on the economy because the rising pound
had tightened monetary conditions, meaning there is less money in
the monetary system.
   Dealers said Mrs. Thatcher's comments didn't have much of an
impact on the pound, which already had risen on the rate cut.
   ``The base rate cuts earlier today already told us that Thatcher
aligned herself with Lawson in trying to cap sterling's rise,'' one
dealer said.
   Mrs. Thatcher and Lawson sat together during the session.
</TEXT>
