<DOCNO> AP880517-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Venezuela-Debt     05-17 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Venezuela-Debt,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuelan Businessmen Call For Renegotiating Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business leaders have called on the
government to renegotiate the repayment terms on the nation's $32
billion foreign debt to ease a liquidity crisis caused by low oil
prices.
   The proposal for ``more just treatment'' by the nation's
creditors was discussed in a Cabinet meeting Tuesday.
   Hugo Fonseca Viso, president of the National Federation of
Chambers of Commerce and Industry , the nation's leading business
organization, met with President Jaime Lusinchi Monday to discuss
the proposal.
   ``It is necessary for the nation to propose that the weight on
Venezuela's economy and finances of the foreign debt be
reconsidered,'' Fonseca said following his meeting with Lusinchi,
the newspaper El Nacional reported Tuesday.
   ``We believe that (international banks) have not been just with
Venezuela, taking into consideration how it has fulfilled its
obligations. We ask not for privileged treatment but at least for
the same treatment given to other Latin American nations,'' Fonseca
said.
   Venezuela is the only major Latin debtor that has been paying
principal as well as interest on its foreign debt. Since 1982 it
has reduced its debt by around $3 billion without receiving new
loans to pay the old debts.
   In the first quarter Venezuela ran a balance of payments deficit
of $850 million as low oil prices yielded income too low to pay for
both $1.7 billion of imports and foreign debt service of $1.3
billion.
   The balance of payments deficit for all of 1987 was $1.2 billion.
   The government's response has been to squeeze imports further
and restrict liquidity in an effort to contain inflation.
   About $20 billion of public sector debt is included in a 14-year
refinancing agreement that requires the nation to pay $400 million
in principal this year. Private firms owe around $7 billion abroad.
</TEXT>
