<DOCNO> AP880517-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RubberStrike 5thLdWritethru   05-17 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rubber Strike, 5th Ld Writethru,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URW, Goodyear Reach Tentative Settlement; Firestone Strike
Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, `Union President ...,' to add detail about how
raise will be implemented.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. and the United
Rubber Workers reached a tentative three-year contract settlement
today, averting a strike scheduled for noon, a union leader said.
   Union President Milan Stone said the agreement calls for an
immediate 25-cent hourly raise, which will be deducted from any
cost-of-living increases the workers would have received in July,
October and January 1989. The pact also allows for a wage reopener
in March 1990, depending on Goodyear's financial situation.
   Stone said Goodyear agreed to keep a provision that all union
locals are required to approve mid-contract wage concessions sought
at any single local.
   ``We're hopeful that it will be ratified,'' said Stone. ``I'm
sure they were looking for more. I'm convinced that there isn't any
more and they should ratify this.
   ``It's a good agreement, and we always would like to have more
on a contract settlement obviously, but I think we have to
recognize the problems that (financier Sir James) Goldsmith has put
upon this company and ultimately puts upon the workers in a company
that's had to undergo such a corporate takeover attempt.''
   Goodyear fended off a takeover attempt by Goldsmith in the fall
1986 by purchasing the 11 percent share he had acquired in the
Akron-based company.
   Goodyear spokesman Fred Haymond said the company would have no
immediate comment but would release a statement later today.
   On average, rubber workers make about $14 an hour.
   The union postponed its strike deadline until a week from today
while another ratification vote is taken.
   The URW represents 15,000 workers at 11 Goodyear locals covered
by a master contract.
   The two sides began meeting this morning at a downtown hotel.
   Meantime, about 4,700 Firestone workers began a third day on
strike today, with no talks planned.
   The union last went on strike against Goodyear in 1976 in an
industrywide walkout that lasted four months.
   ``Both parties traditionally have been willing to work up to the
last minute to avoid strikes that create hardships for employees
and affect the company's competitive position,'' Goodyear officials
said. ``We'll do our best to resolve our differences.''
   Six of the Goodyear locals had approved a tentative agreement,
although it was rejected nationally. URW President Milan Stone
supported the tentative agreement, designed to set an industry
pattern.
   The agreement contained no pay increase, instead concentrating
on job security improvements, cost-of-living allowances, and
pension and health insurance benefits.
   In Lincoln, Neb., union leaders decided that Goodyear workers
will stay on the job, according to Lee Domeier, URW Local 286 vice
president. The local's bargaining committee and executive board
unanimously approved the decision to keep working, he said.
   In Akron, members of URW Local 2, which previously approved the
contract by a 3-1 ratio, voted 722-691 in favor of striking today.
Bill Breslin, the local's president, had urged the local's members
to keep working despite the strike deadline. After the vote,
Breslin said he would resign his post.
   Besides Akron and Lincoln, the Goodyear locals facing the strike
deadline were in Marysville and St. Marys, Ohio; New Bedford,
Mass.; Sun Prairie, Wis.; Topeka, Kan.; Union City, Tenn.;
Danville, Va.; Madisonville, Ky., and Gadsden, Ala.
   The union struck Firestone on Sunday because the company failed
to accept the Goodyear pattern, Stone said. Firestone officials,
however, said their latest offer was equal to the pattern.
   The URW represents workers at Firestone plants in Noblesville,
Ind.; Des Moines, Iowa; Decatur, Ill.; Russellville, Ark., and
Oklahoma City as well as maintenance workers and technicians in
Akron.
   One of the nation's Big Three tire makers, Uniroyal Goodrich
Tire Co., came to terms in mid-April in a contract taking into
account the company's special needs because of the recent Goodrich
and Uniroyal merger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
