<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Copper-7Trial 2ndLd-Writethru   05-17 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copper-7 Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IUD Trial: Lawyers Begin Arguing Contraceptive Device Civil Suit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with opening arguments. Picks
up in 13th graf, `Searle won ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturer of the Copper-7
intrauterine device displayed ``corporate irresponsibility'' by
withholding knowledge about the device's potential for causing
infertility, an attorney for a woman suing G.D. Searle & Co. said
today.
   ``It's a story of a company closing the door on the God-given
right of a woman to bear children,'' attorney Michael Ciresi told a
federal jury in his 1{-hour opening statement.
   Ciresi, one of a team of attorneys from the Minneapolis law firm
of Robins, Zelle, Larson & Kaplan, said he will introduce evidence
showing that Searle changed the string on its Copper-7 IUD,
stretching it, which weakened it horizontally.
   After the Copper-7 was approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration in 1974, Searle sold between 300,000 and 400,000 of
the IUDs in the United States annually. It was taken off the U.S.
market in 1986.
   Searle has denied that its IUD caused any injury. Opening
arguments by attorney for Searle were to follow Ciresi's remarks
today.
   A jury of five women and three men, including two undesignated
alternates, was chosen Monday to hear the civil suit brought by
Esther R. Kociemba, 29, and her husband, William, of Elk River.
   The Kociembas are asking for an unspecified amount in
compensatory and punitive damages for injuries Mrs. Kociemba
allegedly suffered as a result of using a Copper-7 IUD for slightly
less than 1{ years in 1977 and 1978.
   According to the suit, Mrs. Kociemba has experienced
infertility, illnesses and ``great pain, suffering and mental
anguish'' that have continued since she had the IUD removed in
November 1978.
   During Ciresi's opening remarks today, Mrs. Kociemba often wiped
tears from her eyes.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Renner is presiding over the trial,
which is expected to last up to two months.
   Robins Zelle, which is representing more than 30 women in
separate Copper-7 lawsuits, also represented plaintiffs in earlier
litigation against Dalkon Shield maker A.H. Robins Co., settling
198 cases for a total of $38 million.
   Another Robins Zelle attorney, Roger P. Brosnahan, has said that
evidence includes testimony of Searle employees and former
employees and internal company documents. He said this is expected
to set a foundation for lawsuits to be tried later.
   ``In our judgment, it will be the first real trial involving the
Copper-7,'' Brosnahan said.
   Searle won 14 of the earlier cases, while one of the cases it
lost is on appeal.
   Kay Bruno, spokeswoman for Skokie, Ill.-based Searle, said the
company doesn't view the Kociemba suit as much different from
earlier ones. Many of the documents have been used in previous
court cases, she said.
   More than 800 lawsuits involving the IUD have been filed against
Searle, Bruno said. Of those, many have been settled out of court.
She said about 500 lawsuits are pending.
   Searle withdrew the Copper-7 and its other IUD, the TATUM-T,
from the U.S. market and stopped manufacturing the two items in
January 1986, citing the cost of litigation and the unavailability
of liability insurance. The birth control devices remain available
in foreign countries.
   Since removal of the Copper-7 from the U.S. market, only one
IUD, the Progestasert, has been available in this country, although
it is not widely marketed. But a new copper IUD has been approved
for sale and soon will be available.
   According to a 1982 survey, the most recent available, 7.3
percent of women using contraceptives chose the IUD. The study by
the National Center for Health Statistics showed the majority of
women using an IUD for birth control were over 25 years old and had
at least one child.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
