<1ST_LINE>d f BC-China-Trade     05-17 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Trade,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Joint Venture Aims To Facilitate Sino-U.S. Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sino-American joint venture established in
Beijing Tuesday aims to encourage trade between China and the
United States by serving as consultants and partners in joint
venture projects.
   ``The objectives of ACB International Ltd. are basically to
serve as a catalyst to promote trade between the United States and
China ... in both directions,'' ACB Chairman A. Robert Abboud said
at a news conference Tuesday.
   The American partners in the project are First City Bank of
Texas and the Hong Kong-based Alexander Y. Chow & Co. Ltd. Abboud
is chairman of First City Bank of Texas.
   The Chinese side of the 50-50 joint venture is made up of the
Bank of China and two affiliates of the Ministry of Foreign
Economic Relations and Trade, China United Trading Corp. Ltd. and
China Export Bases Development Corp.
   As consultants, the company will match U.S. businesses that want
to do business in China with Chinese partners. It also is prepared
to invest in joint ventures and enter the project as a partner, he
said.
   Company officials said ACB offers U.S. businesses support on the
Chinese side from the foreign trade ministry and experience from
its staff and from advisers who have been successful in business
ventures in China.
   ``Other companies say they can do the same thing, but they don't
have the experience or the resources,'' said ACB President
Alexander Y. Chow.
</TEXT>
