<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks1stLd-Writethru     05-17 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks 1st Ld-Writethru,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares More Up 12.6 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices finished higher on London's Stock Exchange
Tuesday, helped by a narrower-than-expected U.S. trade deficit for
March.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed up
12.6 points, or 0.7 percent, at 1,789.2.
   Volume was a healthy 425.9 million shares, compared with
Monday's 311.7 million shares.
   The London equity market was boosted at midday by news that the
Bank of England had signaled a cut in the commercial banks' base
lending rate to 7.5 percent from 8 percent.
   But several traders said the market failed to capitalize on the
rate cut as players quickly turned their attention to the U.S.
trade report.
   The Commerce Department reported the March merchandise trade
deficit narrowed to $9.7 billion from February's $13.8 billion. The
markets had expected a deficit of $12 billion to $13 billion.
   The 100-stock index was up nearly 24 points immediately
afterward, but then proceeded to drift lower throughout the rest of
the day.
   A muted opening on Wall Street dampened enthusiasm in London,
dealers said.
   The Commerce Department said that a large increase in exports
reflected gains in manufactured goods shipments, especially
machinery, computers and aircraft as well as increased shipments of
gold.
   A dealer said that ``exports were a little disturbing due to the
rise in gold and aircraft which can't be sustained over many
months.''
   But London market players also were heartened by the apparent
end to a rift between Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson over exchange rate policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
