<DOCNO> AP880517-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     05-17 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0458</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A big drop in the trade deficit failed to
generate much excitement today in the stock market, where a rally
quickly faded in another sign of post-crash investor apathy and
growing fear of inflation.
   ``The fact that it waned so quickly is disappointing to me,''
said Peter J. DaPuzzo, manager of retail equities at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. ``The psychology is negative and low. One number
isn't going to change that.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which rose about
15 points at the opening on the trade news, retreated by 2 p.m. EDT
to 2,012.27, up 4.64. Among broader market barometers, the New York
Stock Exchange composite index of all listed issues fell 0.17 to
146.04. On the American Exchange, the market value index fell 0.54
to 297.42.
   Advancing and declining issues were nearly even on the NYSE,
with 714 up, 651 down and 538 unchanged. With two hours of trading
left, volume on the Big Board totaled 80.08 million shares,
considered extremely slow.
   The Commerce Department said the merchandise trade deficit
shrank to $9.7 billion in March, a drop of more than $4 billion
over the previous monthly deficit, reflecting a 23 percent surge in
exports to a record $29.97 billion. Imports rose 3.6 percent to
$38.72 billion.
   The improvement was a major surprise, driving the dollar sharply
higher and initially boosting the bond market, a sensitive economic
barometer. But bond prices later retreated and the stock market
followed, a reflection of the pessimism that has pervaded the
securities industry since the Oct. 19 crash.
   ``I haven't seen this negative psychology for a long time,''
said Peter A. Karos, manager of equity and over-the-counter trading
for the Minneapolis investment firm Piper, Jaffray & Hopwood Inc.
``Investors are depressed. They're frustrated. They don't know
which way to react.''
   Some economists interpreted the trade figure as another sign of
a rapidly growing domestic economy, which translates into higher
inflation and rising interest rates.
   That theory was reinforced by another economic statistic
released this morning from the Federal Reserve, which showed
American industry operated at 82.7 percent of capacity in April,
the highest level in more than eight years.
   Texaco was among the most-active NYSE issues, up } to 49| on
volume exceeding 2 million shares. The oil giant was holding talks
with its largest shareholder, takeover strategist Carl Icahn.
   Among other actively traded blue-chips, IBM rose } to 112], AT&T
fell ] to 26~ and Bethlehem Steel rose \ to 19[.
   Cray Research dropped 3~ to 78. Some Wall Street analysts
reportedly cut their earnings estimates for the company.
</TEXT>
