<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Retail, 1st Ld-Writethru,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>J.C. Penney, Dayton Hudson, Carter Hawley Hale Earnings Reflect
Sluggish Consumer Spending</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: rewrites throughout with Dayton Hudson earnings.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc., Dayton Hudson Corp. and Carter Hawley Hale
Stores Inc. reported Tuesday that sluggish consumer has taken a
toll on their earnings.
   Penney's income was up 141 percent from the first three months
of 1987, when the company took a $140 million charge for the cost
of relocating its headquarters to Dallas from New York.
   Penney reported it earned $131 million, or 96 cents per share,
in the quarter ended April 30, compared with $54 million, or 36
cents per share, in the first quarter of last year.
   However, Penney's income dipped slightly when compared with its
year-earlier earnings before the $140 million charge. Penney earned
$136 million in the first three months of 1987, which translates
into a 4 percent decline for the latest quarter.
   The retailer's sales declined to $3.17 billion from $3.22
billion.
   Penney and other retailers suffered from sluggish consumer
spending that has continued from 1987 into the first part of this
year. Apparel retailers, including Penney, have been especially
hard-hit.
   Penney also cited other factors for its lackluster performance,
including higher expenses for selling and administrative operations
and developmental costs from the company's video home shopping
venture and interactive television program.
   Meanwhile, Dayton Hudson said its first-quarter earnings tumbled
more than 19 percent, to $30.7 million, or 36 cents per share, from
$38.1 million, or 39 cents per share, in the first quarter of 1987.
   Sales for the quarter ended April 30 totaled $2.54 billion, up
from $2.15 billion a year ago.
   Dayton Hudson chairman Kenneth Macke said soft sales put
pressure on margins, the profits on merchandise, and contributed to
the decline. A drop in profits at the company's Mervyn's division,
which sells mostly apparel, also was a factor in the Dayton Hudson
decline.
   Carter Hawley Hale was another casualty of the sluggish retail
environment. The Los Angeles-based department store company
reported it suffered a $4.4 million loss in its third quarter.
   The retailer said the loss in the three months ended April 30
compared with earnings of $7.7 million, or 1 cent per share, in the
same period a year ago.
   Sales fel to $546.1 million from $563.7 million in the latest
quarter.
   The 1987 figures are restated to account for the sale of
Neiman-Marcus Group Inc. and other stores.
   For the first nine months of the fiscal year, Carter Hawley Hale
earned $16.6 million, or 67 cents per share, compared with a loss
of $262,000 in the year-earlier period.
   Sales for the nine-month period totaled $2.02 billion, compared
with $2.27 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
