<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Hutton-Broker     05-17 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hutton-Broker,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broker Pleads Innocent In Hutton Money Laundering Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former E.F. Hutton & Co. Inc. broker
pleaded innocent Tuesday to charges stemming from a
money-laundering scheme at the brokerage firm's Providence office.
   Brian Lareau, of Jamestown, R.I., appeared in U.S. District
Court on charges of false representation of a Social Security
account number and money laundering, Justice Department attorney
John Voorhees said.
   On Monday, Hutton was fined $1.01 million after pleading guilty
to two money-laundering charges and one count of conspiracy in
connection with the scheme.
   Federal authorities charged that Lareau and another former
broker, since deceased, helped clients hide about $1.5 million in
cash from the Internal Revenue Service.
   Lareau, 46, worked for the Hutton branch from 1980 to 1985. He
is accused of laundering $183,950 from August 1982 to October 1984.
The federal felony charges carry maximum penalties of six years in
prison and $6,000 in fines.
   According to documents filed in federal court, Lareau allegedly
created two accounts for fictitious people and used them to conceal
customers' money from the Securities and Exchange Commission and
the IRS.
   Cash transactions greater than $10,000, which must be reported
to the IRS, were divided into smaller amounts and deposited into
the false accounts, according to the documents.
   Lareau was released on his personal recognizance. He is
scheduled to appear before U.S. District Judge Francis J. Boyle on
May 25, Voorhees said.
   Authorities said another former Hutton broker, Stephen S. Fusco,
who died two years ago of cancer, was also involved in the scheme.
Fusco was accused of helping members of organized crime turn
illegally earned money into legitimate income.
   Jeremiah T. O'Sullivan, head of the Justice Department's New
England Organized Crime Strike Force said Lareau had no ties to
organized crime, and that he and Fusco _ who was known to associate
with organized crime figures _ apparently were not partners in
their alleged illegal activities.
   Hutton was acquired last year by Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc.,
and the company is now known as Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
