<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed narrowly mixed
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid conflicting forecasts
for Midwestern crop weather.
   Soybean futures, which led grain futures in a powerful rally
Monday, were held down by soybean oil, which experienced weak cash
markets and slack demand, analysts said.
   But weather-watchers dominated the trade, said Richard Loewy,
senior grain and oilseed analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities in
New York.
   ``We had a two-sided affair because rain was being forecast by
some meteorologists'' in contrast to earlier predictions for hot,
dry weather until late in the week, Loewy said. ``But the bulk of
them are still looking hot and dry.''
   The Agriculture Department reported most winter wheat in good to
fair condition as of Sunday but cited a lack of moisture heading
into the crop's critical heading stage.
   The USDA said late Monday corn planting was 88 percent complete
as of Sunday, while soybean planting was about 40 percent finished.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.18 a bushel; corn was } cent to
2 cents higher with May at $2.08 a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 2
cents lower with May at $1.61 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower
to 2{ cents higher with May at $7.51 a bushel.
</TEXT>
