<HEAD>BP America Reports 13.6 Percent Increase In Operating Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increased earnings in the refining and
marketing segment, along with gains in chemicals and minerals
helped boost BP America's first-quarter operating income 13.6
percent over the same period last year, the company announced
Tuesday.
   BP America, the U.S. affiliate of British Petroleum Co. PLC of
London, said it had first quarter operating profits of $576
million, compared to a $507 operating profit during the first
quarter of 1987.
   Net income for the quarter totaled $199 million. BP America
spokesman John Andes said the company did not have a comparable
figure for the first quarter of last year because BP America did
not exist at that time.
   BP America was formed last June through the merger of BP North
America and Standard Oil Co.
   The operating income from petroleum exploration and production
dropped 22.7 percent, to $326 million from $422 million, while
operating income from refining and marketing increased 30.7
percent, to $119 million from $91 million, Ross said.
   ``In these areas, stronger margins in downstream petroleum
operations and a 5 percent increase in oil and gas production
helped offset the effect of lower oil prices,'' said James H. Ross,
president and chief executive officer of BP America.
   Operating income in the chemicals segment jumped 230 percent,
from $10 million to $33 million. In the minerals segment, operating
income increased 240 percent, from $22 million to $121 million.
