<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Phillips-Award 1stLd-Writethru   05-17 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phillips-Award, 1st Ld-Writethru,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Chief Honored by Communications Group</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to add dropped words to make it `Wall Street
Journal.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warren H. Phillips, chairman and chief executive
officer of Dow Jones & Co. Inc., received the annual leadership
award of the Center for Communication on Tuesday, marking his
contributions to journalism over a career that has spanned four
decades.
   The award, presented at a luncheon at the Plaza Hotel,
recognizes individuals who exemplify courage, conscience and
leadership in the communications field.
   Past recipients are Katharine Graham, publisher of the
Washington Post; Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, chairman and publisher of
the New York Times; William Paley, founder of CBS; and Allen H.
Neuharth, chairman of Gannett Co.
   The center noted in its award to Phillips that he played a
pivotal role in shaping the Wall Street Journal, which has
undergone major design and content changes in recent years. Under
Phillips, the Journal has won seven Pulitzer prizes, added a second
section and will soon add a third.
   The company also has added Asian and European daily editions and
10 new printing plants to regionalize its U.S. editions, the center
noted.
   Dow Jones meanwhile has used the Journal to become ``a leading
global supplier of computerized business and financial news and
information,'' the center's citation said.
   Phillips began his career at the Journal as a copyreader after
graduation from Queens College in 1947. During his 41 years at Dow
Jones, he has held a variety of posts in New York, Chicago and
Europe.
   ``He is to be commended for his part in making the global
village much more of a reality,'' said Thornton F. Bradshaw,
chairman of the center and former chief of RCA Corp.
   The Center for Communication is a non-profit organization
created in 1980 to help universities keep abreast of changes in the
media business. It holds workshops and seminars for students and
professors around the country free of charge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
