<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0177</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks sagged today despite a sharply lower
trade deficit, and brokers called the reaction another bad sign of
an anemic post-crash market that shows little inclination to
recover soon.
   ``People just don't seem to care,'' said Robert Meyer, director
of research at the New York investment firm Fahnestock & Co.
   ``It's a bit similar to what you go through when you lose a
member of your family,'' he said. ``There's a mourning period
before you go out and face life again. I don't know how long this
mourning period is going to take.''
   After a short-lived rally on the trade news, selling pressure
intensified as investors grew concerned that the surprisingly small
trade deficit of $9.7 billion for March was an abberation.
   Others worried that a record surge in exports provided further
evidence of a rapidly growing economy and higher inflation, which
caused a big selloff in the bond market that spilled over into
stocks.
</TEXT>
