<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Spain-Banks     05-17 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Banks,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Banks To Merge To Form Largest Spanish Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banco Central and Banco Espanol de Credito
announced a friendly merger Tuesday aimed at creating Spain's
largest bank by 1992, when the European Economic Community is to
remove all barriers to free capital movements within the 12-nation
bloc.
   The combined bank would have assets of more than 5.5 trillion
pesetas, or $50 billion. Banco Central is currently the nation's
second largest bank, and Banco Espanol de Credito is No.3.
   The government of Socialist Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez has
been urging mergers among the so-called Big Seven Spanish private
banks to prepare them for stiff competition expected from larger
European institutions when the EEC capital movement barriers come
down in 1992.
   The merger will give the new entity control over 25 percent of
the Spanish banking sector, or total deposits amounting to more
than 2 billion pesetas, according to the latest statistics from the
Spanish Banking Commission.
   The merger is the second among the Big Seven banks. The first,
between Banco de Bilbao and Banco de Vizcaya, was announced in
January.
   The unified Banco Bilbao-Vizcaya is currently Spain's largest
bank, with 4.3 trillion pesetas in total assets.
   The sole obstacle to the latest merger appeared to have been
cleared away with the announcement by the owners of Banco Central's
principal shareholder, the Cartera Central holding company, that
they would not oppose the action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
