<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   05-17 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0584</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices sagged Tuesday despite news of a
sharply lower trade deficit, and brokers called the reaction
another disturbing sign that the market's post-crash anemia won't
disappear soon.
   An early rally over the trade report collapsed, reflecting some
concern that it signaled a surging economy, hence higher inflation
and rising interest rates. Selling intensified late in the day,
though volume remained light.
   ``People just don't seem to care,'' said Robert Meyer, director
of research at the New York investment firm Fahnestock & Co.
   ``It's a bit similar to what you go through when you lose a
member of your family,'' he said. ``There's a mourning period
before you go out and face life again. I don't know how long this
mourning period is going to take.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 21.22 points to
1,986.41, erasing its 17.08-point gain Monday. Broader market
indices also fell substantially.
   The $9.7 billion March trade deficit reported by the Commerce
Department, down from a February imbalance of $13.8 billion, was so
unexpectedly low that some investors assumed the April number
released next month would be much higher. Brokers said customers
sold stock based on that assumption.
   Some said the explosive growth in exports contained in the March
number added to growing fear in the financial markets that higher
inflation is unavoidable. That fear caused a bond market selloff
that spilled into stocks.
   Many Wall Street professionals agreed that the reaction typified
the investor cynicism and anemia that has afflicted the market
since the October crash. They also recalled that when the high
February trade deficit was announced last month, it contributed to
a 101-point selloff in the Dow average.
   ``Psychology seems to be taking a bigger portion of investor
decision-making now,'' said Peter J. DaPuzzo, manager of retail
equities at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``The psychology is so
apathetic, people look for any excuse not to buy. You're not going
to get them off the fence if they don't want to.''
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading, declines
outnumbered advances by nearly 2-to-1, with 985 down, 521 up and
473 unchanged. Volume on the Big Board totaled 133.85 million
shares, vs. 155.01 million Monday.
   Among the most-active NYSE issues, Texaco rose { to 49] on
reports of talks between the oil giant and takeover strategist Carl
Icahn, its largest shareholder, aimed at averting a fight for
director seats.
   Losing blue-chips included IBM, down 1{ to 110[; Philip Morris,
down 1} to 82{; Alcoa, down ~ to 44{; and AT&T, down } to 26{.
   Cray Research fell 5[ to 76} on word that some Wall Street
analysts had lowerered their earnings projections and investment
rating for the company.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 156.45 million shares.
   The NYSE index fell 1.56 to 144.65.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 3.85 to 296.71,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index fell 3.32 to 255.39.
   The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, the market value of
5,000 NYSE, American and OTC issues, fell by $24.59 billion.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1.39
to 296.57. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 372.27, down 1.08.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
