<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-ReynoldsCuts     05-17 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reynolds Cuts,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reynolds & Reynolds Cuts 10 Percent Of Computer Division Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reynolds & Reynolds Co. says it will cut
about 10 percent of its computer division work force and refocus
the marketing of its main computer products.
   The company announced the elimination of 250 jobs on Monday,
spokesman Paul Guthrie said. The computer division employs about
2,200 nationwide.
   Another 60 jobs will depart with the leveraged buyout of
Reynolds' money-losing catalog sales operation for computer
accessories and forms, Guthrie said. He declined to disclose the
terms of the buyout.
   The Dayton-based computer and business forms maker, a Fortune
500 company, said it wanted to concentrate on marketing and service
of its industry-leading automotive dealer computer systems.
   Orders for its auto dealer systems slowed late last year, but
rebounded in January, Reynolds President David R. Holmes said.
   The cuts announced Monday stem not only from poor financial
performance, but also from the maturing of several development
projects, the company indicated.
   Much of the computer work at auto dealers now is done on
free-standing computers, not on-line or in batch processing, Holmes
said.
   ``We've invested a large amount of resources in that product
change and we've developed that product now, so we're able to do
some realigning in that regard,'' he said.
   An interactive video customer-assistance system for Chrysler
Corp. and a management system for large dealerships are among other
projects nearing completion, Holmes said.
   Computer division earnings also were hurt by losses in the
company's tax-processing business, the result of expenses to meet
new changes in the tax code.
   Computer systems division sales for the six months ended March
31 were up 13.7 percent to $119 million from the same period in
1987, but profits dropped 13 percent to $40 million.
   Net income for the entire company increased about 30 percent to
$12 million, largely because of reduced taxes and a tax accounting
change, on sales of $289.9 million.
   In its last fiscal year, Reynolds & Reynolds posted a profit of
$21.2 million on sales of $562.7 million.
</TEXT>
