<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1806EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PCClones Bjt   05-17 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PC Clones, Bjt,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Demands Retroactive License Fees From PC Clone Makers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. is putting
the squeeze on makers of personal computer clones that have not
paid for patent licenses.
   Some companies could be forced to pay substantial retroactive
royalty payments on their IBM-compatible personal computers.
   ``To be consistent, we are not going to enter into new patent
licensing agreements with companies that refuse to recognize their
liability to IBM for the use of IBM patents in their existing
products,'' spokesman Michael Starks said Tuesday.
   IBM said it will require companies to settle up their past
royalties before they are allowed to license the patents required
to make computers compatible with its new Personal System-2 line.
   IBM could also pursue companies for retroactive payments even if
they do not want to produce Personal System-2 clones, Starks said.
   ``It appears that they are being a little overbearing,'' said
Michael Shane, chairman of Leading Edge Hardware Products Inc. of
Canton, Mass., which imports Korean-made personal computers.
   ``This latest move certainly can't help the American consumer,''
Shane said. He predicted it would increase prices and increase
confusion.
   Shane said Leading Edge has no interest in building a Personal
System-2 compatible computer. In that case it would probably not be
one of IBM's first targets for royalty payments.
   Unaffected would be companies such as Tandy Corp. and Compaq
Computer Corp. that have cross-licensing agreements with IBM. Under
those agreements, the companies allow each other to use certain of
their patents without charge.
   Starks said the company would accept payments totaling 1 percent
of sales on computers sold through this past April 1, assuming the
companies settle up with IBM by the end of 1988. After that, the
fee could rise.
   IBM stated recently that license fees related to its new PS-2
line could range as high as 5 percent of sales. IBM says that
license fees on clones of its old line of PCs could also range as
high as 5 percent of sales for computers sold after this past April
1.
   IBM's failure to demand license fees until now could give
competitors some legal grounds to argue that it is too late for IBM
to start now. Starks declined to comment on that possibility, but
said, ``Depending on the circumstances, we may be in a position to
ask for payments.''
</TEXT>
