<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 1808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-17 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0834</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Surge; Market Remains Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices rose sharply Tuesday, indicating strong
demand despite indications that supplies will be rising soon.
   On other markets, precious metals futures were mixed; orange
juice futures plunged; grains and soybeans, livestock and meat, and
energy futures all were mixed; and stock-index futures fell.
   After reaching an all-time high of $1.46 as pound at the end of
1987, copper futures have traded in a range from about 85 cents a
pound to about $1.05 a pound.
   Copper for May delivery settled 2.7 cents higher Tuesday at
$1.03 a pound on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   ``Every time the market dips, the trade buys it,'' said John
O'Connell, metals analyst in New York with Refco Inc.
   Copper's steep increase last year stemmed from a shortage.
Although the market remains fairly tight, an increase in readily
available supplies now allows for more price elasticity, analysts
said.
   Richard Levine, vice president of precious metals and foreign
exchange at Elders Futures Inc. in New York, said he expected
copper prices to continue hovering within the current range.
   ``Copper above $1 is just too high given the amount of
production capability and below 85 cents is too low to warrant the
production to come out,'' he said. ``But anywhere in the 90 cents
to $1 range is safe territory. It's a reasonable price to pay if
you're a buyer and a reasonable price to receive if you're a
seller.''
   Also on the Commodity Exchange, gold futures finished slightly
higher while silver futures posted modest losses.
   Gold initially fell in reaction to a government report showing a
dramatic narrowing of the U.S. trade deficit, then recovered on
ideas that an increase in manufacturing activity would ultimately
prove inflationary, Levine said.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 60 cents higher with June at $456.40 a
troy ounce; silver was 4 cents to 4.5 cents lower with May at $6.54
a troy ounce.
   Frozen concentrated orange juice futures plunged on the New York
Cotton Exchange on selling inspired by the upcoming expiration of
the May contract, analysts said.
   Reports of an 8 percent wholesale price cut by Florida processor
Winter Garden Citrus Products fueled further selling, said Sandra
Kaul, an analyst in New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Orange juice futures have climbed from about $1.30 a pound last
fall to around $1.70 a pound. But a recent decline in wholesale
sales of orange juice indicates falling demand due to high prices,
analysts said.
   Orange juice settled 2 cents to 6.5 cents lower with May at
$1.6715 a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid conflicting forecasts for Midwestern crop weather.
   Soybean futures, which led a powerful rally Monday, were
restrained by soybean oil, which faced weak cash markets and slack
demand, analysts said.
   But weather-watchers dominated the trade, said Richard Loewy,
senior grain and oilseed analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York.
   ``We had a two-sided affair because rain was being forecast by
some meteorologists'' in contrast to earlier predictions for hot,
dry weather until late in the week, Loewy said. ``But the bulk of
them are still looking hot and dry.''
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 4 cents lower with May at $3.18 a
bushel; corn was } cent to 2 cents higher with May at $2.08 a
bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2} cents lower with May at $1.61 a
bushel; soybeans were { cent lower to 4 cents higher with May at
$7.50{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in a surprisingly weak performance following a
bullish cattle-on-feed report Monday from the USDA.
   The report showed larger-than-expected marketings in April, and
analysts had expected a strong rally in the cattle futures market.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent lower to .13 cent higher with June
at 73.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .85
cent higher with May at 80.85 cents a pound; hogs were .52 cent
lower to .17 cent higher with June at 53.10 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .32 cent lower to .23 cent higher with May at
53.80 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices were mixed in lackluster trading on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents lower to 9
cents higher with June at $17.75 a barrel; heating oil was .20 cent
lower to .17 cent higher with June at 47.78 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .09 cent lower to .06 cent higher with June
at 52.74 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures fell on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 4.45 points lower at 255.10.
</TEXT>
