<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PurchasingManagers     05-17 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Purchasing Managers,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Purchasing Managers Expect Continued Economic Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's purchasing managers have grown more
optimistic in the past six months that the economy will continue to
grow this year, but they also expect higher inflation, a new report
said Tuesday.
   In their latest semiannual forecast, 73 percent of the
purchasing managers predicted the economy would be better in 1988
than it was in 1987, compared with 57 percent in their December
report.
   They said price increases averaged about 3.8 percent since the
end of 1987 and forecast a sharp net average increase of about 5.8
percent for the year, the report said. In the December report, the
purchasing managers forecast a price rise of 3.6 percent for all of
1988.
   The latest survey was released by the National Association of
Purchasing Management, an education and research organization with
nearly 30,000 members.
   ``The number of purchasing managers expressing optimism about
the next 12 months is the highest since May 1984,'' said Robert J.
Bretz, chairman of the group's business survey committee and
director of materials management at Pitney Bowes Inc.
   ``This reflects their expectations for increased capital
expenditures and sharply higher exports despite
higher-than-expected prices,'' he said.
   Some 53 percent of members forecast their capital expenditures
would be higher in 1988 than last year, compared with 42 percent
making the same forecast in December.
   Eighty-two percent of the purchasers also predicted higher
prices over the last half of 1988, up from 76 percent in December,
while 90 percent said they were paying higher prices at the end of
April than at year-end 1987.
   Among exporting companies, 53 percent said their export business
rose moderately over the first half of this year, while 12 percent
reported substantial increases.
   Fifty-two percent forecast moderate increases in exports for the
second half of this year, the same as in December.
</TEXT>
