<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EmbezzlementScheme     05-17 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Embezzlement Scheme,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Says It Thwarts $70 Million Computerized Embezzlement Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First National Bank of Chicago announced Tuesday
it had thwarted an employee's attempt to embezzle $70 million
through a computerized wire transfer scheme.
   The nation's 10th-largest bank would release no details, and
stated only that the FBI had taken charge of the investigation and
that neither the bank nor its customers expected to suffer any
losses.
   ``It was really the efficiency and the soundness of our controls
that allowed us to thwart this embezzlement,'' said bank spokesman
Tony Zehnder.
   He said the employee had been identified, but could not say
whether the person had been charged.
   FBI spokesman Jim Kuntzelman refused comment on the case.
   A bank source, who refused to be identified, told the Associated
Press the embezzlement was attempted through wire transfers, or the
computerized movement of money from one account to another.
   The source said three customer accounts, including the
investment firm Merrill Lynch & Co., were affected, but the
embezzlement attempt was discovered before any of the accounts
actually lost money.
   Merrill Lynch reportedly discovered a discrepancy in its account
Monday and alerted the bank to the problem. No one answered the
phone at Merrill Lynch's New York headquarters Tuesday night.
   Zehnder said he could not say whether it was the largest
attempted embezzlement ever at the bank.
   First National Bank, a unit of First Chicago Corp., ranked as
the nation's 10th-largest bank with $27.2 billion in deposits at
year-end 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
