<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 2311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     05-17 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Upholds Friday Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. District Court judge on Tuesday ruled
that Allegheny International Inc. could hold its annual meeting
Friday as originally planned, renewing a proxy fight for control of
the troubled company.
   Allegheny said the judge stayed a preliminary injunction issued
Monday by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court, which barred the meeting from
taking place for 90 days.
   As a result of the new ruling the meeting is scheduled for
Friday, pending a further hearing on the case in U.S. District
Court.
   Tuesday's federal court ruling will be in place until the judge
conducts another hearing Wednesday on the bankruptcy court's
preliminary injunction.
   The ruling means the proxy contest between a group of dissident
shareholders and the company is again under way.
   The struggle to wrest control of Allegheny International _ which
is reorganizing under Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy protection from
creditors _ is led by Spear Leeds & Kellogg, a New York investment
banker that has invested about $30 million in the company's
preferred stock.
   The bankruptcy court had issued its injunction at the request of
Allegheny's unsecured creditors committee. The court ruled the
Pittsburgh-based company could call its annual meeting after it had
submitted its Chapter 11 reorganization plan to shareholders and
creditors, but before they had voted on it.
   Speer Leeds asked U.S. District Judge Alan Bloch to overturn the
bankruptcy court ruling and reinstate the proxy fight.
   Pittsburgh-based Allegheny International manufactures consumer
products, including Sunbeam and Oster appliances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
